  <graph edgedefault="directed">
    <node id="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2, a respiratory virus that caused the COVID-19 pandemic and is a major target of nanostructured viral vaccines and mRNA vaccines mentioned in the text. | Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2, the airborne viral pathogen that causes COVID-19 and is the primary target of molecular diagnostic platforms discussed in the text. | Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2, the airborne pathogen causing COVID-19, targeted for rapid primary screening using the optical hyperspectral imaging spectroscopy platform. | SARS-CoV-2 is a coronavirus responsible for COVID-19; in this context it is discussed as the viral pathogen whose nucleocapsid (N) protein folds viral RNA and is considered a potential target for antiviral strategies and, by extension, biosensing approaches. | A respiratory coronavirus responsible for COVID-19, frequently used as a target in CRISPR-Cas12a-based visual detection assays for rapid, point-of-care diagnosis and surveillance. | The coronavirus responsible for COVID-19, referenced in the context of detection via machine learning-driven SERS fingerprinting of disintegrated viral components in environmental dust. | An airborne coronavirus responsible for COVID-19, used here as a target pathogen for CRISPR-based diagnostic assays including colorimetric detection with CRISPR/dCas9. | The respiratory coronavirus responsible for COVID-19, serving as the nucleic acid target for Cas12a-based DETECTR and dual CRISPR-Cas12a assays using respiratory swab RNA extracts.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_4,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_5,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_44,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_51,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_70,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_74,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_75,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_81,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_82,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_84,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_85,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_86,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_87,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_211,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_215,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_216,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_247,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_265,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_281,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_295,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_303,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_313,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_320,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_329,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_334,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_335,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_343,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_345,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_346,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_347,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_348,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_349,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_350,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_351,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_354,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_520,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_522,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_540,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_544,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_548,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_549</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1,4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99,8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">SARS-COV-2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFLUENZA VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">INFLUENZA VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Influenza viruses, airborne respiratory pathogens for which nanostructured viral vaccines based on virus-like particles (VLPs) have been widely deployed. | Influenza A virus (IV) is an airborne respiratory pathogen whose infectivity is attenuated and rendered inactive by porous gold nanoparticles (PoGNPs) via gold–disulfide bond formation with the viral hemagglutinin (HA) protein, preventing membrane fusion and viral entry. | A respiratory virus mentioned as one of the infections clinically diagnosed using the Roche cobas Liat PCR System within lab-in-a-tube platforms. | A respiratory virus targeted for detection and subtyping by the integrated microfluidic system developed by Shen et al. | An airborne respiratory virus detected by the cobas Liat point-of-care system. | A group of influenza A viruses that primarily infect humans, birds, pigs, horses, and marine mammals; in humans they are transmitted mainly via respiratory droplets and can cause illnesses ranging from mild respiratory symptoms to severe pneumonia and ARDS. | Influenza A virus subtype H5 detected and genotypically differentiated by qPCR assays. | Influenza A virus subtype H7 detected and genotypically differentiated by qPCR assays. | A broad group of influenza A and B viruses that infect humans and animals and are transmitted mainly via respiratory droplets and aerosols; the main focus of diagnostic technique reviews and assay development.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_4,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_335</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">INFLUENZA A VIRUS,INFLUENZA VIRUS,INFLUENZA B VIRUS,H5 INFLUENZA A VIRUS,H7 INFLUENZA A VIRUS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POLYETHYLENEIMINE-ASSISTED COPPER IN SITU GROWTH-AMPLIFIED LATERAL FLOW SENSOR">
      <data key="d0">POLYETHYLENEIMINE-ASSISTED COPPER IN SITU GROWTH-AMPLIFIED LATERAL FLOW SENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A lateral flow biosensor platform that uses polyethyleneimine-assisted copper in situ growth to amplify signal for sensitive, reliable, and field-deployable infectious disease diagnostics.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ESCHERICHIA COLI">
      <data key="d0">ESCHERICHIA COLI</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Bacterial pathogen (E. coli) that is among the infectious agents detected by the copper in situ growth-amplified lateral flow sensor. | Escherichia coli bacteria that can be present in aerosolized form and serve as a non-viral airborne pathogen target for the capacitive biosensor platform.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_5,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_83</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">ESCHERICHIA COLI</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COPPER IN SITU GROWTH SIGNAL AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">COPPER IN SITU GROWTH SIGNAL AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A signal amplification method based on in situ growth of copper on the test line of a lateral flow assay to enhance detection sensitivity and precision.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SENSITIVITY, PRECISION, AND REPEATABILITY EVALUATION OF THE COPPER IN SITU GROWTH-AMPLIFIED LATERAL FLOW SENSOR">
      <data key="d0">SENSITIVITY, PRECISION, AND REPEATABILITY EVALUATION OF THE COPPER IN SITU GROWTH-AMPLIFIED LATERAL FLOW SENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Validation of the copper in situ growth-amplified lateral flow sensor demonstrating excellent sensitivity, precision, and repeatability for infectious disease diagnostics.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VISUAL/READOUT SIGNAL FROM COPPER DEPOSITION ON LATERAL FLOW STRIP">
      <data key="d0">VISUAL/READOUT SIGNAL FROM COPPER DEPOSITION ON LATERAL FLOW STRIP</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The enhanced visual or instrumental readout signal generated by copper deposition on the lateral flow strip, enabling sensitive detection of pathogens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CARBON-BASED NANOPARTICLES BIOSENSING PLATFORMS">
      <data key="d0">CARBON-BASED NANOPARTICLES BIOSENSING PLATFORMS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">General class of biosensor and detection platforms that use carbon-based nanoparticles, leveraging their optical and electromagnetic properties and surface functionalization with biomolecules for high sensitivity and selectivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CARBON NANOTUBE-BASED CONTINUOUS DOPAMINE AND ASCORBIC ACID SENSOR">
      <data key="d0">CARBON NANOTUBE-BASED CONTINUOUS DOPAMINE AND ASCORBIC ACID SENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A continuous sensing system using carbon nanotubes (CNTs) to monitor dopamine (DA) release and ascorbic acid levels, designed for in vivo neurochemical monitoring.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CARBON NANOTUBE-BASED GLUCOSE AND LACTATE BRAIN SENSOR">
      <data key="d0">CARBON NANOTUBE-BASED GLUCOSE AND LACTATE BRAIN SENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An advanced CNT-based biosensor platform capable, with further improvements, of simultaneously detecting baseline levels of glucose and lactate in the rat brain.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOPAMINE">
      <data key="d0">DOPAMINE</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Neurotransmitter whose concentration changes are continuously monitored as an electrochemical/optical signal by CNT-based biosensors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ASCORBIC ACID">
      <data key="d0">ASCORBIC ACID</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Analyte whose concentration is monitored by CNT-based biosensors, providing a measurable signal for in vivo chemical monitoring.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GLUCOSE (BASELINE BRAIN LEVELS)">
      <data key="d0">GLUCOSE (BASELINE BRAIN LEVELS)</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Metabolite whose baseline concentration in the rat brain is a target signal for advanced CNT-based biosensors. | Metabolite whose baseline concentration in the rat brain is simultaneously detected by improved CNT-based biosensors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
      <data key="d6">LACTATE (BASELINE BRAIN LEVELS)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus (SARS-CoV), a respiratory coronavirus responsible for the 2003 SARS outbreak, primarily transmitted via respiratory droplets and aerosols. | The coronavirus responsible for the 2003 SARS outbreak, an airborne respiratory pathogen whose viral RNA can be detected by qRT-PCR assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1</data>
      <data key="d6">SARS-COV</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H1N1 INFLUENZA">
      <data key="d0">H1N1 INFLUENZA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">H1N1 influenza A virus, the strain that caused the 2009 influenza pandemic and is transmitted mainly through airborne respiratory particles and droplets. | A highly pathogenic avian influenza A subtype H5N1 virus discussed in the context of a global panzootic in mammals and experimental infection of dairy cows, relevant as a zoonotic airborne pathogen.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">H5N1 INFLUENZA</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MERS-COV">
      <data key="d0">MERS-COV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Middle East Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus (MERS-CoV), a zoonotic betacoronavirus identified in 2012 that can spread via respiratory routes and cause severe lower respiratory tract disease. | Middle East Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus, referenced in the context of an updated roadmap for research and product development with a focus on diagnostics.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_44,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_87,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_351</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1</data>
      <data key="d6">MERS-COV</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EBOLA VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">EBOLA VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Ebola virus, a filovirus that causes severe hemorrhagic fever; although primarily transmitted through direct contact with infected bodily fluids, it is included here as a major high-consequence viral pathogen of the 2013–2016 West Africa outbreak. | Ebola virus is the target pathogen detected by a pipette tip-based nucleic acid test that integrates extraction, LAMP amplification, and signal readout.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1</data>
      <data key="d6">EBOLA VIRUS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ZIKA VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">ZIKA VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Zika virus, a flavivirus mainly transmitted by Aedes mosquitoes and associated with congenital abnormalities and neurological complications, listed among major viral outbreaks of the 21st century. | Zika virus is the target pathogen for an instrument-free microfluidic platform within the LionX lab-on-a-chip systems. | A flavivirus mentioned as being detected in Aedes aegypti mosquitoes using near-infrared diffuse reflectance spectroscopy, demonstrating noninvasive optical detection in vectors. | An enveloped RNA flavivirus; in this context it is a viral target whose SERS spectral signature in environmental dust is discriminated by the SERS–machine learning biosensing approach alongside SARS-CoV-2 and influenza A. | Zika virus, a mosquito-borne flavivirus; in this context it is the viral target detected by the paper-based diagnostic platform.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_44,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_342</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1,4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">ZIKA VIRUS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFLUENZA">
      <data key="d0">INFLUENZA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Influenza refers to respiratory influenza viruses; here it is mentioned as a viral pathogen for which LNP-delivered mRNA vaccines could be developed. | A group of respiratory viruses transmitted via aerosols and droplets; influenza viral RNAs are commonly detected using qRT-PCR assays for early clinical diagnosis. | A seasonal respiratory virus cited as one of the most likely co-circulating pathogens in the study’s geographical location, against which the technique’s specificity for SARS-CoV-2 discrimination is relevant.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_51,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_265,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_294</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1,4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
      <data key="d6">INFLUENZA</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY SYNCYTIAL VIRUS (RSV)">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY SYNCYTIAL VIRUS (RSV)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) is a respiratory pathogen; the text discusses an LNP-encapsulated mRNA vaccine expressing RSV F protein variants that provided protection against RSV infection in animal models. | An airborne respiratory pathogen included as a target in the cobas Liat Influenza A/B &amp; RSV point-of-care assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1</data>
      <data key="d6">RESPIRATORY SYNCYTIAL VIRUS (RSV)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EBV">
      <data key="d0">EBV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">EBV (Epstein–Barr virus) is a human virus that can be transmitted via respiratory secretions; it is cited as a candidate pathogen for future LNP–mRNA vaccine development.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMAN INFLUENZA A/PUERTO RICO/8/1934 (H1N1) VIRUS (PR8)">
      <data key="d0">HUMAN INFLUENZA A/PUERTO RICO/8/1934 (H1N1) VIRUS (PR8)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A laboratory strain of human influenza A (H1N1), referred to as PR8; described as a negatively charged influenza A virus that can electrostatically associate with positively charged polymers such as chitosan or trimethylchitosan, relevant to nanoparticle-based nasal immunization formulations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFLUENZA A VIRUS (IAV)">
      <data key="d0">INFLUENZA A VIRUS (IAV)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A class of influenza A viruses; PR8 is identified as a subclass of IAV with a negative surface charge that can bind to cationic polymers, illustrating electrostatic interactions between viral particles and polymeric carriers. | An airborne respiratory influenza A virus serving as the target analyte for the SERS imaging-based aptasensor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
      <data key="d6">INFLUENZA VIRUS A</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEPATITIS C VIRUS (HCV)">
      <data key="d0">HEPATITIS C VIRUS (HCV)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Hepatitis C virus; in this passage, its envelope glycoprotein glycans form cyclic diesters with boronic acid-modified lipid nanocapsules (BA-LNCs), a mechanism proposed to prevent viral entry into host cells. | Hepatitis B virus, a human viral pathogen whose DNA is the target of the CRISPR/Cas13a-assisted rapid and portable HBV DNA detection assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
      <data key="d6">HEPATITIS B VIRUS (HBV)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PAC-MAN">
      <data key="d0">PAC-MAN</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas13d-based antiviral platform in which Cas13d and designed crRNAs co-localize in the cytosol to target conserved regions of viral RNA, thereby inhibiting replication of influenza A H1N1, SARS-CoV-2 variants, and multiple human coronaviruses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS13D">
      <data key="d0">CAS13D</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">An RNA-targeting CRISPR-Cas13 effector enzyme variant used in the PAC-MAN platform to bind and cleave viral RNA when guided by specific crRNAs, resulting in inhibition of viral replication.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR RNAS (CRRNA) TARGETING CONSERVED VIRAL REGIONS">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR RNAS (CRRNA) TARGETING CONSERVED VIRAL REGIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">Designed and screened crRNAs used in the PAC-MAN platform that target conserved regions of viral genomes, guiding Cas13d to complementary viral RNA sequences for cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H1N1 IAV">
      <data key="d0">H1N1 IAV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A subtype of influenza A virus (H1N1) whose load in respiratory epithelial cells was effectively reduced by the Cas13d-based PAC-MAN system through targeted viral RNA cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENDEMIC HUMAN CORONAVIRUS STRAINS">
      <data key="d0">ENDEMIC HUMAN CORONAVIRUS STRAINS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Multiple endemic human coronavirus strains that were inhibited in vitro by the PAC-MAN CRISPR-Cas13d platform, with viral titers reduced by more than 99% through targeted RNA degradation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS13">
      <data key="d0">CAS13</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">Cas13 is an RNA-targeting CRISPR effector nuclease used in a multiplexed, portable nucleic acid detection platform to recognize viral RNA and trigger collateral cleavage of reporter molecules. | An RNA-targeting CRISPR effector nuclease used in massively multiplexed nucleic acid detection platforms to sense RNA targets and produce a reporter signal. | An RNA-targeting CRISPR effector nuclease used in several SARS-CoV-2 and multiplexed nucleic acid detection platforms. | A CRISPR effector nuclease that, upon binding its target RNA, performs non-specific collateral cleavage of nearby single-stranded RNA, which is used in CRISPR diagnostics for sensitive nucleic acid detection. | A family of RNA-targeting CRISPR effector nucleases; orthogonal Cas13 variants are used in SHERLOCKv2 to enable multiplexed detection of multiple nucleic acid targets in a single reaction.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_81,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_86,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_347,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_348,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_350,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_522,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_555</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">CAS13</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS12A">
      <data key="d0">CAS12A</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">Cas12a is a DNA-targeting CRISPR effector nuclease used in a multiplexed nucleic acid detection platform to recognize viral DNA (or DNA copies of viral genomes) and activate collateral cleavage of reporter substrates. | A CRISPR-associated nuclease whose target binding unleashes indiscriminate single-stranded DNase activity, enabling signal amplification in CRISPR-based diagnostic assays, as characterized by Chen et al. (2018). | A CRISPR-associated nuclease with guide RNA–dependent trans-cleavage activity on single-stranded DNA, serving as the core effector enzyme in the single-molecule SARS-CoV-2 gene detection assay. | A CRISPR-Cas effector nuclease variant used in diagnostic assays for DNA targeting and collateral (trans) cleavage, enabling signal amplification in CRISPR-based detection platforms. | A CRISPR effector nuclease variant employed in CRISPR–Cas12a-based assays for avian influenza detection, providing target-activated collateral cleavage activity that underlies the assay signal generation. | A specific Cas12 effector (also known as Cpf1) with both cis- and trans-cleavage activity on ssDNA, forming the basis of several portable CRISPR-Cas12 biosensing platforms, including HOLMES.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_81,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_85,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_347,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_348,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_555</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1,8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">CAS12A</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CSM6">
      <data key="d0">CSM6</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">Csm6 is a CRISPR-associated RNase used in combination with Cas13 and Cas12a in a nucleic acid detection platform to amplify the detection signal by degrading reporter molecules once activated. | A CRISPR-associated RNase used as a signal amplification component in multiplexed nucleic acid detection platforms. | A CRISPR type III effector nuclease that can be activated downstream of Cas13 in SHERLOCKv2 to provide an additional amplification layer via its nuclease activity on reporter substrates, thereby increasing assay sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_81,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_555</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">CSM6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-CAS-BASED NANOPROBES FOR VIRAL GENE DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-CAS-BASED NANOPROBES FOR VIRAL GENE DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A nanotechnology-enabled biosensing platform that integrates CRISPR-Cas effectors (such as Cas13, Cas12a, and Csm6) with nanoprobes to detect viral genes in a multiplexed and portable nucleic acid assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_81</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COLLOIDAL GOLD IMMUNOCHROMATOGRAPHIC ASSAY FOR SARS-COV-2 ANTIBODIES">
      <data key="d0">COLLOIDAL GOLD IMMUNOCHROMATOGRAPHIC ASSAY FOR SARS-COV-2 ANTIBODIES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A rapid lateral-flow style biosensor that uses colloidal gold nanoparticles in an antigen–antibody–nanoparticle sandwich format to detect total antibodies against SARS-CoV-2 after COVID-19 vaccination. | A rapid colloidal gold-based immunochromatographic (lateral flow) assay designed to detect total antibodies against SARS-CoV-2 following vaccination.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_81</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
      <data key="d6">COLLOIDAL GOLD IMMUNOCHROMATOGRAPHIC ASSAY FOR SARS-COV-2 TOTAL ANTIBODIES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AUNP-BASED ANTIGEN–ANTIBODY–NANOPARTICLE SANDWICH IMMUNOSENSOR">
      <data key="d0">AUNP-BASED ANTIGEN–ANTIBODY–NANOPARTICLE SANDWICH IMMUNOSENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An immunosensor configuration employing gold nanoparticles (AuNPs) arranged in an antigen–antibody–nanoparticle sandwich to capture SARS-CoV-2-specific antibodies and generate a visible colorimetric signal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_81</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-CAS13/CAS12A/CSM6 MULTIPLEXED NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-CAS13/CAS12A/CSM6 MULTIPLEXED NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A multiplexed and portable nucleic acid detection platform that integrates Cas13, Cas12a, and Csm6 for nucleic acid sensing, as reported by Gootenberg et al. (Science 360, 439–444, 2018).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_82</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-CAS13A/C2C2 NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-CAS13A/C2C2 NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-based nucleic acid detection assay using Cas13a (C2c2) for RNA sensing, as described by Gootenberg et al. (Science 356, 438–442, 2017). | A CRISPR-based nucleic acid detection platform using the Cas13a (C2c2) RNase, which leverages target-activated collateral cleavage of labeled reporter RNAs to detect specific nucleic acid sequences, as described in Science 2017 (356, 438–442). | A CRISPR-based nucleic acid detection assay that uses the Cas13a (formerly C2c2) effector and its collateral RNase activity to generate detectable reporter signals. | A CRISPR-Cas13a (C2c2)-based nucleic acid detection platform that uses RNA-guided RNase activity and collateral cleavage for sensitive detection of nucleic acids.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_82</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">CRISPR-CAS13A/C2C2 NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION ASSAY</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GOLD NANOPARTICLE (AUNP) COLORIMETRIC SARS-COV-2 ASSAY">
