      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A paper-based immunoassay platform utilizing carbon quantum dots on filter or nitrocellulose paper to detect HIV antigen, demonstrating a higher detection range and shorter detection time compared to traditional ELISA methods.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_84</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MICROBEAD QD-ELISA">
      <data key="d0">MICROBEAD QD-ELISA</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A microbead-based ELISA that uses biocatalytic formation of quantum dots for ultra-high sensitivity optical and electrochemical detection, achieving orders-of-magnitude improvement in sensitivity over previous ELISA studies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_84,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_344</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELISA">
      <data key="d0">ELISA</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Conventional enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay used as a reference immunoassay method for comparison of detection range, sensitivity, and handling time with quantum dot-based and nanoparticle-based platforms. | Conventional enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) format, referenced as a standard immunoassay platform whose sensitivity is challenged by low viral concentrations (&lt;10³ copies mL⁻¹) in water and aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_84</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">ELISA</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAPID LATERAL FLOW IMMUNOASSAY (LFIA)">
      <data key="d0">RAPID LATERAL FLOW IMMUNOASSAY (LFIA)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A standard rapid lateral flow immunoassay format used as a benchmark for manual handling complexity and assay time when comparing newer nanoparticle fluorescence-based lateral flow platforms. | Immunochromatographic strip-based assay platform used for rapid, point-of-care detection of antibodies or antigens, offering higher accessibility than centralized ELISA and HI assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_84</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">LATERAL FLOW IMMUNOASSAY (LFA)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR/CAS-BASED NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION METHODS">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR/CAS-BASED NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION METHODS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A class of nucleic acid detection assays that use CRISPR-associated (Cas) enzymes as the core sensing mechanism, providing scalable, rapid, often visually readable, highly sensitive and specific viral detection compared with traditional RT-qPCR and immunoassays. | A CRISPR-mediated nucleic acid detection module that is integrated with lateral flow strips for visual readout in SARS-CoV-2 assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_85</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1</data>
      <data key="d6">CRISPR-BASED NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS13A">
      <data key="d0">CAS13A</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">An RNA-targeting CRISPR-associated nuclease with collateral RNase activity, used in CRISPR diagnostic assays for sensitive detection of viral RNA, including SARS-CoV-2. | Cas13a is a CRISPR-associated RNase effector that exclusively targets RNA and can be incorporated into biosensor platforms for RNA detection, regulation, and imaging. | An RNA-targeting CRISPR effector nuclease with collateral RNase activity upon target binding, used as the detection enzyme in platforms such as SHERLOCK and other Cas13a-based cartridges. | A CRISPR effector nuclease (Cas13a) with single-stranded RNA (ssRNA) trans-cleavage activity, used as the core detection enzyme in Cas13a-based nucleic acid detection platforms for sequence-specific nucleic acid sensing.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_85,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_346,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_349,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_522,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_523</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">CAS13A</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DETECTR">
      <data key="d0">DETECTR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">DNA Endonuclease-Targeted CRISPR Trans Reporter (DETECTR) is a CRISPR–Cas12-based diagnostic platform for rapid detection of viral nucleic acids, here applied to SARS-CoV-2, enabling significantly shorter assay times than conventional molecular tests. | A CRISPR-Cas12-based diagnostic platform for nucleic acid detection that can reach sub-10-copy-per-microliter limits of detection in under an hour. | A CRISPR–Cas12a-based DNA-endonuclease-targeted CRISPR trans reporter platform that uses a one-pot nucleic acid-sensing method for sensitive DNA detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_86,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_215,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_521</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">DETECTR</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SHERLOCK">
      <data key="d0">SHERLOCK</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Specific High-sensitivity Enzymatic Reporter Unlocking (SHERLOCK) is a CRISPR–Cas13-based diagnostic platform for RNA virus detection that, in clinical testing for SARS-CoV-2, achieved 100% specificity and 96% sensitivity with performance comparable to RT-PCR. | A CRISPR-based nucleic acid detection platform that couples isothermal amplification with Cas13-family nucleases and collateral reporter cleavage to sensitively detect specific RNA or DNA targets. | A CRISPR-Cas13-based nucleic acid detection system achieving sub-10-copy-per-microliter sensitivity within 45–60 minutes, comparable to RT-qPCR. | Specific High-Sensitivity Enzymatic Reporter UnLOCKing (SHERLOCK), a Cas13a-based nucleic acid detection platform capable of attomolar-level detection of viral and bacterial nucleic acids, compatible with single-pot reactions and freeze-dried, paper-based formats.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_86,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_215,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_216,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_521,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_522</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">SHERLOCK</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS12">
      <data key="d0">CAS12</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">Cas12 is a CRISPR-associated DNA endonuclease used in platforms such as DETECTR to recognize target nucleic acids and generate collateral cleavage of reporter molecules for signal readout. | A CRISPR-Cas effector nuclease used in CRISPR–Cas12-based detection platforms to recognize target nucleic acid sequences and generate a detectable reporter signal via collateral cleavage. | A CRISPR-associated nuclease whose activity can be tuned and that is widely used in CRISPR-based diagnostic assays for nucleic acid detection; mentioned in the context of tunable control of Cas12 activity for fast one-pot diagnostics, though the specific assay is not fully described in the provided text fragment. | Cas12 is a CRISPR-associated nuclease family used as the core detection enzyme in CRISPR–Cas12-based assays, enabling sequence-specific recognition and collateral cleavage of nucleic acids for diagnostic readout. | A CRISPR effector nuclease that, upon binding its target nucleic acid, performs non-specific collateral cleavage of nearby single-stranded DNA, which is exploited in CRISPR diagnostics for signal amplification. | A family of CRISPR effector nucleases with cis and trans ssDNA cleavage activity, incorporated into SHERLOCKv2 and other platforms to detect DNA targets and generate collateral cleavage of ssDNA reporters.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_86,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_349,f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_350</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">CAS12</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RT-PCR">
      <data key="d0">RT-PCR</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) is a nucleic acid amplification method used as the clinical reference standard for SARS-CoV-2 RNA detection, providing the benchmark against which SHERLOCK’s sensitivity is compared. | Reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction, a nucleic-acid amplification method used in many commercial kits for SARS-CoV-2 testing by converting viral RNA to cDNA and amplifying specific genomic regions. | Reverse transcription quantitative PCR used as a nucleic acid amplification and detection method targeting influenza A HA and NA genes for subtype-specific diagnostics. | Reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction used to convert SARS-CoV-2 RNA into cDNA prior to Argonaute (PfAgo)-based cleavage and detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_86</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b</data>
      <data key="d6">RT-PCR,RT-QPCR</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SHERLOCK CLINICAL VALIDATION ON 154 COVID-19 SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">SHERLOCK CLINICAL VALIDATION ON 154 COVID-19 SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A clinical validation study of the Cas13-based SHERLOCK assay using 154 clinical samples from COVID-19 patients, reporting 100% specificity and 96% sensitivity for SARS-CoV-2 RNA detection relative to standard methods.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_86</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="100% SPECIFICITY (SHERLOCK SARS-COV-2 ASSAY)">
      <data key="d0">100% SPECIFICITY (SHERLOCK SARS-COV-2 ASSAY)</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The specificity profile of the SHERLOCK Cas13-based SARS-CoV-2 assay in a 154-sample clinical validation, indicating no false positives and thus 100% specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_86</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SENSITIVITY COMPARABLE TO RT-PCR (SHERLOCK SARS-COV-2 ASSAY)">
      <data key="d0">SENSITIVITY COMPARABLE TO RT-PCR (SHERLOCK SARS-COV-2 ASSAY)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A performance characterization indicating that the sensitivity of the SHERLOCK Cas13-based SARS-CoV-2 assay is comparable to that of RT-PCR in clinical testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_86</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NAKED-EYE VIRUS DETECTION APPROACH">
      <data key="d0">NAKED-EYE VIRUS DETECTION APPROACH</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A biosensing approach in which viral nucleic acid detection is configured to yield a visually readable, naked-eye signal, typically via colorimetric or other visible outputs, by integrating nanotechnology with genetic detection techniques.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_86</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NANOTECHNOLOGY–GENETIC DETECTION MICROPLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">NANOTECHNOLOGY–GENETIC DETECTION MICROPLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A nucleic acid detection microplatform that combines nanotechnology with genetic detection methods to enable one-step, visually interpretable detection of nucleic acid targets, supporting naked-eye virus detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_86</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="N-GENE TARGETING NPS COLORIMETRIC SENSOR">
      <data key="d0">N-GENE TARGETING NPS COLORIMETRIC SENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A plasmonic nanoparticle-based colorimetric biosensor in which antisense oligonucleotide (ASO)-capped plasmonic nanoparticles targeting the SARS-CoV-2 N gene enable selective, naked-eye detection of the virus in a simple, instrumentation-free assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_87</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELECTROCHEMICAL IMMUNOSENSOR WITH AUNP-MODIFIED ARRAY ELECTRODES">
      <data key="d0">ELECTROCHEMICAL IMMUNOSENSOR WITH AUNP-MODIFIED ARRAY ELECTRODES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A low-cost electrochemical immunosensor that uses a dielectric electrophoresis array of gold nanoparticle-modified carbon electrodes to detect MERS-CoV by monitoring electrochemical changes such as current or impedance upon antigen binding.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_87</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="N-GENE TARGETING ANTISENSE OLIGONUCLEOTIDE CAPPED PLASMONIC NANOPARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">N-GENE TARGETING ANTISENSE OLIGONUCLEOTIDE CAPPED PLASMONIC NANOPARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Plasmonic nanoparticles capped with antisense oligonucleotides complementary to the SARS-CoV-2 N gene; hybridization with target viral sequences induces plasmonic changes that function as the primary transducing element for the colorimetric signal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_87</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COLORIMETRIC READOUT (NAKED-EYE DETECTION)">
      <data key="d0">COLORIMETRIC READOUT (NAKED-EYE DETECTION)</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A colorimetric readout in which aggregation or plasmonic shifts of ASO-capped nanoparticles cause a visible color change, enabling naked-eye detection of SARS-CoV-2 without complex instrumentation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_87</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELECTROCHEMICAL SIGNAL (CURRENT, POTENTIAL, IMPEDANCE CHANGES)">
      <data key="d0">ELECTROCHEMICAL SIGNAL (CURRENT, POTENTIAL, IMPEDANCE CHANGES)</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Electrochemical readouts, including changes in current, potential, or impedance, generated by the AuNP-modified array electrodes when MERS-CoV antigens are captured, serving as the quantitative signal of the immunosensor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_87</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SELF-ASSEMBLED STAR-RIDGE PLASMONIC AUNPS CHIRO-IMMUNOSENSOR">
      <data key="d0">SELF-ASSEMBLED STAR-RIDGE PLASMONIC AUNPS CHIRO-IMMUNOSENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A self-assembled star-ridge chiroplasmonic gold nanoparticle (AuNP)–based immunosensor platform reported in 2017, used for ultrasensitive detection of viral targets such as avian influenza A H5N1 at picomolar concentrations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SELF-ASSEMBLED CHIRAL QDS AND AUNPS NANOSTRUCTURE ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">SELF-ASSEMBLED CHIRAL QDS AND AUNPS NANOSTRUCTURE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A biosensor platform composed of self-assembled chiral quantum dots (QDs) and gold nanoparticle (AuNP) nanostructures, applied for highly effective detection of infectious bronchitis virus (IBV) in chicken blood samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="METAL NANOPARTICLE PROBES FOR DARK FIELD MICROSCOPY">
      <data key="d0">METAL NANOPARTICLE PROBES FOR DARK FIELD MICROSCOPY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Metal nanoparticle (NP)–based probe systems used as viral markers for identification of viruses via dark field microscopy, enabling rapid qualitative or quantitative detection through optical signal changes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QUANTUM DOT-BASED FLUORESCENCE IMAGING ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">QUANTUM DOT-BASED FLUORESCENCE IMAGING ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A quantum dot (QD)–based nanomaterial platform that binds strongly to fluorescent samples and is used for continuous fluorescence imaging and process-specific detection of cells and potentially viruses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="METAL CHELATOR–REGULATED PLASMONIC COLORIMETRIC BIOASSAY">
      <data key="d0">METAL CHELATOR–REGULATED PLASMONIC COLORIMETRIC BIOASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A plasmonic colorimetric bioassay platform in which a metal chelator acts as a signal-generation superregulator, achieving ultrasensitive detection of disease biomarkers such as HBsAg and alpha-fetoprotein.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AVIAN INFLUENZA A H5N1 VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">AVIAN INFLUENZA A H5N1 VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A highly pathogenic avian influenza A subtype H5N1 virus, an airborne viral pathogen whose low-concentration detection is enabled by self-assembled star-ridge plasmonic AuNP-based immunosensors. | A respiratory influenza A virus of avian origin mentioned as a target recognized by microfluidic devices, representing an airborne/respiratory pathogen for optical biosensing. | An avian influenza A virus of the H5N1 subtype associated with infections in dairy cattle and cross-species transmission, discussed as part of the ongoing HPAI H5N1 situation in the United States. | A segmented, negative-sense ssRNA(−) influenza A virus infecting birds, with eight RNA segments encoding 12–14 proteins and a total genome size of about 13.5 kb, providing the genomic context for H5N1 and its variants. | An airborne influenza A virus infecting birds, targeted by serological assays such as ELISA, HI, and LFAs for surveillance and outbreak monitoring. | A group of avian influenza A viruses, including H5N1, that are detected and pathotyped using handheld nanopore sequencing platforms for rapid molecular epidemiology. | A highly pathogenic H5N1 influenza A virus strain infecting humans, transmitted primarily via respiratory routes and capable of causing neurotropic, pneumotropic, and adipotropic infection in animal models.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">AVIAN INFLUENZA A VIRUS,AVIAN INFLUENZA A (H5N1) VIRUS,AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS,AVIAN INFLUENZA A VIRUSES,HUMAN INFLUENZA A (H5N1) VIRUS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS BRONCHITIS VIRUS (IBV)">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS BRONCHITIS VIRUS (IBV)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Infectious bronchitis virus (IBV), a coronavirus affecting poultry and transmitted via aerosols, detected using self-assembled chiral QD and AuNP nanostructure-based assays in chicken blood samples. | Infectious Bronchitis Virus (IBV), an avian coronavirus causing respiratory disease in poultry, cited as another pathogen suitable for early detection using the proposed multimodal sensing framework.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">INFECTIOUS BRONCHITIS VIRUS (IBV)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HBSAG">
      <data key="d0">HBSAG</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg), a viral antigen biomarker of hepatitis B virus infection, used here as a target analyte in plasmonic colorimetric bioassays whose detection sensitivity is compared to gold standard assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ALPHA-FETOPROTEIN">
      <data key="d0">ALPHA-FETOPROTEIN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Alpha-fetoprotein, a serum biomarker often associated with liver disease and cancer, serving as a target analyte in the described plasmonic colorimetric bioassay with enhanced detection sensitivity over gold standard assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LIMIT OF DETECTION FOR AVIAN INFLUENZA A H5N1 AT PICOMOLAR LEVELS">
      <data key="d0">LIMIT OF DETECTION FOR AVIAN INFLUENZA A H5N1 AT PICOMOLAR LEVELS</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The lower limit of detection for avian influenza A H5N1 virus achieved at picomolar (pmol) concentration levels using self-assembled star-ridge plasmonic AuNP-based chiro-immunosensors, indicating very high analytical sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DETECTION SENSITIVITY INCREASE OF MORE THAN THREE ORDERS OF MAGNITUDE OVER GOLD STANDARD ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">DETECTION SENSITIVITY INCREASE OF MORE THAN THREE ORDERS OF MAGNITUDE OVER GOLD STANDARD ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A performance validation result showing that the metal chelator–regulated plasmonic colorimetric bioassay achieves an increase in detection sensitivity of more than three orders of magnitude compared to gold standard assays for HBsAg and alpha-fetoprotein.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VISUAL OR FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL CHANGES FROM NANOPARTICLE VIRAL MARKERS">
      <data key="d0">VISUAL OR FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL CHANGES FROM NANOPARTICLE VIRAL MARKERS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Optical reporter signals, including visual colorimetric and fluorescence changes, generated by nanoparticle-based viral markers to enable rapid qualitative or quantitative virus detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTINUOUS FLUORESCENCE IMAGING SIGNAL FROM QUANTUM DOTS">
      <data key="d0">CONTINUOUS FLUORESCENCE IMAGING SIGNAL FROM QUANTUM DOTS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Continuous fluorescence emission produced by quantum dots (QDs), used for real-time imaging and process-specific detection of cells and potentially viral infection processes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="T7 PHAGE-BASED MIRNA QUANTIFICATION ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">T7 PHAGE-BASED MIRNA QUANTIFICATION ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A phage-mediated biosensing platform that uses T7 phage to quantify miRNAs, enabling effortless and precise detection of miRNAs without the need for conventional laboratory equipment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_90</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MIRNA">
      <data key="d0">MIRNA</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">MicroRNA molecules that serve as the target analyte in the T7 phage-based quantification assay, where their presence and amount are inferred via phage-mediated detection readouts.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_90</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="M13@H9N2BP@AUBP PHAGE–GOLD NANOPARTICLE BIOSENSOR">
      <data key="d0">M13@H9N2BP@AUBP PHAGE–GOLD NANOPARTICLE BIOSENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A phage-based biosensor constructed from M13 phage displaying H9N2-binding peptides and decorated with gold nanoparticles, exhibiting a surface plasmon resonance electric field about 40-fold higher than traditional gold nanoparticles for virus detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_90</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H9N2 VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">H9N2 VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">An avian influenza virus subtype (H9N2) that can be detected at extremely low concentrations using the M13@H9N2BP@AuBP phage–gold nanoparticle biosensor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_90</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H9N2 DETECTION LIMIT OF 6.3 COPIES/ML (~1.04 × 10−5 FM)">
      <data key="d0">H9N2 DETECTION LIMIT OF 6.3 COPIES/ML (~1.04 × 10−5 FM)</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The reported analytical sensitivity of the M13@H9N2BP@AuBP biosensor, corresponding to a minimum detectable H9N2 virus concentration of 6.3 copies per milliliter, approximately 1.04 × 10−5 femtomolar.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_90</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="D-ALANYL-D-ALANINE-MODIFIED GOLD NANOPARTICLES (D-AMINO ACID-CAPPED AUNPS) BROAD-SPECTRUM BACTERIAL DETECTION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">D-ALANYL-D-ALANINE-MODIFIED GOLD NANOPARTICLES (D-AMINO ACID-CAPPED AUNPS) BROAD-SPECTRUM BACTERIAL DETECTION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Gold nanoparticle-based biosensor platform capped with D-alanyl-D-alanine (D-amino acids) that specifically targets bacteria and differentiates Staphylococcus aureus from methicillin-resistant S. aureus (MRSA) via colorimetric changes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_118</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BROAD-SPECTRUM TB DETECTOR USING ANTIBODY-LABELED POROUS SILICA NANODISKS AND HIGH-THROUGHPUT MASS SPECTROMETRY">
      <data key="d0">BROAD-SPECTRUM TB DETECTOR USING ANTIBODY-LABELED POROUS SILICA NANODISKS AND HIGH-THROUGHPUT MASS SPECTROMETRY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Sputum-free tuberculosis detection platform in clinical research (NCT03271567) that uses antibody labeling, energy-focused porous disk-shaped silica nanoparticles (nanodisks), and high-throughput mass spectrometry to quantify circulating Mycobacterium tuberculosis antigen peptides with high sensitivity in PTB, EPTB, and HIV-positive patients.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_118</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BACTERIA-ACTIVATED THERANOSTIC NANOPROBE AGAINST MRSA">
      <data key="d0">BACTERIA-ACTIVATED THERANOSTIC NANOPROBE AGAINST MRSA</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Activatable theranostic nanoprobe that is specifically activated by methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA), enabling rapid near-infrared fluorescence (NIRF) imaging and prolonged tracking of MRSA infection progression.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_118</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPTICAL IMAGING READOUT FOR NANOPARTICLE-BASED BACTERIAL DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">OPTICAL IMAGING READOUT FOR NANOPARTICLE-BASED BACTERIAL DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Optical imaging-based reporter modality used to detect modified nanoparticles via recognition of bacterial ligands, including colorimetric and fluorescence signals. | Electrochemical signal output used as a detection modality for nanoparticle-based biosensors recognizing bacterial ligands.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_118</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
      <data key="d6">ELECTROCHEMICAL SENSING READOUT FOR NANOPARTICLE-BASED BACTERIAL DETECTION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECTROSCOPY-BASED READOUT FOR NANOPARTICLE-BASED BACTERIAL DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">SPECTROSCOPY-BASED READOUT FOR NANOPARTICLE-BASED BACTERIAL DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Spectroscopic reporter modality (e.g., mass spectrometry, optical spectroscopy) used to detect signals from modified nanoparticles that bind bacterial ligands.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_118</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-THROUGHPUT MASS SPECTROMETRY READOUT FOR TB NANODISK DETECTOR">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-THROUGHPUT MASS SPECTROMETRY READOUT FOR TB NANODISK DETECTOR</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">High-throughput mass spectrometry signal used as the primary analytical readout to quantify circulating Mycobacterium tuberculosis antigen peptides in the nanodisk-based TB detector.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_118</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEAR-INFRARED FLUORESCENCE (NIRF) IMAGING SIGNAL FROM MRSA THERANOSTIC NANOPROBE">
      <data key="d0">NEAR-INFRARED FLUORESCENCE (NIRF) IMAGING SIGNAL FROM MRSA THERANOSTIC NANOPROBE</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Near-infrared fluorescence signal generated upon activation of the bacteria-activated theranostic nanoprobe, enabling rapid imaging and longitudinal tracking of MRSA infections.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_118</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPUTUM-FREE BLOOD-BASED SAMPLE PROCESSING FOR TB NANODISK DETECTOR">
      <data key="d0">SPUTUM-FREE BLOOD-BASED SAMPLE PROCESSING FOR TB NANODISK DETECTOR</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Sample preparation workflow for the TB nanodisk detector that avoids sputum collection and instead processes blood or plasma to measure circulating Mycobacterium tuberculosis antigen peptides.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_118</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLINICAL RESEARCH VALIDATION OF TB NANODISK DETECTOR (NCT03271567)">
      <data key="d0">CLINICAL RESEARCH VALIDATION OF TB NANODISK DETECTOR (NCT03271567)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Clinical research study (NCT03271567) evaluating the performance of the sputum-free TB nanodisk detector, including sensitivity in culture-positive PTB, EPTB, and HIV-positive patients.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_118</data>
