      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_526</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SERS BIOSENSOR SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">SERS BIOSENSOR SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The surface-enhanced Raman scattering (SERS) spectral signal generated by analytes interacting with the porous silk fibroin and gold nanocrack platform, used as the readout of the biosensor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_526</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SHERLOCK MULTIPLEXED NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">SHERLOCK MULTIPLEXED NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A portable, multiplexed CRISPR-based nucleic acid detection platform described by Gootenberg et al. (Science 2018) that integrates Cas13, Cas12a, and Csm6 for sensitive detection of diverse nucleic acid targets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_555</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENT REPORTER CLEAVAGE SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENT REPORTER CLEAVAGE SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A fluorescence-based readout generated when activated Cas13, Cas12a, or Csm6 cleaves labeled reporter molecules in the SHERLOCK assay. | Fluorescent signal generated when CRISPR-based tools cleave DNA fragments labeled with fluorescent probe–quencher pairs, indicating the presence of target RNA. | A CRISPR-associated reporter signal in which target recognition activates nuclease-mediated cleavage of a fluorescently labeled reporter, generating a measurable fluorescence increase used to read out TRACE assay results. | A fluorescence signal generated when activated Cas12a or Cas13a cleaves labeled single-stranded DNA or RNA reporter molecules in CRISPR-based nucleic acid detection assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a_chunk_555</data>
      <data key="d5">f2b3cfad-751c-4e9d-a9ef-77be12b8fc1a,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">FLUORESCENT CLEAVAGE SIGNAL,FLUOROGENIC REPORTER CLEAVAGE SIGNAL</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUCLEIC ACID TEST (LAB-BASED)">
      <data key="d0">NUCLEIC ACID TEST (LAB-BASED)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A laboratory-based nucleic acid test for COVID-19 that detects SARS-CoV-2 by amplifying and measuring viral nucleic acids, regarded as the gold standard diagnostic method.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRUS RNA EXTRACTION">
      <data key="d0">VIRUS RNA EXTRACTION</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sample preparation step in which viral RNA is purified from collected clinical specimens prior to nucleic acid amplification in COVID-19 diagnostic workflows.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1_chunk_2,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PCR-BASED RNA AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">PCR-BASED RNA AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A nucleic acid amplification method involving reverse transcription followed by PCR in a thermal cycler to amplify SARS-CoV-2 RNA-derived nucleic acids for sensitive detection. | A reverse-transcription polymerase chain reaction method used on-chip in the integrated microfluidic system for influenza A virus detection and subtyping.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1</data>
      <data key="d6">RT-PCR-BASED AMPLIFICATION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A general class of enzymatic methods that increase the copy number of target viral nucleic acids, forming the core of lab-based COVID-19 nucleic acid tests. | A generic nucleic acid amplification (NAA) step used in CRISPR diagnostics, typically performed prior to or integrated with CRISPR-based detection to increase assay sensitivity, but often adding complexity and contamination risk when done in separate steps. | Nucleic acid amplification (NAA) used generically to denote the amplification reaction that shares its amplicon with the CRISPR detection step; excessive Cas12a activity during NAA can deplete this shared amplicon and reduce amplification efficiency. | A generic nucleic acid amplification process that is explicitly not required in the ANCA method workflow for detecting carbapenemase-producing bacteria in human samples such as urine and blood.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b</data>
      <data key="d6">NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION,NAA</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CT CHEST SCAN">
      <data key="d0">CT CHEST SCAN</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A CT chest imaging procedure used for COVID-19 diagnosis that detects lung abnormalities associated with SARS-CoV-2 infection, with relatively high sensitivity but low specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEROLOGICAL TESTS">
      <data key="d0">SEROLOGICAL TESTS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Serological assay runs that detect antibodies generated by the immune system against SARS-CoV-2, useful for confirming infection or prior exposure but not for early diagnosis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENT SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENT SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">An optical reporter signal generated during nucleic acid amplification or detection, used as the measurable readout indicating the presence of SARS-CoV-2 RNA in diagnostic assays. | The fluorescence-based reporter readout used in the TRACE duplex assay, with stage-specific changes (ΔF1 and ΔF2) corresponding to RNase P and MPXV J2L detection, respectively. | Time-resolved fluorescence readouts recorded from free 3′-FAM-gRNA 1 and from the 3′-FAM-gRNA 1/5′-BHQ1-ssRNA blocker 1 complex at various temperatures, used to characterize thermal dissociation and quenching efficiency. | A fluorescence-based reporter signal generated by Argonaute-mediated cleavage reactions to indicate the presence of amplified target nucleic acids. | The optical reporter output generated when the ANCA reaction produces the output DNA material; its increase reflects successful target DNA-dependent amplification. | Optical reporter readout in the ANCA reaction, where strong fluorescence indicates successful target-dependent amplification and negligible fluorescence indicates absence or failure of key reaction components.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b</data>
      <data key="d6">FLUORESCENT SIGNAL,FLUORESCENCE SIGNALS,FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COVID-19 DIAGNOSTICS">
      <data key="d0">COVID-19 DIAGNOSTICS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The overall diagnostic framework for COVID-19, within which nucleic acid tests are considered the gold standard and are compared to CT chest scans and serological tests in terms of sensitivity and specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1_chunk_2,ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CT CHEST SCAN SPECIFICITY PROFILE">
      <data key="d0">CT CHEST SCAN SPECIFICITY PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The specificity characteristics of CT chest scans for COVID-19 diagnosis, described as low (~25%) due to imaging features that overlap with other viral pneumonias. | The sensitivity characteristics of CT chest scans for COVID-19 diagnosis, reported as relatively high (approximately 86%–98%) for detecting lung abnormalities associated with infection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ed45ef2f-ad29-4058-8b09-5fed00b411a1</data>
      <data key="d6">CT CHEST SCAN SENSITIVITY PROFILE</data>
    </node>
