      <data key="d0">EXPERIMENT 3 ASSAY RUN ON FRESH SALIVA</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The experimental run (Experiment 3) in which optical PA spectra from fresh saliva specimens of SARS-CoV-2 patients were collected and analyzed to assess the feasibility of saliva-based detection using the proposed technique.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INACTIVATION OF NASOPHARYNGEAL EXUDATES">
      <data key="d0">INACTIVATION OF NASOPHARYNGEAL EXUDATES</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">The sample preparation step in which nasopharyngeal exudate specimens are inactivated prior to optical PA spectral analysis and model-based classification of SARS-CoV-2 infection status.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECTRAL FEATURE DESCRIPTOR 483–610 NM">
      <data key="d0">SPECTRAL FEATURE DESCRIPTOR 483–610 NM</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A quantitative spectral feature descriptor (SFD) computed from saliva pixel spectra in the 483–610 nm wavelength band, used as a signal metric to distinguish SARS-CoV-2 PCR-positive from PCR-negative cases, with statistically significant differences by infection status and sex. | A quantitative spectral feature descriptor (SFD) computed from saliva pixel spectra in the 407–470 nm wavelength band, used as a signal metric to distinguish SARS-CoV-2 PCR-positive from PCR-negative cases, with statistically significant differences by infection status and sex.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
      <data key="d6">SPECTRAL FEATURE DESCRIPTOR 407–470 NM</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SALIVA SPECTRAL SCREENING ASSAY FOR SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d0">SALIVA SPECTRAL SCREENING ASSAY FOR SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An optical screening method based on analysis of pixel-level spectra from fresh human saliva samples, using PLS-DA and spectral feature descriptors to differentiate the presence of SARS-CoV-2 in PCR-positive versus PCR-negative cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ASSAY VALIDATION WITH WILCOXON RANK SUM AND KOLMOGOROV–SMIRNOV TESTS">
      <data key="d0">ASSAY VALIDATION WITH WILCOXON RANK SUM AND KOLMOGOROV–SMIRNOV TESTS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Statistical validation of the saliva spectral screening assay using the Kolmogorov–Smirnov test to reject normality and the Wilcoxon rank sum test, which showed highly significant differences (p-value = 0 as reported) in spectral feature descriptor values between SARS-CoV-2 positive and negative cases, including male and female subsets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HYPERSPECTRAL IMAGE ANALYSIS IN THE VISIBLE AND NEAR-INFRARED RANGE">
      <data key="d0">HYPERSPECTRAL IMAGE ANALYSIS IN THE VISIBLE AND NEAR-INFRARED RANGE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A label-free optical biosensing platform that uses hyperspectral imaging across visible and near-infrared wavelengths to scan many samples simultaneously for high-throughput detection of SARS-CoV-2 without reagents or nucleic acid amplification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-THROUGHPUT TESTING BY SCANNING MANY SAMPLES SIMULTANEOUSLY">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-THROUGHPUT TESTING BY SCANNING MANY SAMPLES SIMULTANEOUSLY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The operational testing configuration in which the hyperspectral imaging platform scans multiple samples in parallel to enable mass screening for SARS-CoV-2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REDUCED SPECIFICITY RELATIVE TO OTHER RESPIRATORY VIRAL SPECIES">
      <data key="d0">REDUCED SPECIFICITY RELATIVE TO OTHER RESPIRATORY VIRAL SPECIES</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">A specificity profile in which the screening test prioritizes high sensitivity for SARS-CoV-2 detection, accepting lower specificity and potential cross-reactivity with other respiratory viruses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMMON COLD VIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">COMMON COLD VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A group of seasonal respiratory viruses (e.g., rhinoviruses and related agents) mentioned as likely causes of respiratory infections in circulation, which the technique must distinguish from SARS-CoV-2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECIFICITY OF DETECTION VERSUS OTHER RESPIRATORY VIRAL SPECIES">
      <data key="d0">SPECIFICITY OF DETECTION VERSUS OTHER RESPIRATORY VIRAL SPECIES</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The specificity profile of the technique, reflecting its ability to correctly distinguish SARS-CoV-2 from other circulating respiratory viruses such as influenza and common cold viruses; further dedicated specificity studies are noted as needed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SENSITIVITY FOR ANALYSIS OF EXUDATE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">SENSITIVITY FOR ANALYSIS OF EXUDATE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">An assay validation result indicating that the sensitivity achieved for detecting SARS-CoV-2 in exudate samples is comparable to that of other rapid diagnostic methods.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH LEVEL OF AGREEMENT AMONG CLASSIFICATION RESULTS">
      <data key="d0">HIGH LEVEL OF AGREEMENT AMONG CLASSIFICATION RESULTS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">An assay validation outcome summarizing that the classification results (e.g., positive/negative calls) show a high degree of concordance, supporting the reliability of the technique.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PLS-DA PER-PIXEL MODEL (PLS-DA MODEL 1)">
      <data key="d0">PLS-DA PER-PIXEL MODEL (PLS-DA MODEL 1)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A partial least squares discriminant analysis model applied at the per-pixel level to PA spectra of exudate samples, later aggregated to per-patient classification. | A partial least squares discriminant analysis model constructed directly at the per-patient level using patient-averaged PA spectra of exudate samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
      <data key="d6">PLS-DA PER-PATIENT MODEL (PLS-DA MODEL 3)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FFNN PER-PIXEL MODEL">
      <data key="d0">FFNN PER-PIXEL MODEL</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A feed-forward neural network classifier using numerical shape descriptors from selected spectral fringes of PA spectra at the per-pixel level, aggregated to per-patient classification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXUDATE PA SPECTRAL ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">EXUDATE PA SPECTRAL ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Photoacoustic spectral analysis of exudate samples used to classify SARS-CoV-2 positive and negative patients, benchmarked against standard PCR and qRT-PCR results.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SALIVA PA SPECTRAL ASSAY (EXPERIMENT 3)">
      <data key="d0">SALIVA PA SPECTRAL ASSAY (EXPERIMENT 3)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Photoacoustic spectral analysis of fresh human saliva samples to distinguish SARS-CoV-2 positive and negative cases at the pixel level.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXUDATE ASSAY VALIDATION VS PCR/QRT-PCR">
      <data key="d0">EXUDATE ASSAY VALIDATION VS PCR/QRT-PCR</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Validation of the exudate PA spectral assay against standard PCR and qRT-PCR tests, including patients with low viral loads.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXUDATE ASSAY SENSITIVITY AND ACCURACY">
      <data key="d0">EXUDATE ASSAY SENSITIVITY AND ACCURACY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Performance metrics for the exudate PA spectral assay, reporting 100% sensitivity and very high overall classification accuracy compared to standard PCR tests.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SALIVA PIXEL-LEVEL CROSS-VALIDATION (10-FOLD)">
      <data key="d0">SALIVA PIXEL-LEVEL CROSS-VALIDATION (10-FOLD)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Tenfold cross-validation of the saliva PA spectral assay at the pixel level, yielding 87% overall accuracy for classifying pixels from positive and negative patients.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WIDE-FOV OPTICAL COVID-19 BIOSENSING SETUP">
      <data key="d0">WIDE-FOV OPTICAL COVID-19 BIOSENSING SETUP</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An optical biosensing platform for COVID-19 detection that uses broadband illumination from conventional halogen sources to image multiple 5-µL droplets over a 7×10 cm² field-of-view at a 30 cm working distance, enabling high-throughput, point-of-care compatible analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MICROSCOPY IMAGING AND LAB-ON-CHIP COVID-19 PLATFORMS">
      <data key="d0">MICROSCOPY IMAGING AND LAB-ON-CHIP COVID-19 PLATFORMS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Conventional optical COVID-19 detection platforms based on microscopy imaging setups and lab-on-chip approaches that operate with a very small field-of-view, short working distance, and often require specific laser light sources.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PLS-DA CLASSIFICATION METHOD">
      <data key="d0">PLS-DA CLASSIFICATION METHOD</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A partial least squares discriminant analysis–based classification run used in the biosensor workflow, providing sample-to-result classification for a patient using six droplets in approximately eight minutes on a standard personal computer.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FFNN CLASSIFICATION ALGORITHM">
      <data key="d0">FFNN CLASSIFICATION ALGORITHM</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A feed-forward neural network–based classification run used to analyze pixel-level data from the optical biosensor, yielding sample-to-result classification for a patient using six droplets in about five minutes, with potential for further acceleration via parallel computing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LIMITS OF DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">LIMITS OF DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The minimum detectable concentration of SARS-CoV-2 for the optical screening technology, discussed as a key performance metric and expressed in units such as TU µL−1 and copies mL−1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="8×10^8 COPIES ML−1">
      <data key="d0">8×10^8 COPIES ML−1</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">A lower-bound concentration derived from the lowest synthetic SARS-CoV-2 model (800 TU µL−1), assuming 0.1% infectious particles, corresponding to approximately 8×10^8 copies mL−1 and used as a reference detectable level. | A medium viral load category for SARS-CoV-2 positive human exudate samples, defined by qRT-PCR and used to evaluate the optical screening system’s performance at intermediate concentrations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
      <data key="d6">10^4 COPIES ML−1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SYNTHETIC SARS-COV-2 MODELS (EXPERIMENT 1)">
      <data key="d0">SYNTHETIC SARS-COV-2 MODELS (EXPERIMENT 1)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Experiment 1, in which synthetic SARS-CoV-2 models were prepared at defined concentrations (800, 1500, 3000, 4000 TU µL−1) to assess detection performance and derive equivalent limits of detection in copies mL−1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 POSITIVE HUMAN EXUDATE SAMPLES (EXPERIMENT 2)">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 POSITIVE HUMAN EXUDATE SAMPLES (EXPERIMENT 2)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Experiment 2, involving SARS-CoV-2 positive human exudate samples classified by qRT-PCR into viral load categories (e.g., 10^6 and 10^4 copies mL−1) to evaluate the optical screening system under clinically relevant conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPTICAL SCREENING SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">OPTICAL SCREENING SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">The optical, image-based screening platform that provides ultra-fast sample-to-result times under one minute per patient and can be extended to detect different viral species by updating numerical models and datasets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMARTPHONE-BASED OPTICAL SPECTROSCOPIC PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">SMARTPHONE-BASED OPTICAL SPECTROSCOPIC PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A smartphone-based optical spectroscopic platform referenced as an enabling technology, suggesting potential implementation of the described optical screening system in personal, mobile devices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HYPERSPECTRAL IMAGE PROCESSING">
      <data key="d0">HYPERSPECTRAL IMAGE PROCESSING</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An optical analysis platform that uses hyperspectral imaging of clinical samples (e.g., inactivated nasopharyngeal swabs, exudate, saliva) to detect the presence of SARS-CoV-2 and distinguish positive carriers from other patients with respiratory symptoms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INACTIVATED NASOPHARYNGEAL SWABS">
      <data key="d0">INACTIVATED NASOPHARYNGEAL SWABS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sample preparation step in which nasopharyngeal swab specimens are inactivated (e.g., by heat or chemical treatment) prior to hyperspectral imaging, enabling safer handling while preserving spectral features relevant to SARS-CoV-2 detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QRT-PCR CLASSIFICATION OF EXUDATE VIRAL LOAD (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW)">
      <data key="d0">QRT-PCR CLASSIFICATION OF EXUDATE VIRAL LOAD (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation experiment (Experiment 2) using SARS-CoV-2 positive human exudate samples classified by qRT-PCR into high (10^6 copies mL−1), medium (10^4 copies mL−1), and low (10^2 copies mL−1) viral load tiers to benchmark hyperspectral image processing performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QUALITATIVE PCR CLASSIFICATION OF FRESH SALIVA (POSITIVE/NEGATIVE)">
      <data key="d0">QUALITATIVE PCR CLASSIFICATION OF FRESH SALIVA (POSITIVE/NEGATIVE)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation experiment (Experiment 3) using fresh human saliva samples classified qualitatively by PCR as SARS-CoV-2 positive or negative, without viral load quantification, to assess hyperspectral image processing in a different clinical matrix.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SYNTHETIC SARS-COV-2 MODELS AT LOW CONCENTRATION">
      <data key="d0">SYNTHETIC SARS-COV-2 MODELS AT LOW CONCENTRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation experiment employing synthetic models of SARS-CoV-2 at very low concentrations, comparable to estimated viral loads of ‘super-carriers’, to probe the sensitivity limits of the hyperspectral image processing approach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="10^2 COPIES ML−1 VIRAL LOAD IN EXUDATE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">10^2 COPIES ML−1 VIRAL LOAD IN EXUDATE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The lowest SARS-CoV-2 viral load of exudate samples analyzed (10^2 copies mL−1), representing the lower concentration boundary at which the hyperspectral image processing platform was empirically evaluated in this study.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUB-PICOMOLAR CONCENTRATION REGIME">
      <data key="d0">SUB-PICOMOLAR CONCENTRATION REGIME</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">A concentration regime below the sub-picomolar range, cited as physiologically relevant for optical detection of SARS-CoV-2 viral proteins and used as a reference for the sensitivity of detection methods.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AVERAGE VIRAL LOAD OF COVID-19 PATIENTS (~7 × 10^6 COPIES ML−1, ~0.01 PM)">
      <data key="d0">AVERAGE VIRAL LOAD OF COVID-19 PATIENTS (~7 × 10^6 COPIES ML−1, ~0.01 PM)</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">A typical SARS-CoV-2 viral load in expelled particles from COVID-19 patients, approximately 7 × 10^6 copies mL−1 (about 0.01 pM), providing a benchmark concentration relative to the detection capabilities discussed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ESTIMATED VIRAL LOAD OF SARS-COV-2 ‘SUPER-CARRIERS’">
      <data key="d0">ESTIMATED VIRAL LOAD OF SARS-COV-2 ‘SUPER-CARRIERS’</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">An estimated viral load range for individuals considered ‘super-carriers’ of SARS-CoV-2, corresponding to the lowest concentration employed in the synthetic model analysis, used to contextualize sensitivity of the hyperspectral method.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ABILITY TO DISCERN SARS-COV-2 POSITIVE CARRIERS FROM OTHER PATIENTS WITH RESPIRATORY SYMPTOMS">
      <data key="d0">ABILITY TO DISCERN SARS-COV-2 POSITIVE CARRIERS FROM OTHER PATIENTS WITH RESPIRATORY SYMPTOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">A demonstrated specificity feature of the hyperspectral image processing platform, referring to its capacity to distinguish SARS-CoV-2 positive carriers from patients who present respiratory symptoms due to other causes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ABILITY TO DIFFERENTIATE SARS-COV-2 FROM OTHER VIRUSES (NOT YET FULLY DETERMINED)">
      <data key="d0">ABILITY TO DIFFERENTIATE SARS-COV-2 FROM OTHER VIRUSES (NOT YET FULLY DETERMINED)</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">A partially characterized aspect of specificity indicating that the potential of hyperspectral image processing to distinguish SARS-CoV-2 from other viral pathogens is recognized but remains to be fully established.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENGINEERED LENTIVIRAL PARTICLES DISPLAYING SARS-COV-2 SPIKE PROTEIN">
      <data key="d0">ENGINEERED LENTIVIRAL PARTICLES DISPLAYING SARS-COV-2 SPIKE PROTEIN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Lentiviral model particles engineered to present the SARS-CoV-2 spike protein on their capsid, used as viral models to generate optical signals and calibrate spectral descriptors versus viral concentration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECTRAL FEATURE DESCRIPTOR FROM INDIVIDUAL PIXEL SPECTRA">
      <data key="d0">SPECTRAL FEATURE DESCRIPTOR FROM INDIVIDUAL PIXEL SPECTRA</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Quantitative spectral descriptor derived from individual pixel spectra that increases linearly with the concentration of viral models in biofluids and SARS-CoV-2 inactivated exudate samples, and differs between positive and negative saliva samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PLS-DA CLASSIFICATION MODEL">
      <data key="d0">PLS-DA CLASSIFICATION MODEL</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Partial least squares discriminant analysis model used as a chemometric classification platform to distinguish SARS-CoV-2 positive from negative samples based on spectral data.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FFNN CLASSIFICATION MODEL">
      <data key="d0">FFNN CLASSIFICATION MODEL</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Feed-forward neural network model used as a machine-learning classification platform to discriminate SARS-CoV-2 positive and negative samples using spectral inputs.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INACTIVATED SARS-COV-2 EXUDATE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">INACTIVATED SARS-COV-2 EXUDATE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Assay runs performed on exudate samples containing inactivated SARS-CoV-2, where accurate classification was achieved despite structural alteration of the viral capsid by the inactivation medium.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SALIVA SAMPLE ASSAY RUNS">
      <data key="d0">SALIVA SAMPLE ASSAY RUNS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Assay runs using saliva samples, including fresh saliva from male and female SARS-CoV-2 positive and negative subjects, used to explore classification performance and spectral descriptor differences, though with limited sample size.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INACTIVATION MEDIUM AND COMMERCIAL BUFFERS">
      <data key="d0">INACTIVATION MEDIUM AND COMMERCIAL BUFFERS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Sample preparation step involving inactivation media and commercial buffers that alter viral capsid structure and may affect optical and spectral properties; their effects require further study.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SALIVA SELF-COLLECTION WITHOUT SWAB">
      <data key="d0">SALIVA SELF-COLLECTION WITHOUT SWAB</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Sample collection step where subjects self-collect saliva without using a swab, enabling non-invasive sampling but with inherent handling risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLASSIFICATION PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT FOR SALIVA">
      <data key="d0">CLASSIFICATION PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT FOR SALIVA</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Validation step to evaluate classification performance on saliva samples, which could not be fully performed due to an insufficient number of salivary specimens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIFFERENTIATION OF SARS-COV-2 POSITIVE AND NEGATIVE SALIVA CASES">
      <data key="d0">DIFFERENTIATION OF SARS-COV-2 POSITIVE AND NEGATIVE SALIVA CASES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed significant differences in spectral descriptors between SARS-CoV-2 positive and negative saliva samples, supporting the assay’s potential diagnostic capability.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEX-BASED SALIVA SPECTRAL DIFFERENCES">
      <data key="d0">SEX-BASED SALIVA SPECTRAL DIFFERENCES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Preliminary validation observation of spectral descriptor differences between fresh saliva from male and female SARS-CoV-2 positive and negative subjects, in a limited number of cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HYPERSPECTRAL IMAGE ANALYSIS">
      <data key="d0">HYPERSPECTRAL IMAGE ANALYSIS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An imaging-based analytical platform that evaluates pixel-level spectral descriptors from sample droplets to infer viral load and enable rapid, high-throughput SARS-CoV-2 primary screening.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUMERICAL MODELS FOR SPECTRAL ANALYSIS">
      <data key="d0">NUMERICAL MODELS FOR SPECTRAL ANALYSIS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Computational models applied to hyperspectral pixel spectra to relate spectral descriptors to viral load, enabling reagent-free, updatable, and scalable analysis of many samples simultaneously.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POINT-OF-CARE PRIMARY SCREENING WORKFLOW">
      <data key="d0">POINT-OF-CARE PRIMARY SCREENING WORKFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The operational use of hyperspectral image analysis and numerical models at the point-of-care as a first-line, high-throughput screening step to select subjects for further molecular evaluation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SENSITIVITY AND SPECIFICITY REFINEMENT STUDIES">
      <data key="d0">SENSITIVITY AND SPECIFICITY REFINEMENT STUDIES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Planned follow-up studies with larger patient cohorts aimed at improving and better characterizing the sensitivity and specificity of the hyperspectral imaging-based SARS-CoV-2 screening technique.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VESICULAR STOMATITIS VIRUS G (VSV-G) PROTEIN PSEUDOTYPED LENTIVIRAL PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">VESICULAR STOMATITIS VIRUS G (VSV-G) PROTEIN PSEUDOTYPED LENTIVIRAL PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Lentiviral particles pseudotyped with the VSV-G protein, used as a model viral particle system in Experiment 1 for hyperspectral imaging-based identification and quantification in fluid samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESUSPENSION IN ARTIFICIAL SALIVA OR PHOSPHATE BUFFERED SALINE">
      <data key="d0">RESUSPENSION IN ARTIFICIAL SALIVA OR PHOSPHATE BUFFERED SALINE</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Sample preparation step in which viral aliquots or negative controls are resuspended in artificial saliva (1700-0305, Pickering Laboratories) or phosphate buffered saline containing 137 mM NaCl, 2.7 mM KCl, 10 mM Na2HPO4, and 1.8 mM KH2PO4 one hour before hyperspectral imaging.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NASOPHARYNGEAL EXUDATE COLLECTION FROM SUSPECTED COVID-19 CASES">
      <data key="d0">NASOPHARYNGEAL EXUDATE COLLECTION FROM SUSPECTED COVID-19 CASES</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Clinical sample collection step in which nasopharyngeal exudates are obtained from subjects referred as suspected COVID-19 cases for subsequent analysis of SARS-CoV-2 presence.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HYPERSPECTRAL IMAGING OF VIRAL SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">HYPERSPECTRAL IMAGING OF VIRAL SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An optical biosensing platform based on VIS/NIR hyperspectral imaging used to identify and quantify lentiviral particles and to analyze clinical specimens potentially containing SARS-CoV-2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPERIMENT 1: VSV-G PSEUDOTYPED LENTIVIRAL PARTICLE IMAGING">
      <data key="d0">EXPERIMENT 1: VSV-G PSEUDOTYPED LENTIVIRAL PARTICLE IMAGING</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An assay run using previously acquired data of VSV-G protein pseudotyped lentiviral particles at defined concentrations, analyzed by hyperspectral imaging for identification and quantification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPERIMENT 2: SARS-COV-2 NASOPHARYNGEAL EXUDATE IMAGING">
      <data key="d0">EXPERIMENT 2: SARS-COV-2 NASOPHARYNGEAL EXUDATE IMAGING</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An assay run in which nasopharyngeal exudates from suspected COVID-19 patients are analyzed by hyperspectral imaging to assess the presence of SARS-CoV-2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRAL PARTICLE CONCENTRATION SERIES (800–4000 TU ΜL−1)">
      <data key="d0">VIRAL PARTICLE CONCENTRATION SERIES (800–4000 TU ΜL−1)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Use of a series of known viral particle concentrations (800, 1500, 3000, and 4000 TU per µL) to characterize and validate the quantitative performance of the hyperspectral imaging assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QRT-PCR ASSAY FOR THE RNA-DEPENDENT RNA POLYMERASE GENE">
      <data key="d0">QRT-PCR ASSAY FOR THE RNA-DEPENDENT RNA POLYMERASE GENE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A quantitative real-time reverse-transcriptase PCR assay targeting the SARS-CoV-2 RNA-dependent RNA polymerase gene, used as the molecular diagnostic platform to classify nasopharyngeal samples as positive or negative based on Ct values.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QRT-PCR TESTING PROCEDURE">
      <data key="d0">QRT-PCR TESTING PROCEDURE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">The standard quantitative real-time RT-PCR diagnostic workflow applied to nasopharyngeal samples, including RNA extraction and amplification, to detect SARS-CoV-2 RNA and interpret results using Ct-based criteria.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PCR TEST">
      <data key="d0">PCR TEST</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A generic PCR-based diagnostic test applied to fresh saliva samples from adult donors to identify SARS-CoV-2 positive and negative cases, using nucleic-acid amplification and Ct-based detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QUANTITATIVE REAL-TIME REVERSE-TRANSCRIPTASE PCR (QRT-PCR)">
      <data key="d0">QUANTITATIVE REAL-TIME REVERSE-TRANSCRIPTASE PCR (QRT-PCR)</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A quantitative real-time RT-PCR amplification method that converts viral RNA to cDNA and amplifies it with real-time fluorescence monitoring, yielding cycle threshold (Ct) values proportional to SARS-CoV-2 RNA concentration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRAL RNA EXTRACTION USING A PATHO GENE-SPIN DNA/RNA EXTRACTION KIT">
      <data key="d0">VIRAL RNA EXTRACTION USING A PATHO GENE-SPIN DNA/RNA EXTRACTION KIT</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">An RNA extraction step using the Patho Gene-spin DNA/RNA extraction kit (Intron Biotechnology, South Korea) to isolate viral RNA from nasopharyngeal specimens prior to qRT-PCR analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INACTIVATING VIRAL TRANSPORT MEDIUM">
      <data key="d0">INACTIVATING VIRAL TRANSPORT MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Placement of collected specimens into an inactivating viral transport medium (Biocomma, Shenzhen, China) to inactivate and stabilize virus particles before RNA extraction and qRT-PCR testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NASOPHARYNGEAL SAMPLE COLLECTION">
      <data key="d0">NASOPHARYNGEAL SAMPLE COLLECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Collection of nasopharyngeal swab samples from pediatric patients suspected of COVID-19, which are then placed into inactivating viral transport medium for subsequent qRT-PCR testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SALIVA SAMPLE COLLECTION WITH FASTING AND EXCLUSION CRITERIA">
      <data key="d0">SALIVA SAMPLE COLLECTION WITH FASTING AND EXCLUSION CRITERIA</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Collection of fresh saliva samples from adult donors after a 6-hour fasting period and exclusion of smokers and individuals with saliva-altering diseases, with mucus-containing samples discarded before PCR analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CT &lt; 37 POSITIVITY CRITERION">
      <data key="d0">CT &lt; 37 POSITIVITY CRITERION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">An operational diagnostic rule defining qRT-PCR positivity as a cycle threshold (Ct) value below 37, used to classify nasopharyngeal samples as SARS-CoV-2 positive or negative.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRAL LOAD CLASSIFICATION (HIGH 10^6, MEDIUM 10^4, LOW 10^2 COPIES/ML)">
      <data key="d0">VIRAL LOAD CLASSIFICATION (HIGH 10^6, MEDIUM 10^4, LOW 10^2 COPIES/ML)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A post-analytical classification scheme that stratifies qRT-PCR positive samples into high (10^6 copies/mL), medium (10^4 copies/mL), and low (10^2 copies/mL) viral load categories based on quantified SARS-CoV-2 RNA levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW VIRAL LOAD (10^2 COPIES/ML)">
      <data key="d0">LOW VIRAL LOAD (10^2 COPIES/ML)</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The lowest viral load category used in this study, approximately 10^2 copies per mL, representing the lower end of the quantifiable range for the qRT-PCR assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PCR TEST SENSITIVITY VS CYCLE THRESHOLD (CT)">
      <data key="d0">PCR TEST SENSITIVITY VS CYCLE THRESHOLD (CT)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A characterization of PCR test performance noting that its sensitivity is mainly determined by the number of amplification cycles (Ct value) required to detect viral nucleic acids in a sample.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NASOPHARYNGEAL SAMPLE QRT-PCR RUN">
      <data key="d0">NASOPHARYNGEAL SAMPLE QRT-PCR RUN</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An execution of the standard qRT-PCR testing procedure on nasopharyngeal samples from pediatric COVID-19 suspects, producing Ct values and viral load classifications for SARS-CoV-2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SALIVA SAMPLE PCR RUN">
      <data key="d0">SALIVA SAMPLE PCR RUN</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An execution of the PCR test on fresh saliva samples from adult donors, generating Ct-based results to determine SARS-CoV-2 infection status and relate it to symptomatology.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENT QRT-PCR READOUT">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENT QRT-PCR READOUT</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The fluorescence signal generated during qRT-PCR amplification, monitored in real time and used to derive Ct values for SARS-CoV-2 detection and viral load estimation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION WITH CRISPR-CAS13A/C2C2">
      <data key="d0">NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION WITH CRISPR-CAS13A/C2C2</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR–Cas13a (C2c2)-based nucleic acid detection assay described by Gootenberg et al. (2017) in Science, demonstrating programmable RNA detection using Cas13a/C2c2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS13A/C2C2">
      <data key="d0">CAS13A/C2C2</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">A specific Cas13a (also known as C2c2) effector nuclease used in nucleic acid detection assays, enabling RNA-guided target recognition and collateral cleavage of reporter molecules.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 SPIKE PROTEIN">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 SPIKE PROTEIN</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The spike (S) surface glycoprotein of SARS-CoV-2, used as the specific analyte in the terahertz plasmonic metasensor study; its binding to the functionalized metasensor produces a measurable terahertz plasmonic signal that reports the presence of the virus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_63</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TERAHERTZ PLASMONIC METASENSOR FOR SARS-COV-2 SPIKE DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">TERAHERTZ PLASMONIC METASENSOR FOR SARS-COV-2 SPIKE DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A functionalized terahertz plasmonic metasensor capable of femtomolar-level detection of SARS-CoV-2 spike proteins by monitoring terahertz resonance shifts upon spike protein binding, as reported in Biosens. Bioelectron. 2021.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_63</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FEMTOMOLAR-LEVEL LIMIT OF DETECTION FOR SARS-COV-2 SPIKE PROTEIN">
      <data key="d0">FEMTOMOLAR-LEVEL LIMIT OF DETECTION FOR SARS-COV-2 SPIKE PROTEIN</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The reported analytical sensitivity of the terahertz plasmonic metasensor, achieving detection of SARS-CoV-2 spike proteins at femtomolar concentrations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_63</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CUCUMBER GREEN MOTTLE MOSAIC VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">CUCUMBER GREEN MOTTLE MOSAIC VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Cucumber green mottle mosaic virus (CGMMV) is a plant virus; in this context it is the target pathogen detected in infected watermelon seeds using a near-infrared hyperspectral imaging system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.4</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_64</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPTICAL DIAGNOSTIC OF DENGUE VIRUS INFECTED HUMAN BLOOD USING RAMAN, POLARIMETRIC AND FLUORESCENCE SPECTROSCOPY (INTECH OPEN, 2017)">
      <data key="d0">OPTICAL DIAGNOSTIC OF DENGUE VIRUS INFECTED HUMAN BLOOD USING RAMAN, POLARIMETRIC AND FLUORESCENCE SPECTROSCOPY (INTECH OPEN, 2017)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An optical diagnostic platform that analyzes Dengue virus–infected human blood using a combination of Raman, polarimetric, and fluorescence spectroscopy for virus detection and characterization.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPTICAL DIAGNOSTIC OF HEPATITIS B (HBV) AND C (HCV) FROM HUMAN BLOOD SERUM USING RAMAN SPECTROSCOPY (LASER PHYS. LETT. 2015)">
      <data key="d0">OPTICAL DIAGNOSTIC OF HEPATITIS B (HBV) AND C (HCV) FROM HUMAN BLOOD SERUM USING RAMAN SPECTROSCOPY (LASER PHYS. LETT. 2015)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A Raman spectroscopy–based optical diagnostic platform for detecting hepatitis B virus (HBV) and hepatitis C virus (HCV) from human blood serum.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAPID LABEL-FREE VIRUS CAPTURE AND IDENTIFICATION PLATFORM FROM CLINICAL SAMPLES (PNAS 2020)">
      <data key="d0">RAPID LABEL-FREE VIRUS CAPTURE AND IDENTIFICATION PLATFORM FROM CLINICAL SAMPLES (PNAS 2020)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A rapid, label-free biosensing platform designed for capture and identification of viruses directly from clinical samples without the need for labeling reagents.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DENGUE VIRUS IN HUMAN BLOOD">
      <data key="d0">DENGUE VIRUS IN HUMAN BLOOD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Dengue virus present in human blood samples, serving as the infectious target for the optical diagnostic platform using Raman, polarimetric, and fluorescence spectroscopy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEPATITIS B VIRUS (HBV) IN HUMAN BLOOD SERUM">
      <data key="d0">HEPATITIS B VIRUS (HBV) IN HUMAN BLOOD SERUM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Hepatitis B virus present in human blood serum, targeted by the Raman spectroscopy–based optical diagnostic platform. | Hepatitis C virus present in human blood serum, targeted by the Raman spectroscopy–based optical diagnostic platform.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
      <data key="d6">HEPATITIS C VIRUS (HCV) IN HUMAN BLOOD SERUM</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRUSES IN CLINICAL SAMPLES (UNSPECIFIED TYPES)">
      <data key="d0">VIRUSES IN CLINICAL SAMPLES (UNSPECIFIED TYPES)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Viruses present in clinical samples that are captured and identified by the rapid, label-free virus capture and identification platform; specific virus types are not specified in the text.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPTICAL BIOSENSORS FOR VIRUS DETECTION: PROSPECTS FOR SARS-COV-2/COVID-19">
      <data key="d0">OPTICAL BIOSENSORS FOR VIRUS DETECTION: PROSPECTS FOR SARS-COV-2/COVID-19</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A set of optical biosensor platform concepts and implementations discussed in the ChemBioChem article by Maddali et al., focusing on optical methods for detecting SARS-CoV-2/COVID-19 and other viruses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="A COLORIMETRIC RT-LAMP ASSAY AND LAMP-SEQUENCING FOR DETECTING SARS-COV-2 RNA IN CLINICAL SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">A COLORIMETRIC RT-LAMP ASSAY AND LAMP-SEQUENCING FOR DETECTING SARS-COV-2 RNA IN CLINICAL SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An assay platform described by Thi et al. that combines colorimetric RT-LAMP with LAMP-sequencing to detect SARS-CoV-2 RNA in clinical samples, providing both rapid visual readout and sequence-level confirmation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LAMP-SEQUENCING">
      <data key="d0">LAMP-SEQUENCING</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Sequencing of LAMP-amplified products, used in the Thi et al. workflow as an amplification-derived readout to confirm the presence and identity of SARS-CoV-2 RNA.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COLORIMETRIC READOUT">
      <data key="d0">COLORIMETRIC READOUT</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A visually observable color change generated by the RT-LAMP reaction in the Thi et al. assay, serving as the primary reporter signal indicating successful amplification of SARS-CoV-2 RNA. | A visual color change used as a detection signal in isothermal amplification assays targeting influenza gene segments, enabling simple, equipment-light interpretation of results. | A visible color change used as the detection signal in the CRISPR/dCas9 assay for SARS-CoV-2 and drug-resistant pH1N1, enabling instrument-free readout.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b</data>
      <data key="d6">COLORIMETRIC READOUT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPTICAL DETECTION OF COV-SARS-2 VIRAL PROTEINS TO SUB-PICOMOLAR CONCENTRATIONS">
      <data key="d0">OPTICAL DETECTION OF COV-SARS-2 VIRAL PROTEINS TO SUB-PICOMOLAR CONCENTRATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An optical detection platform described by Stanborough et al. in ACS Omega that measures SARS-CoV-2 viral proteins with sensitivity down to sub-picomolar concentrations using optical methods.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 VIRAL PROTEINS">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 VIRAL PROTEINS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Protein components of the SARS-CoV-2 virus that serve as the molecular targets whose optical signatures are measured to sub-picomolar concentrations in the ACS Omega study.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECTROSCOPY-BASED COVID-19 DIAGNOSTIC TECHNIQUE (KITANE ET AL. 2021)">
      <data key="d0">SPECTROSCOPY-BASED COVID-19 DIAGNOSTIC TECHNIQUE (KITANE ET AL. 2021)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A simple and fast spectroscopy-based technique described by Kitane et al. for diagnosing COVID-19, using spectral signatures from patient samples to infer SARS-CoV-2 infection status.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ATR-FTIR SPECTROSCOPY WITH ANALYSIS ALGORITHM (BARAUNA ET AL. 2021)">
      <data key="d0">ATR-FTIR SPECTROSCOPY WITH ANALYSIS ALGORITHM (BARAUNA ET AL. 2021)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An ultrarapid on-site diagnostic platform using simple ATR-FTIR spectroscopy combined with an analysis algorithm to detect SARS-CoV-2 infection with high sensitivity and specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH SENSITIVITY AND SPECIFICITY (BARAUNA ET AL. 2021)">
      <data key="d0">HIGH SENSITIVITY AND SPECIFICITY (BARAUNA ET AL. 2021)</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The reported performance characteristics of the ATR-FTIR spectroscopy and analysis algorithm platform, indicating strong ability to correctly identify SARS-CoV-2 positive and negative samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">4dc306e7-3b4b-4f0b-9c14-b13bbd895a99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MEGFP-LINKER-MSCARLET-I MACROMOLECULAR CROWDING CONSTRUCT (GE2.3)">
      <data key="d0">MEGFP-LINKER-MSCARLET-I MACROMOLECULAR CROWDING CONSTRUCT (GE2.3)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A genetically encoded FRET-based crowding biosensor composed of mEGFP and mScarlet-I connected by a linker, used to report on macromolecular crowding via time-resolved two-photon fluorescence measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_109</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FÖRSTER RESONANCE ENERGY TRANSFER (FRET) FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">FÖRSTER RESONANCE ENERGY TRANSFER (FRET) FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The fluorescence energy transfer signal between mEGFP and mScarlet-I used to quantify environmental sensitivity and macromolecular crowding in the GE2.3 biosensor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_109</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR RNA (CRRNA) GUIDE">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR RNA (CRRNA) GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR RNA (crRNA) guide that base-pairs with complementary RNA targets to direct Cas13a-mediated RNA cleavage in CRISPR-based detection and regulation assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_131</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE-MOLECULE ASSAY FOR HIGHLY SENSITIVE SARS-COV-2 GENE DETECTION BASED ON CRISPR-CAS12A">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE-MOLECULE ASSAY FOR HIGHLY SENSITIVE SARS-COV-2 GENE DETECTION BASED ON CRISPR-CAS12A</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas12a-based single-molecule gene detection platform for SARS-CoV-2 that exploits Cas12a trans-cleavage activity, combined with a nucleic acid pre-amplification step, to achieve highly sensitive detection of viral genetic material.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_208</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GUIDE RNA">
      <data key="d0">GUIDE RNA</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A programmable RNA that base-pairs with a specific target gene sequence to activate Cas12a or Cas13a trans-cleavage activity; in the described assay, it confers sequence specificity for SARS-CoV-2 gene detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_208</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PRE-AMPLIFICATION STEP">
      <data key="d0">PRE-AMPLIFICATION STEP</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A generic nucleic acid amplification step performed before CRISPR-Cas12a detection to increase target copy number, enabling attomolar-level sensitivity but introducing primer design complexity and potential DNA polymerase base substitution errors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_208</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ATTOMOLAR DETECTION LIMIT">
      <data key="d0">ATTOMOLAR DETECTION LIMIT</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">An extremely low limit of detection, on the order of 10^-18 moles, reported as achievable by CRISPR-Cas12a-based gene detection methods when combined with a pre-amplification step.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_208</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FCSSOFI">
      <data key="d0">FCSSOFI</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescence correlation spectroscopy super-resolution optical fluctuation imaging (fcsSOFI), a fluorescence-based imaging and analysis platform used to measure and characterize (bio)molecular diffusion dynamics in porous hydrogels, patterned nanosurfaces, and aqueous environments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_353</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FIBIS">
      <data key="d0">FIBIS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">FLIM intensity based image segmentation (FIBIS), a fluorescence lifetime imaging microscopy (FLIM) analysis platform that segments images by intensity to metabolically profile transferred mitochondria at single-cell resolution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_353</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BIOMOLECULAR DIFFUSION IN POROUS HYDROGELS">
      <data key="d0">BIOMOLECULAR DIFFUSION IN POROUS HYDROGELS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An application of fcsSOFI to measure and characterize diffusion dynamics of biomolecules of varying size and chemical properties in water, patterned nanosurfaces, and porous agarose hydrogels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_353</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="METABOLIC PROFILING OF TRANSFERRED MITOCHONDRIA IN BREAST CANCER CELLS">
      <data key="d0">METABOLIC PROFILING OF TRANSFERRED MITOCHONDRIA IN BREAST CANCER CELLS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An application of FIBIS to profile metabolic state changes in breast cancer cells following mitochondrial transfer, focusing on shifts toward oxidative phosphorylation and associated cell fate decisions at single-cell resolution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_353</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENCE CORRELATION SPECTROSCOPY">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENCE CORRELATION SPECTROSCOPY</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescence intensity fluctuation signal used within fcsSOFI to infer molecular diffusion properties in porous and complex matrices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_353</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENCE LIFETIME IMAGING MICROSCOPY (FLIM) SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENCE LIFETIME IMAGING MICROSCOPY (FLIM) SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescence lifetime-based signal used in FIBIS to distinguish metabolic states of transferred mitochondria via intensity-based image segmentation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_353</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ESPRESSO">
      <data key="d0">ESPRESSO</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A hyperspectral imaging-based biosensor platform (Environmental Sensors Profiling Relayed by Subcellular Structures and Organelles) that uses organelle-specific environment-sensitive probes and phasor unmixing to monitor keratinocyte cell states in living 3D skin organoids.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_355</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ORGANELLE-SPECIFIC ENVIRONMENT-SENSITIVE PROBES (ESPS)">
      <data key="d0">ORGANELLE-SPECIFIC ENVIRONMENT-SENSITIVE PROBES (ESPS)</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescent environment-sensitive probes targeted to specific organelles (chromatin, mitochondria, lysosomes, tubulin, Golgi apparatus, lipid droplets) whose spectral properties report on local cellular environments and are read out by the ESPRESSO platform.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_355</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HYPERSPECTRAL IMAGING AND PHASOR UNMIXING READOUT">
      <data key="d0">HYPERSPECTRAL IMAGING AND PHASOR UNMIXING READOUT</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The combined hyperspectral imaging and phasor unmixing signal used by ESPRESSO to simultaneously resolve up to six organelle-targeted ESPs with a single laser excitation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_355</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPANSION MICROSCOPY (EXM) SAMPLE PREPARATION">
      <data key="d0">EXPANSION MICROSCOPY (EXM) SAMPLE PREPARATION</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sample preparation method that uses osmotic forces to physically expand biological specimens, separating features below the diffraction limit to enable super-resolution imaging.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_357</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MINSTED NANOSCOPY">
      <data key="d0">MINSTED NANOSCOPY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A super-resolution fluorescence nanoscopy platform that localizes single fluorophores with angstrom-level precision using stimulated emission depletion (STED) and detection-driven repositioning of a STED donut minimum.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_357</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STED (STIMULATED EMISSION DEPLETION) PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">STED (STIMULATED EMISSION DEPLETION) PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A dedicated light pattern used to inhibit fluorophore emission via stimulated emission depletion, forming a donut-shaped intensity profile with a central minimum for super-resolution localization.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_357</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WEAK-AFFINITY FLUOROPHORE LABELS">
      <data key="d0">WEAK-AFFINITY FLUOROPHORE LABELS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Non-covalent, weak-affinity fluorophore labels that transiently bind to targets, enabling multi-target super-resolution microscopy and helping to circumvent spectral overlap limitations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_357</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTI-TARGET SUPER-RESOLUTION MICROSCOPY WORKFLOW">
      <data key="d0">MULTI-TARGET SUPER-RESOLUTION MICROSCOPY WORKFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A microscopy workflow that uses transient binding of weak-affinity fluorophore labels and sequential imaging of multiple targets to overcome the spectral barrier in fluorescence microscopy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_357</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 VARIANTS">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 VARIANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">SARS-CoV-2 variants are genetically distinct forms of SARS-CoV-2 that arise through mutation; they are the focus of antigen design efforts aimed at eliciting protective antibody responses against current and potential future strains, and represent a moving panel of airborne viral targets for detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_401</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ZOONOTIC CORONAVIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">ZOONOTIC CORONAVIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Zoonotic coronaviruses are coronaviruses that originate in animal hosts and can spill over into humans, causing outbreaks; they provide historical context motivating broad, variant-resilient vaccine and antigen design and, in biosensing, represent a broader class of related airborne viral pathogens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_401</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IRREVERSIBLE FLUORESCENT SENSORS TO MAP OPIOID MOLECULES ACROSS ANIMAL TISSUES">
      <data key="d0">IRREVERSIBLE FLUORESCENT SENSORS TO MAP OPIOID MOLECULES ACROSS ANIMAL TISSUES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A new class of irreversible fluorescent biosensors designed to map the spatial distribution of opioid molecules across animal tissues, enabling investigation of neuronal signaling and neurodegenerative disease mechanisms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_430</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FIBRIL-SPECIFIC NANOBODY SENSORS TARGETING ALPHA-SYNUCLEIN PATHOLOGY">
      <data key="d0">FIBRIL-SPECIFIC NANOBODY SENSORS TARGETING ALPHA-SYNUCLEIN PATHOLOGY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Fibril-specific nanobody-based tools designed to recognize and inhibit alpha-synuclein fibrils, used to study and modulate pathology development in Parkinson's disease mouse models.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_430</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MODULAR GENETICALLY ENCODABLE RNA-BASED BRET SENSORS">
      <data key="d0">MODULAR GENETICALLY ENCODABLE RNA-BASED BRET SENSORS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Modular, genetically encodable RNA-based bioluminescence resonance energy transfer (BRET) biosensors that use a luciferase/luciferin donor and a fluorescent acceptor for real-time, quantitative cellular target detection and high-throughput screening.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_430</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LUCIFERASE/LUCIFERIN DONOR–FLUORESCENT PROTEIN ACCEPTOR BRET SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">LUCIFERASE/LUCIFERIN DONOR–FLUORESCENT PROTEIN ACCEPTOR BRET SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A bioluminescence resonance energy transfer reporter system in which a luciferase/luciferin pair serves as the energy donor and a fluorescent protein serves as the energy acceptor, producing a ratiometric bioluminescent signal for sensitive, low-background imaging.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_430</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GENETICALLY ENCODED FLUORESCENT KINASE BIOSENSORS">
      <data key="d0">GENETICALLY ENCODED FLUORESCENT KINASE BIOSENSORS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Genetically encoded fluorescent biosensors designed to report kinase activity, enabling multiplexed activity sensing and super-resolution imaging of dynamic biochemical processes in living cells.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_430</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DNA-TEMPLATED SILVER NANOCLUSTER-BASED CLEAVABLE PROBES (DNA/AGNCS)">
      <data key="d0">DNA-TEMPLATED SILVER NANOCLUSTER-BASED CLEAVABLE PROBES (DNA/AGNCS)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A nucleic-acid-based biosensor platform in which DNA-templated silver nanoclusters act as fluorescent reporters that are activated or modulated upon enzymatic cleavage of the DNA probe, enabling nucleic acid and nuclease activity detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_432</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TAQMAN PROBES">
      <data key="d0">TAQMAN PROBES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Conventional short oligonucleotide FRET-based probes dually labeled with a fluorophore and quencher, used in nucleic acid amplification assays to report target-dependent enzymatic digestion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_432</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DNASEALERT">
      <data key="d0">DNASEALERT</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A commercial FRET-based oligonucleotide probe system that fluoresces upon nuclease-mediated cleavage, used to detect DNase activity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_432</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION ASSAYS USING TAQMAN/DNASEALERT">
      <data key="d0">NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION ASSAYS USING TAQMAN/DNASEALERT</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Assay runs in which FRET-based dual-labeled oligonucleotide probes such as TaqMan or DNaseAlert are used to monitor nucleic acid amplification or nuclease activity via fluorescence increase upon probe digestion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_432</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION WITH DNA/AGNC CLEAVABLE PROBES">
      <data key="d0">NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION WITH DNA/AGNC CLEAVABLE PROBES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Assay runs that employ DNA-templated silver nanocluster-based cleavable probes to detect DNA or RNA targets or nuclease activity through changes in nanocluster fluorescence upon enzymatic digestion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_432</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENT SIGNAL FROM DNA-TEMPLATED SILVER NANOCLUSTERS">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENT SIGNAL FROM DNA-TEMPLATED SILVER NANOCLUSTERS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The fluorescence emitted by silver nanoclusters templated on DNA, which serves as the readout signal that changes upon enzymatic cleavage of the DNA probe.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_432</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRET-BASED FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">FRET-BASED FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A fluorescence resonance energy transfer signal generated between a donor fluorophore and a quencher on dual-labeled oligonucleotide probes, used as the readout in TaqMan and DNaseAlert assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_432</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE MOLECULE TIRF-BASED PLATFORM TO STUDY DNA SUPERCOILING EFFECT ON DNA PROCESSING ENZYMES">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE MOLECULE TIRF-BASED PLATFORM TO STUDY DNA SUPERCOILING EFFECT ON DNA PROCESSING ENZYMES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A single-molecule total internal reflection fluorescence (TIRF) microscopy platform designed to investigate how DNA supercoiling influences the activity of DNA processing enzymes, effectively functioning as a specialized biosensing setup for DNA–protein interactions under controlled supercoiling conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c_chunk_471</data>
      <data key="d5">8b626067-a7f3-4d8f-bbf1-8f50269e849c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THERMALLY REGULATED ASYNCHRONOUS CRISPR-ENHANCED (TRACE) ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">THERMALLY REGULATED ASYNCHRONOUS CRISPR-ENHANCED (TRACE) ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">TRACE is a thermally programmed, one-pot CRISPR-based diagnostic platform that enables rapid, sensitive detection of multiple DNA targets in a streamlined format suitable for on-site pandemic surveillance and point-of-care testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MONKEYPOX VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">MONKEYPOX VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Monkeypox virus (MPXV) is an orthopoxvirus responsible for recent outbreaks; it can be transmitted via close contact and potentially via respiratory routes, making it a relevant pathogen for surveillance diagnostics such as TRACE.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_0,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_1,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_59,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_61,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MPXV">
      <data key="d0">MPXV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">MPXV is the abbreviation for monkeypox virus, the DNA pathogen that TRACE detects rapidly in clinical samples (within about 11 minutes).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_0,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_8,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_18,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_22,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_23,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_26,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_38,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_46,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="2.5 COPIES/TEST LIMIT OF DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">2.5 COPIES/TEST LIMIT OF DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The analytical sensitivity of TRACE, reported as a limit of detection of 2.5 copies of target DNA per test, indicating very low minimal detectable target levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CANONICAL ONE-POT CRISPR ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">CANONICAL ONE-POT CRISPR ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A reference one-pot CRISPR diagnostic assay used as a benchmark for TRACE; it has a higher (worse) limit of detection, making TRACE approximately 40 times more sensitive under comparable conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="99.5% ACCURACY ACROSS DIVERSE SAMPLE TYPES">
      <data key="d0">99.5% ACCURACY ACROSS DIVERSE SAMPLE TYPES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A clinical validation result showing that TRACE achieves 99.5% diagnostic accuracy across multiple clinical specimen types when compared to a reference standard such as qPCR.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POINT-OF-CARE TRACE ASSAYS MEET ASSURED CRITERIA">
      <data key="d0">POINT-OF-CARE TRACE ASSAYS MEET ASSURED CRITERIA</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation statement indicating that point-of-care implementations of TRACE satisfy WHO ASSURED criteria (Affordable, Sensitive, Specific, User-friendly, Rapid and robust, Equipment-free, Deliverable to end-users), supporting its suitability for decentralized testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FIVEFOLD REDUCED REPORT TIME IN OUTPATIENT SETTINGS">
      <data key="d0">FIVEFOLD REDUCED REPORT TIME IN OUTPATIENT SETTINGS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A comparative performance outcome showing that TRACE provides diagnostic reports about five times faster than qPCR in outpatient clinical settings while maintaining comparable accuracy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIMULTANEOUS DETECTION OF PATHOGEN AND HOST GENES">
      <data key="d0">SIMULTANEOUS DETECTION OF PATHOGEN AND HOST GENES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A demonstrated capability of TRACE to co-detect pathogen DNA and host gene targets as internal controls at comparable sensitivity, addressing the lack of internal controls in many CRISPR assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT ASSAY RUN FORMAT">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT ASSAY RUN FORMAT</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The operational format of TRACE in which amplification and CRISPR-based detection occur together in a single reaction vessel, simplifying workflow and enabling rapid, on-site testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THERMALLY PROGRAMMED ASSAY RUN">
      <data key="d0">THERMALLY PROGRAMMED ASSAY RUN</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A thermally regulated run protocol used by TRACE to asynchronously coordinate amplification and CRISPR detection steps through controlled temperature changes, improving sensitivity and speed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTI-GUIDE RNA CAS12A ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">MULTI-GUIDE RNA CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas12a biosensing platform that uses multiple guide RNAs to detect pathogen DNA with high sensitivity, designed to favor trans-cleavage over cis-cleavage for signal generation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUSTAINABLE AND PORTABLE CRISPR-BASED DIAGNOSTICS FOR HIGH-SENSITIVITY MPOX DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">SUSTAINABLE AND PORTABLE CRISPR-BASED DIAGNOSTICS FOR HIGH-SENSITIVITY MPOX DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A sustainable, portable CRISPR-based diagnostic platform intended for high-sensitivity detection of Mpox in field or point-of-care settings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ULTRASENSITIVE SINGLE-STEP CRISPR DETECTION OF MONKEYPOX VIRUS IN MINUTES WITH A VEST-POCKET DIAGNOSTIC DEVICE">
      <data key="d0">ULTRASENSITIVE SINGLE-STEP CRISPR DETECTION OF MONKEYPOX VIRUS IN MINUTES WITH A VEST-POCKET DIAGNOSTIC DEVICE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A vest-pocket CRISPR diagnostic device that enables ultrasensitive, single-step detection of Monkeypox virus within minutes, optimized for rapid point-of-care testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_1,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MPOX">
      <data key="d0">MPOX</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Mpox, the disease associated with infection by Monkeypox virus (MPXV), referenced as the target condition for high-sensitivity CRISPR-based diagnostic platforms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_1,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-BASED DIAGNOSTIC PLATFORMS">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-BASED DIAGNOSTIC PLATFORMS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A general class of CRISPR-based nucleic acid diagnostic systems that can achieve single-molecule detection and discriminate single-nucleotide polymorphisms under optimal conditions, and whose modular design allows rapid reconfiguration to detect different pathogens by changing the guide RNA.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GUIDE RNA (GRNA)">
      <data key="d0">GUIDE RNA (GRNA)</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">The programmable RNA component of CRISPR diagnostics that defines sequence-specific target recognition; swapping the gRNA allows rapid reconfiguration of CRISPR diagnostic platforms to detect different pathogen nucleic acid sequences.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE-MOLECULE RESOLUTION DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE-MOLECULE RESOLUTION DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">An extremely low limit of detection achievable by some CRISPR-based diagnostic platforms under optimal conditions, enabling detection of individual nucleic acid molecules.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE-NUCLEOTIDE POLYMORPHISM DISCRIMINATION">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE-NUCLEOTIDE POLYMORPHISM DISCRIMINATION</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">A specificity profile of certain CRISPR-based diagnostic assays that allows them to distinguish nucleic acid targets differing by only a single nucleotide, providing high diagnostic accuracy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR/CAS12A-BASED PLATFORM FOR RAPID AND VISUAL NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR/CAS12A-BASED PLATFORM FOR RAPID AND VISUAL NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Cas12aVDet, a CRISPR-Cas12a-based single-tube diagnostic platform that combines nucleic acid amplification with Cas12a-mediated detection to enable rapid, visual nucleic acid readout while reducing workflow complexity and contamination risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_4,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTAMINATION-FREE VISUAL DETECTION OF SARS-COV-2 WITH CRISPR/CAS12A">
      <data key="d0">CONTAMINATION-FREE VISUAL DETECTION OF SARS-COV-2 WITH CRISPR/CAS12A</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas12a-based closed-tube diagnostic assay for visual detection of SARS-CoV-2, designed to minimize cross-contamination and support point-of-care testing by integrating amplification and detection in a sealed format.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_4,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_5,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR/CAS12A">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR/CAS12A</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">A Cas12a-based CRISPR effector system used for visual nucleic acid detection, here applied to SARS-CoV-2 in point-of-care assays and one-pot formats. | A Cas12b CRISPR effector used in TRACE as a temperature-activated detection enzyme that forms a ribonucleoprotein complex with guide RNA to recognize amplified targets and cleave reporter probes. | A Cas12a CRISPR effector nuclease employed in CRISPR–Cas12a assays to detect influenza A viral RNA/DNA via guide-RNA-directed collateral cleavage. | A CRISPR-associated nuclease (Cas12a) used in CRISPR-based molecular assays for sensitive detection of HPAI avian influenza viral nucleic acids, typically following an upstream amplification step. | A CRISPR-Cas12a effector system used as the detection mechanism in an on-site and visual assay for H5 subtype avian influenza virus following RT-RPA amplification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_5,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_30,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">CRISPR/CAS12B,CRISPR–CAS12A,CRISPR CAS12A,CRISPR/CAS12A</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS13-BASED DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">CAS13-BASED DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR detection approach using Cas13 effectors to recognize and cleave SARS-CoV-2 RNA within streamlined inactivation–amplification–detection workflows.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RECOMBINASE POLYMERASE AMPLIFICATION (RPA)">
      <data key="d0">RECOMBINASE POLYMERASE AMPLIFICATION (RPA)</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">An isothermal nucleic acid amplification method whose temperature range and buffer system are compatible with one-pot CRISPR reactions, enabling integrated amplification and detection. | Recombinase polymerase amplification (RPA) is a rapid, low-temperature isothermal amplification method combined with lateral flow strip readout for detecting OXA-48-like carbapenemase genes in Enterobacterales. It is suitable for point-of-care and field-deployable biosensing and can serve as a pre-amplification module in airborne pathogen biosurveillance assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b</data>
      <data key="d6">RECOMBINASE POLYMERASE AMPLIFICATION (RPA)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT ASSAY STRATEGY WITH SIMULTANEOUS NAA AND CRISPR REACTIONS">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT ASSAY STRATEGY WITH SIMULTANEOUS NAA AND CRISPR REACTIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A one-pot CRISPR diagnostic configuration in which nucleic acid amplification (NAA) and CRISPR detection occur concurrently under isothermal conditions in a single reaction vessel.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SHERLOCK ONE-POT TESTING">
      <data key="d0">SHERLOCK ONE-POT TESTING</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A SHERLOCK-based one-pot CRISPR assay for SARS-CoV-2 that integrates isothermal amplification and CRISPR-mediated detection in a single tube. | A one-pot CRISPR-based diagnostic platform (SHERLOCK) for SARS-CoV-2 detection that integrates nucleic acid amplification and CRISPR-mediated detection in a single reaction for rapid, field-ready testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_5,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_30,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">SHERLOCK ONE-POT TESTING</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STREAMLINED INACTIVATION, AMPLIFICATION, AND CAS13-BASED DETECTION OF SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d0">STREAMLINED INACTIVATION, AMPLIFICATION, AND CAS13-BASED DETECTION OF SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An integrated SARS-CoV-2 diagnostic workflow combining sample inactivation, nucleic acid amplification, and Cas13-based CRISPR detection in a streamlined format.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_5,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAST AND SENSITIVE DETECTION OF SARS-COV-2 RNA USING SUBOPTIMAL PROTOSPACER ADJACENT MOTIFS FOR CAS12A">
      <data key="d0">FAST AND SENSITIVE DETECTION OF SARS-COV-2 RNA USING SUBOPTIMAL PROTOSPACER ADJACENT MOTIFS FOR CAS12A</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A Cas12a-based assay design that leverages suboptimal protospacer adjacent motifs (PAMs) to achieve fast and sensitive detection of SARS-CoV-2 RNA under isothermal conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_5,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_30,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GRNAS WITH SUBOPTIMAL OR MISSING PROTOSPACER ADJACENT MOTIF RECOGNITION SEQUENCES">
      <data key="d0">GRNAS WITH SUBOPTIMAL OR MISSING PROTOSPACER ADJACENT MOTIF RECOGNITION SEQUENCES</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">Guide RNAs engineered with suboptimal or absent PAM recognition sequences to intentionally reduce Cas12a-mediated cleavage efficiency, thereby minimizing interference with nucleic acid amplification while still enabling CRISPR-based detection in one-pot assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MODIFIED GRNAS WITH PHOTODEGRADABLE MOLECULAR LOCKS">
      <data key="d0">MODIFIED GRNAS WITH PHOTODEGRADABLE MOLECULAR LOCKS</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">Guide RNAs that incorporate photodegradable molecular locks to block Cas12a/gRNA target recognition until light activation, providing temporal control over Cas12a activity so that nucleic acid amplification can proceed before CRISPR detection is triggered.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_6,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT CRISPR–NAA ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT CRISPR–NAA ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Single-reaction CRISPR-based detection assays in which nucleic acid amplification and Cas12a-mediated detection occur concurrently and share the same amplicon pool, requiring careful tuning of Cas12a activity (e.g., via suboptimal PAM gRNAs or photodegradable locks) to avoid depleting amplification products.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO-STEP CRISPR ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">TWO-STEP CRISPR ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">CRISPR-based detection workflows in which nucleic acid amplification and CRISPR detection are performed in separate steps; by physically or temporally separating amplification from Cas12a activity, these assays typically achieve higher sensitivity than one-pot CRISPR–NAA assays. | Two-step RPA/CRISPR assay workflows in which RPA amplification is performed first, followed by a separate CRISPR-based detection step; they serve as a reference for analytical sensitivity when comparing TRACE. | A rapid, approximately 1-hour CRISPR-based molecular diagnostic performed on-site on targeted environmental air samples to detect high-pathogenicity avian influenza (HPAI) as a Tier 2 step in a modular, tiered farm surveillance stack.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_6,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">TWO-STEP RPA/CRISPR ASSAYS,ON-SITE CRISPR ASSAY</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENCE OF QUENCHED REPORTERS">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENCE OF QUENCHED REPORTERS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A fluorescent reporter signal that is initially quenched and becomes unmasked (increased fluorescence) when Cas-mediated trans-cleavage cleaves the reporter oligonucleotide in CRISPR-based assays, serving as the readout for target detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONVENTIONAL CRISPR-BASED ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">CONVENTIONAL CRISPR-BASED ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Standard CRISPR diagnostic assay formats that couple nucleic acid amplification with Cas nuclease trans-cleavage of quenched fluorescent reporters to detect target nucleic acids.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS12A WITH PHOTODEGRADABLE LOCKED GRNA">
      <data key="d0">CAS12A WITH PHOTODEGRADABLE LOCKED GRNA</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas12a diagnostic assay configuration that uses photodegradable molecular lock–modified gRNAs to temporally control Cas12a activation and reduce interference with nucleic acid amplification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS VARIANTS WITH SELECTIVE TRANS-CLEAVAGE SPECIFICITIES">
      <data key="d0">CAS VARIANTS WITH SELECTIVE TRANS-CLEAVAGE SPECIFICITIES</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">Engineered or selected Cas proteins whose collateral (trans) nuclease activity preferentially cleaves specific reporter substrates, enabling multiplex CRISPR assays but still exhibiting some off-target cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTIPLEX CRISPR ASSAYS USING SELECTIVE CAS VARIANTS">
      <data key="d0">MULTIPLEX CRISPR ASSAYS USING SELECTIVE CAS VARIANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Multiplex nucleic acid detection assays that rely on Cas variants with selective trans-cleavage specificities to distinguish multiple targets via different reporter substrates in a single reaction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION (NAA) REACTION">
      <data key="d0">NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION (NAA) REACTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A generic nucleic acid amplification step (e.g., PCR or isothermal amplification) used upstream or in one-pot with CRISPR-based detection to increase target copy number.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW SPECIFICITY TRANS-CLEAVAGE ACTIVITY OF CAS PROTEINS">
      <data key="d0">LOW SPECIFICITY TRANS-CLEAVAGE ACTIVITY OF CAS PROTEINS</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The promiscuous collateral nuclease activity of Cas proteins (such as Cas12a or Cas13a) that, once activated by target binding, cleaves many non-target reporter molecules, enabling signal amplification but limiting multiplexing due to low substrate specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OFF-TARGET CLEAVAGE ACTIVITY IN MULTIPLEX ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">OFF-TARGET CLEAVAGE ACTIVITY IN MULTIPLEX ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">Undesired cleavage of non-intended reporter substrates by Cas variants in multiplex CRISPR assays, which reduces target resolution and complicates assay interpretation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTIPLEX DETECTION IN CRISPR DIAGNOSTICS">
      <data key="d0">MULTIPLEX DETECTION IN CRISPR DIAGNOSTICS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">CRISPR-based diagnostic configurations designed to detect multiple nucleic acid targets simultaneously, which are challenged by overlapping trans-cleavage activities and off-target reporter cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THERMALLY REGULATED ASYNCHRONOUS CRISPR-ENHANCED (TRACE) ONE-POT DUPLEX ASSAY PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">THERMALLY REGULATED ASYNCHRONOUS CRISPR-ENHANCED (TRACE) ONE-POT DUPLEX ASSAY PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A thermally regulated one-pot duplex CRISPR diagnostic platform that asynchronously controls nucleic acid amplification and CRISPR activity using RPA, Cas effectors, and an ssRNA gRNA inhibitor to enhance detection of low-abundance nucleic acid targets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE-PLEX TRACE">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE-PLEX TRACE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A single-target implementation of the TRACE platform configured to detect one nucleic acid target per reaction, demonstrated to sensitively detect MPXV nucleic acid.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INTEGRATED RPA/CAS12A TRACE VARIANT">
      <data key="d0">INTEGRATED RPA/CAS12A TRACE VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A TRACE variant that integrates RPA amplification with Cas12a-based CRISPR detection in a single reaction to enable duplex detection, including a host gene internal control for sample quality.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS EFFECTERS">
      <data key="d0">CAS EFFECTERS</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">A general reference to CRISPR-Cas effector enzymes employed in the TRACE platform whose activity is thermally regulated to separate amplification and detection phases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SSRNA GRNA INHIBITOR">
      <data key="d0">SSRNA GRNA INHIBITOR</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A single-stranded RNA guide-RNA-based inhibitor used in TRACE to modulate Cas effector activity in a temperature-dependent manner, enabling temporal segregation of amplification and CRISPR detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="2.5 MPXV TARGET COPIES/TEST">
      <data key="d0">2.5 MPXV TARGET COPIES/TEST</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The analytical sensitivity of the Single-plex TRACE assay, indicating it can reliably detect approximately 2.5 copies of MPXV target nucleic acid per test.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STANDARD TWO-STEP CRISPR METHODS">
      <data key="d0">STANDARD TWO-STEP CRISPR METHODS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Conventional CRISPR diagnostic workflows that separate nucleic acid amplification and CRISPR detection into two distinct steps, used as a benchmark for sensitivity against TRACE.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HOST GENE">
      <data key="d0">HOST GENE</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A host-derived gene target co-detected in the integrated RPA/Cas12a TRACE variant as an internal control to assess sample quality and adequacy of nucleic acid content.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUMEROUS CLINICAL SAMPLE TYPES">
      <data key="d0">NUMEROUS CLINICAL SAMPLE TYPES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation context in which the lateral flow TRACE assay is compared to qPCR across a variety of clinical sample types, establishing its diagnostic performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LATERAL FLOW READOUT">
      <data key="d0">LATERAL FLOW READOUT</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The visual signal generated on a lateral flow strip by the lateral flow TRACE assay, enabling equipment-free detection consistent with REASSURED criteria. | A strip-based immunochromatographic readout format used with isothermal amplification products to provide simple, field-deployable detection of influenza targets. | A reporter format where CRISPR detection products are visualized on a lateral-flow strip, enabling rapid, equipment-free interpretation. | A paper-based, visually interpretable signal format implemented in SHERLOCKv2, where CRISPR-mediated reporter cleavage is converted into a band pattern on a lateral flow strip for point-of-care use. | A colorimetric lateral flow strip signal used by the DETECTR platform to provide rapid, point-of-care visual detection of SARS-CoV-2 from RNA extracts.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_8,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">LATERAL FLOW-BASED READOUT,LATERAL-FLOW READOUT,LATERAL FLOW READOUT,LATERAL FLOW STRIP READOUT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A one-pot CRISPR-based biosensor platform that integrates asynchronous recombinase polymerase amplification (RPA) and CRISPR/Cas12b reactions in a lyophilized format for sensitive nucleic acid target detection directly from lysed clinical samples, designed for point-of-care use with lateral flow strips or a portable device.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_13,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_15,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_32,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_46,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LATERAL FLOW TRACE ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">LATERAL FLOW TRACE ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A lateral-flow implementation of the TRACE assay that provides a visual band-based readout on assay strips, designed to meet ASSURED (affordable, sensitive, specific, user-friendly, rapid, equipment-free, and delivered) criteria for point-of-care testing, including in resource-limited settings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GRNA">
      <data key="d0">GRNA</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">The guide RNA that complexes with Cas12b in the TRACE assay to form a ribonucleoprotein complex, providing sequence-specific recognition of the amplified nucleic acid target.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_12,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_13,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_38,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_39,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_42,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_46,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SSRNA BLOCKER">
      <data key="d0">SSRNA BLOCKER</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A single-stranded RNA blocker that anneals to the guide RNA at low temperature in TRACE, preventing Cas12b:gRNA ribonucleoprotein assembly and suppressing target cleavage during the amplification stage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_13,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LYSED CLINICAL SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">LYSED CLINICAL SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sample preparation step in which clinical specimens are lysed to release nucleic acids, enabling their direct addition to lyophilized TRACE reagents without further extraction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO-STAGE INCUBATION PROCEDURE">
      <data key="d0">TWO-STAGE INCUBATION PROCEDURE</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The defined incubation protocol in TRACE consisting of a low-temperature stage that favors RPA and suppresses Cas12b activity, followed by a high-temperature stage that inactivates RPA and activates Cas12b for target detection and probe cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW-TEMPERATURE STAGE">
      <data key="d0">LOW-TEMPERATURE STAGE</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The first stage of the TRACE incubation protocol, operated at a lower temperature to promote efficient RPA-based target amplification while ssRNA blocker and temperature effects suppress Cas12b:gRNA complex formation and target cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-TEMPERATURE STAGE">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-TEMPERATURE STAGE</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The second stage of the TRACE incubation protocol, operated at a higher temperature that inactivates RPA, promotes gRNA:ssRNA dissociation, and enables Cas12b ribonucleoprotein formation for efficient target recognition and probe degradation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LATERAL FLOW ASSAY STRIPS">
      <data key="d0">LATERAL FLOW ASSAY STRIPS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A visual lateral-flow readout format used by TRACE to display positive or negative results as bands on assay strips, translating Cas12b-mediated probe cleavage into an easily interpretable signal. | Lateral flow strips that provide a visual, colorimetric readout as the reporter signal for TRACE LFA, translating CRISPR-mediated cleavage events into a point-of-care detectable signal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">LATERAL FLOW STRIPS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PORTABLE DEVICE">
      <data key="d0">PORTABLE DEVICE</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A portable readout device used with TRACE to visualize and interpret the reporter signal generated by probe degradation, enabling electronic readout for point-of-care deployment outside centralized laboratories.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PROBE DEGRADATION">
      <data key="d0">PROBE DEGRADATION</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The Cas12b-mediated cleavage of reporter probes upon target recognition in TRACE, generating the biochemical reporter signal that underlies both visual and device-based assay readouts and contributes to high assay sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ASSURED CRITERIA">
      <data key="d0">ASSURED CRITERIA</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A set of performance and implementation benchmarks—affordable, sensitive, specific, user-friendly, rapid, equipment-free, and delivered—that lateral flow TRACE assays are designed to fulfill for point-of-care testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A two-step Cas12a-based detection assay in which RPA amplification of the MPXV J2L region and Cas12a-based detection occur in separate steps, achieving high sensitivity (2.5 copies/test) and high specificity. | A two-step nucleic acid detection platform that first uses RPA-based preamplification of target DNA and then a Cas12a-based CRISPR fluorescence reaction to detect the amplified product.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">TWO-STEP CRISPR/CAS12A ASSAY</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A single-reaction (one-pot) Cas12a assay combining RPA amplification and Cas12a detection in the same mixture for MPXV J2L targets, with reduced sensitivity (100 copies/test) due to Cas12a-mediated inhibition of RPA. | An integrated CRISPR-based nucleic acid detection platform combining RPA amplification and Cas12b-mediated detection in a single reaction, using sequential 37 °C and 60 °C incubations to separate amplification and cleavage activities and enhance sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.99</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">ONE-POT RPA/CAS12B ASSAY</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MPXV J2L GRNA">
      <data key="d0">MPXV J2L GRNA</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A guide RNA sequence complementary to a conserved region within the MPXV J2L gene, designed to direct Cas12a to monkeypox virus targets with broad strain coverage and high specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MONKEYPOX VIRUS (MPXV)">
      <data key="d0">MONKEYPOX VIRUS (MPXV)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Monkeypox virus (MPXV), the target pathogen for the described Cas12a-RPA TRACE assays, including detection in low viral load specimens such as urine and early-stage infection samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="2.5 COPIES/TEST">
      <data key="d0">2.5 COPIES/TEST</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The analytical limit of detection achieved by the two-step Cas12a assay for MPXV J2L targets, corresponding to 2.5 copies of target per test.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="100 COPIES/TEST">
      <data key="d0">100 COPIES/TEST</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The analytical limit of detection of the optimized one-pot Cas12a assay for MPXV J2L targets, corresponding to 100 copies of target per test, indicating reduced sensitivity. | The analytical sensitivity of the optimized one-pot RPA/Cas12b assay, indicating it can detect as few as 10 target copies per test.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">10 COPIES/TEST</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IN-SILICO SPECIFICITY PROFILE FOR MPXV J2L TARGETING">
      <data key="d0">IN-SILICO SPECIFICITY PROFILE FOR MPXV J2L TARGETING</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">An in-silico specificity profile showing that RPA primers and gRNA targeting a conserved MPXV J2L region provide 99.6% coverage of reported MPXV strains with complete predicted specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMPIRICAL PERFORMANCE PROFILE OF TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">EMPIRICAL PERFORMANCE PROFILE OF TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">An empirical performance profile of the two-step Cas12a assay demonstrating high analytical sensitivity (2.5 copies/test) and strong specificity in experimental characterization.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS12B">
      <data key="d0">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas effector nuclease with both cis- and trans-cleavage activity and a broad operating temperature range (reported 31–59 °C), used here as the detection nuclease in CRISPR/Cas12b reactions and in the one-pot RPA/Cas12b assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_12,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_13,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_32,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_41,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_44,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_45,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_46,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SSRNA GRNA BLOCKER">
      <data key="d0">SSRNA GRNA BLOCKER</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A single-stranded RNA oligonucleotide designed to bind or sequester the guide RNA, acting as a blocker that reduces formation of the Cas12b–gRNA RNP and thereby modulates Cas12b cis- and trans-cleavage activity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REPORTER SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">REPORTER SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A fluorescence-based readout generated by Cas12b trans-cleavage of a labeled reporter substrate; weak signal at the end of the first incubation stage indicates low but detectable Cas12b activity during early amplification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_12,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO-POT RPA/CAS12A ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">TWO-POT RPA/CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A benchmark two-step CRISPR diagnostic platform that performs RPA amplification and Cas12a-based detection in separate reactions, used as a comparator for TRACE assay sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="37 °C AMPLIFICATION PHASE">
      <data key="d0">37 °C AMPLIFICATION PHASE</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The low-temperature (37 °C) amplification interval in the one-pot TRACE assay during which target nucleic acids are amplified while Cas12b activity is intentionally attenuated by ssRNA blockers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WEAK REPORTER SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">WEAK REPORTER SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A low-level fluorescence reporter signal observed at the end of the first stage of the TRACE assay, indicating residual Cas12b activity despite attempted attenuation. | Volatile gas output engineered as a non-visual reporter from biosensors, enabling nondisruptive monitoring of gene expression and hazard detection in opaque environments such as soil.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">GAS REPORTER SIGNAL</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STRONG SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">STRONG SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A robust fluorescence reporter signal observed in optimized TRACE assays employing appropriately designed ssRNA blockers, indicating effective target detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
