      <data key="d0">2.5 J2L GENE COPIES/TEST LOD</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">A limit of detection metric for the TRACE assay, indicating that 2.5 copies of the MPXV J2L gene per test can be detected under the optimized 40-minute protocol.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="0.5 FFU/ML OF MPXV VIRAL PARTICLES LOD">
      <data key="d0">0.5 FFU/ML OF MPXV VIRAL PARTICLES LOD</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">A functional limit of detection for the TRACE assay expressed as 0.5 focus-forming units per milliliter of MPXV viral particles under the optimized protocol.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="10–10,000 COPIES/TEST LINEAR RANGE">
      <data key="d0">10–10,000 COPIES/TEST LINEAR RANGE</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The reported broad linear detection range of the TRACE assay, spanning from 10 to 10,000 target copies per test, defining its quantitative dynamic range.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="≥5 COPIES/TEST SENSITIVITY (95% DETECTION)">
      <data key="d0">≥5 COPIES/TEST SENSITIVITY (95% DETECTION)</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">A practical sensitivity threshold at which the TRACE assay detected MPXV DNA in at least 95% (19 of 20) of synthetic replicate samples, corresponding to 5 or more copies per test.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NO CROSS-REACTIVITY WITH OTHER ORTHOPOXVIRUSES OR SIMILAR PATHOGENS">
      <data key="d0">NO CROSS-REACTIVITY WITH OTHER ORTHOPOXVIRUSES OR SIMILAR PATHOGENS</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The specificity profile of the TRACE assay, indicating no detectable cross-reactivity with other orthopoxviruses or pathogens that can produce similar clinical symptoms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BENCH VALIDATION WITH SYNTHETIC REPLICATE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">BENCH VALIDATION WITH SYNTHETIC REPLICATE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Validation experiments in which the TRACE assay was evaluated using synthetic replicate samples spiked with MPXV DNA to characterize sensitivity, linear range, and detection reliability.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="40-MIN TWO-TEMPERATURE ASSAY RUN">
      <data key="d0">40-MIN TWO-TEMPERATURE ASSAY RUN</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The optimized TRACE assay run protocol consisting of 10 minutes at 37 °C followed by 30 minutes at 60 °C, under which the reported limits of detection were achieved.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="400 NM CAS12B RNP CONCENTRATION">
      <data key="d0">400 NM CAS12B RNP CONCENTRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An assay condition in the optimized TRACE protocol, using 400 nM Cas12b ribonucleoprotein complex to maximize signal and signal-to-noise while balancing cost and performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="1:4 GRNA:SSRNA BLOCKER RATIO">
      <data key="d0">1:4 GRNA:SSRNA BLOCKER RATIO</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An optimized reagent ratio in the TRACE assay, where gRNA and ssRNA blocker 1-S14 are used at a 1:4 ratio to achieve improved signal and signal-to-noise.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POLY T REPORTER">
      <data key="d0">POLY T REPORTER</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A poly-thymidine fluorescent reporter oligonucleotide used in the TRACE assay; its cleavage by activated Cas12b generates the measurable signal, optimized for signal-to-noise.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MPXV TRACE ASSAY ANALYTICAL CHARACTERIZATION">
      <data key="d0">MPXV TRACE ASSAY ANALYTICAL CHARACTERIZATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Analytical validation of the MPXV TRACE assay, including signal kinetics with serially diluted MPXV J2L gene standards, reproducibility across replicate low-copy standards, and specificity against other orthopoxviruses and related pathogens. | Clinical validation of the MPXV TRACE assay using 118 MPXV-positive and 80 MPXV-negative clinical samples, including analysis by specimen type, HIV infection status, time-to-threshold versus qPCR Ct, and run time to achieve 95% sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">MPXV TRACE ASSAY CLINICAL CHARACTERIZATION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MPXV J2L GENE STANDARDS">
      <data key="d0">MPXV J2L GENE STANDARDS</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">Serially diluted monkeypox virus J2L gene DNA standards, ranging down to 0–10 copies per test, used to characterize TRACE signal kinetics and reproducibility and to define the assay’s analytical sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE SPECIFICITY PROFILE FOR MPXV">
      <data key="d0">TRACE SPECIFICITY PROFILE FOR MPXV</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">Specificity profile of the MPXV TRACE assay demonstrating discrimination of MPXV from other orthopoxviruses and related pathogens, based on mean ± SD signal measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ISOTHERMAL RAPID AMPLIFICATION (RPA AND ANALOGS)">
      <data key="d0">ISOTHERMAL RAPID AMPLIFICATION (RPA AND ANALOGS)</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Recombinase polymerase amplification and related multienzyme isothermal rapid amplification systems that are compatible upstream amplification methods for the TRACE platform.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROLLING CIRCLE AMPLIFICATION (RCA)">
      <data key="d0">ROLLING CIRCLE AMPLIFICATION (RCA)</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A divergent isothermal amplification system, rolling circle amplification, demonstrated to be compatible with TRACE for nucleic acid signal generation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL KINETICS">
      <data key="d0">TRACE FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL KINETICS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Time-resolved fluorescence signal (mean ± SD) generated by the TRACE assay in response to serially diluted MPXV J2L gene standards, used to assess analytical performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE POSITIVE RATE IN CLINICAL SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">TRACE POSITIVE RATE IN CLINICAL SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The proportion of MPXV-positive calls (positive rate) and associated TRACE signal levels observed across 118 MPXV-positive and 80 MPXV-negative clinical samples and across specific specimen types.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE TIME-TO-THRESHOLD (TT)">
      <data key="d0">TRACE TIME-TO-THRESHOLD (TT)</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The time required for the TRACE fluorescence signal to cross a predefined threshold (Tt), used as a quantitative readout and compared against qPCR Ct values, including assignment of Tt=40 for a false-negative urine sample.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE F18 SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">TRACE F18 SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The TRACE fluorescence signal intensity measured at 18 minutes (F18), used to assess correlation with qPCR Ct values in MPXV-positive specimens. | The fluorescence readout of the TRACE assay, including the value at 18 minutes (F18), used to determine positivity based on a threshold derived from no-template controls and to correlate with qPCR Ct values.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">TRACE SIGNAL</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE RUN TIME FOR 95% SENSITIVITY">
      <data key="d0">TRACE RUN TIME FOR 95% SENSITIVITY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Operational run time of the TRACE assay required to achieve 95% diagnostic sensitivity in rash swab, saliva, and combined specimen types.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="40-MIN PROTOCOL">
      <data key="d0">40-MIN PROTOCOL</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The specific 40-minute operational run of the TRACE assay used in the diagnostic performance evaluation on biobank samples from MPXV-positive and MPXV-negative patients.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RASH SWAB SPECIMENS">
      <data key="d0">RASH SWAB SPECIMENS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">TRACE assay runs performed on rash swab specimens from MPXV cases, used to assess time to 95% sensitivity and to compare longitudinal TRACE and qPCR results in a representative case.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SALIVA SPECIMENS">
      <data key="d0">SALIVA SPECIMENS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">TRACE assay runs performed on saliva specimens from MPXV cases, evaluated alongside rash swabs to determine time to 95% sensitivity and to track serial results relative to qPCR.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ALL SPECIMEN TYPES">
      <data key="d0">ALL SPECIMEN TYPES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The combined set of TRACE assay runs across all evaluated specimen types (including rash swab, saliva, and other sample types) used to determine the overall run time required to achieve 95% sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NTC GROUP (0 COPY/TEST)">
      <data key="d0">NTC GROUP (0 COPY/TEST)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The no-template control group containing 0 copies per test, used to define the positive TRACE signal threshold as mean + 3×SD, establishing the baseline for analytical specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIAGNOSTIC PERFORMANCE EVALUATION WITH 118 QPCR-POSITIVE AND 80 NEGATIVE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">DIAGNOSTIC PERFORMANCE EVALUATION WITH 118 QPCR-POSITIVE AND 80 NEGATIVE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A blinded clinical validation of the optimized 40-minute TRACE assay using 118 qPCR-positive (Ct ≤ 40) biobank samples from 27 confirmed MPXV cases and 80 samples from 31 MPXV-negative patients to estimate sensitivity, specificity, and predictive values.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="99% SENSITIVITY AND 100% SPECIFICITY">
      <data key="d0">99% SENSITIVITY AND 100% SPECIFICITY</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The diagnostic performance profile of the TRACE assay in the described validation, with 99% sensitivity and 100% specificity (with 95% confidence intervals), indicating one misclassified weakly positive urine sample and no false positives.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE">
      <data key="d0">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">TRACE is a CRISPR-based diagnostic assay platform used in this study to detect MPXV infection in clinical specimens, generating a time-to-threshold positive signal for rapid identification of infected individuals.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_18,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE LFA">
      <data key="d0">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">TRACE LFA is a lateral-flow assay format of the TRACE diagnostic platform, used on-site to detect MPXV infection in symptomatic individuals as a rapid, point-of-care test.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_22,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_23,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE DUPLEX">
      <data key="d0">TRACE DUPLEX</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">TRACE duplex is a duplex version of the TRACE assay platform applied to remaining nucleic acid and/or specimens to detect MPXV, enabling simultaneous detection or internal control measurement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TIME-TO-THRESHOLD (TT) FOR POSITIVE SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">TIME-TO-THRESHOLD (TT) FOR POSITIVE SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The time-to-threshold (Tt) for positive signal is the kinetic reporter metric in TRACE assays, representing the time required for the assay signal to cross a predefined positivity threshold in MPXV patient samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POSITIVE SIGNAL IN MPXV PATIENT SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">POSITIVE SIGNAL IN MPXV PATIENT SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The positive signal in MPXV patient samples is the detectable assay output generated by TRACE when MPXV nucleic acid is present, which is quantified using time-to-threshold analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="11 MIN TIME-TO-THRESHOLD FOR 70% OF SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">11 MIN TIME-TO-THRESHOLD FOR 70% OF SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The observation that 70% (83/118) of MPXV-positive patient samples reached the TRACE positive signal threshold within 11 minutes, characterizing the assay’s speed in clinical specimens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RETROSPECTIVE STUDY OF 74 PARTICIPANTS">
      <data key="d0">RETROSPECTIVE STUDY OF 74 PARTICIPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A retrospective validation cohort of 74 participants diagnosed as MPXV or non-MPXV cases by qPCR, whose remaining nucleic acid and/or specimens were tested by TRACE, TRACE LFA, and TRACE duplex.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PROSPECTIVE STUDY OF 28 SYMPTOMATIC INDIVIDUALS">
      <data key="d0">PROSPECTIVE STUDY OF 28 SYMPTOMATIC INDIVIDUALS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A prospective validation cohort of 28 symptomatic individuals with epidemiological histories consistent with MPXV infection, whose samples were analyzed in parallel by on-site TRACE LFA and off-site central laboratory qPCR.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REMAINING NUCLEIC ACID FROM THE QPCR ANALYSIS">
      <data key="d0">REMAINING NUCLEIC ACID FROM THE QPCR ANALYSIS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Remaining nucleic acid from the qPCR analysis, derived from clinical specimens, which is reused as prepared input material for TRACE, TRACE LFA, and TRACE duplex assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLINICAL SPECIMENS USED FOR TRACE-BASED ANALYSES">
      <data key="d0">CLINICAL SPECIMENS USED FOR TRACE-BASED ANALYSES</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Processed clinical specimens from participants that serve as the source material for TRACE, TRACE LFA, and TRACE duplex analyses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OFF-SITE CENTRAL LABORATORY QPCR TEST">
      <data key="d0">OFF-SITE CENTRAL LABORATORY QPCR TEST</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The specific off-site central laboratory execution of the qPCR assay on prospectively collected samples, providing reference diagnostic results for MPXV infection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ON-SITE TRACE LFA RUN ON PROSPECTIVE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">ON-SITE TRACE LFA RUN ON PROSPECTIVE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The set of on-site TRACE LFA assay executions performed on prospectively obtained samples from symptomatic individuals to detect MPXV at the point of care.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REPORTER SIGNAL AT 18-MIN TRACE ENDPOINT">
      <data key="d0">REPORTER SIGNAL AT 18-MIN TRACE ENDPOINT</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The reporter signal measured at the 18-minute TRACE endpoint (after 10 min at 37 °C and 8 min at 60 °C) is the assay readout used to determine TRACE positivity and to infer semi-quantitative MPXV viral load based on its strong negative correlation with qPCR Ct values (r = -0.8036, p &lt; 0.0001 for Ct 25–40).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="18-MIN TRACE PROTOCOL">
      <data key="d0">18-MIN TRACE PROTOCOL</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The 18-min TRACE protocol (10 min at 37 °C followed by 8 min at 60 °C) is the standardized assay run configuration adopted for all subsequent experiments. It was selected because it correctly identified 95% (95% CI, 89–98) of tested samples, meeting the specified MPXV detection guideline.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GUIDELINE FOR MPXV DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">GUIDELINE FOR MPXV DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The guideline for MPXV detection, issued by the China National Medical Products Administration Center, specifies performance criteria (such as ≥95% correct identification of positive samples) for poxvirus nucleic acid detection reagents and serves as the external benchmark that the 18-min TRACE assay configuration meets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE LATERAL FLOW ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">TRACE LATERAL FLOW ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A TRACE-based lateral flow biosensor platform adapted for point-of-care MPXV detection, integrating sample processing, analysis, and visual readout without expensive equipment, and using lyophilized reagents stable at ambient temperature.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MPXV LYSIS PROTOCOL">
      <data key="d0">MPXV LYSIS PROTOCOL</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A 5-minute, temperature-agnostic lysis protocol for MPXV that releases viral DNA from specimens mixed with lysis buffer, generating crude lysates suitable for direct input into the one-pot TRACE assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LYSIS BUFFER">
      <data key="d0">LYSIS BUFFER</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">The buffer used in the MPXV lysis protocol; specimens are mixed with this buffer to achieve efficient viral DNA release and produce crude lysates compatible with TRACE.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRUDE LYSATES">
      <data key="d0">CRUDE LYSATES</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Unpurified lysates generated after the MPXV lysis protocol, which can be directly used as input to the one-pot TRACE assay while still yielding robust signal intensities.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE RESULTS">
      <data key="d0">TRACE RESULTS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Outputs from individual TRACE assay runs that quantify MPXV levels in serial rash and saliva specimens and are compared with qPCR trajectories.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QPCR RESULTS">
      <data key="d0">QPCR RESULTS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Quantitative PCR assay outputs used as a reference standard to compare with TRACE results for monitoring MPXV viral load dynamics in clinical specimens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE SAMPLE PROCESSING STUDIES">
      <data key="d0">TRACE SAMPLE PROCESSING STUDIES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Sample processing optimization and robustness studies that identified the 5-minute temperature-agnostic MPXV lysis protocol and demonstrated compatibility with diverse specimen types and conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE VS QPCR COMPARISON IN TWO MPXV CASES">
      <data key="d0">TRACE VS QPCR COMPARISON IN TWO MPXV CASES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation comparison using serial rash and saliva specimens from two MPXV cases, showing corresponding viral load trajectories between TRACE and qPCR and supporting TRACE’s use for rapid MPXV load tracking.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LYOPHILIZED TRACE REAGENTS">
      <data key="d0">LYOPHILIZED TRACE REAGENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Pre-formulated, lyophilized reagents for the TRACE assay that are stable at ambient temperature and support deployment of the lateral flow format in resource-limited, point-of-care settings. | Freeze-dried assay components used to extend shelf stability of CRISPR diagnostic reagents under ambient conditions, simplifying storage and transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">LYOPHILIZED REAGENTS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RASH AND SALIVA SPECIMENS">
      <data key="d0">RASH AND SALIVA SPECIMENS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Clinical rash and saliva samples collected serially from MPXV cases, used as input specimens for both TRACE and qPCR to track viral load trajectories.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PLASMA AND URINE SPECIMENS">
      <data key="d0">PLASMA AND URINE SPECIMENS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Low viral titer plasma and urine samples used in sample processing studies to demonstrate that the MPXV lysis protocol and TRACE assay are compatible with diverse specimen types.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MPXV J2L GENE">
      <data key="d0">MPXV J2L GENE</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">The J2L gene region of MPXV used as the specific nucleic acid target for the TRACE assay; assay performance is characterized in terms of MPXV J2L gene copies per test, implying targeting by assay guides/primers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LYOPHILIZED TRACE REAGENT FORMULATIONS">
      <data key="d0">LYOPHILIZED TRACE REAGENT FORMULATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Five lyophilized formulations of TRACE assay reagents that are reconstituted before use, enabling improved storage stability and simplified preparation for the lateral flow test.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NATIVE (LIQUID) TRACE REAGENTS">
      <data key="d0">NATIVE (LIQUID) TRACE REAGENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">The original, non-lyophilized liquid TRACE reagents used as a reference condition when comparing performance with lyophilized formulations at low MPXV J2L gene copy numbers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.58</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LIQUID TRACE REAGENTS STORED AT 37 °C">
      <data key="d0">LIQUID TRACE REAGENTS STORED AT 37 °C</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Liquid TRACE reagents stored at 37 °C for defined times before use, used to assess the impact of elevated-temperature storage on assay performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DNA EXTRACTS">
      <data key="d0">DNA EXTRACTS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Purified nucleic acid isolates obtained from the same clinical specimens as the crude lysates, used as a benchmark input for the TRACE assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="25 MPXV J2L GENE COPIES/TEST">
      <data key="d0">25 MPXV J2L GENE COPIES/TEST</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">A low target level of 25 MPXV J2L gene copies per test used to evaluate TRACE assay performance across five lyophilized reagent formulations and native liquid reagents, probing near-limit detection behavior. | A higher target level of 1000 MPXV J2L gene copies per test used to assess the stability and performance of lyophilized formulation 4 versus liquid TRACE reagents after storage at 37 °C.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">1000 MPXV J2L GENE COPIES/TEST</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RASH SWAB LYSATES FROM AN MPXV PATIENT">
      <data key="d0">RASH SWAB LYSATES FROM AN MPXV PATIENT</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A TRACE assay run using lysates from rash swab samples of an MPXV-positive patient, yielding positive LFA results. | A TRACE assay run using lysates from rash swab samples of a non-MPXV patient, serving as a negative control and yielding non-reactive or background LFA results.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">RASH SWAB LYSATES FROM A NON-MPXV PATIENT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TECHNICAL REPLICATES OF MPXV J2L GENE STANDARDS">
      <data key="d0">TECHNICAL REPLICATES OF MPXV J2L GENE STANDARDS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">An assay validation experiment using three technical replicates per concentration of MPXV J2L gene standards to characterize reproducibility and quantitative performance of the TRACE LFA.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPARISON OF TRACE SIGNAL WITH LYSATES AND DNA EXTRACTS OF 18 CLINICAL SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">COMPARISON OF TRACE SIGNAL WITH LYSATES AND DNA EXTRACTS OF 18 CLINICAL SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation study comparing TRACE signal from crude lysates versus DNA extracts across 18 clinical samples from three MPXV patients, showing comparable signal intensities and positivity rates.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPARISON OF TRACE SIGNAL ACROSS SAMPLE TYPES">
      <data key="d0">COMPARISON OF TRACE SIGNAL ACROSS SAMPLE TYPES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation analysis stratifying TRACE signal by clinical sample type (rash, oral, rectal swabs, saliva, urine, plasma) to evaluate assay robustness across diverse specimen matrices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPARISON OF LYOPHILIZED TRACE REAGENT FORMULATIONS WITH NATIVE TRACE REAGENTS">
      <data key="d0">COMPARISON OF LYOPHILIZED TRACE REAGENT FORMULATIONS WITH NATIVE TRACE REAGENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation experiment in which samples containing 25 MPXV J2L gene copies/test are analyzed using five lyophilized TRACE reagent formulations and native liquid TRACE reagents to compare formulation performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPARISON OF LYOPHILIZED AND LIQUID TRACE REAGENTS STORED AT 37 °C">
      <data key="d0">COMPARISON OF LYOPHILIZED AND LIQUID TRACE REAGENTS STORED AT 37 °C</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation study comparing TRACE signal when 1000 MPXV J2L gene copies/test are analyzed using lyophilized formulation 4 versus liquid TRACE reagents after storage at 37 °C for varying times.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE ASSAY SPECIFICITY FOR MPXV">
      <data key="d0">TRACE ASSAY SPECIFICITY FOR MPXV</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed specificity profile of the TRACE LFA, supported by contrasting results between MPXV-positive and non-MPXV rash swab lysates, indicating discrimination between infected and non-infected patients.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.63</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE FLUORESCENT ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">TRACE FLUORESCENT ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A TRACE-based fluorescent CRISPR diagnostic platform used to classify MPXV-positive and MPXV-negative clinical sample lysates, achieving 100% overall sensitivity and 100% specificity in the described blinded evaluation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SENSITIVITY 86% (95% CI, 65–97) FOR SAMPLES WITH CT ≥ 31">
      <data key="d0">SENSITIVITY 86% (95% CI, 65–97) FOR SAMPLES WITH CT ≥ 31</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation metric for the TRACE LFA indicating 86% sensitivity (95% confidence interval 65–97) for MPXV-positive clinical samples with qPCR Ct values ≥ 31, when samples were split into tertiles by Ct.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SENSITIVITY 95% (95% CI, 85–97) FOR ALL MPXV-POSITIVE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">SENSITIVITY 95% (95% CI, 85–97) FOR ALL MPXV-POSITIVE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">An overall sensitivity metric for the TRACE LFA across all MPXV-positive clinical samples, reporting 95% sensitivity with a 95% confidence interval of 85–97. | The overall sensitivity performance of the TRACE fluorescent assay for MPXV-positive clinical samples, reported as 100% with a 95% confidence interval of 94–100.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">SENSITIVITY 100% (95% CI, 94–100) FOR MPXV-POSITIVE SAMPLES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECIFICITY 100% (95% CI, 92–100) FOR MPXV CLASSIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">SPECIFICITY 100% (95% CI, 92–100) FOR MPXV CLASSIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">A specificity profile indicating that both the TRACE fluorescent assay and TRACE LFA showed 100% specificity with a 95% confidence interval of 92–100 when classifying MPXV-positive and MPXV-negative clinical samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BLINDED ANALYSIS OF 55 MPXV-POSITIVE AND 47 MPXV-NEGATIVE SAMPLE LYSATES">
      <data key="d0">BLINDED ANALYSIS OF 55 MPXV-POSITIVE AND 47 MPXV-NEGATIVE SAMPLE LYSATES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A blinded retrospective evaluation in which 55 MPXV-positive and 47 MPXV-negative clinical sample lysates were analyzed in parallel using the TRACE fluorescent assay and TRACE LFA to determine diagnostic performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QPCR ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">QPCR ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A central laboratory quantitative PCR assay used as the reference molecular test for MPXV infection status in the study. Rash swab aliquots are transported to the lab and analyzed by this qPCR assay, with a sample-to-answer time of roughly 3 hours.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PROSPECTIVE PILOT STUDY INTEGRATING TRACE LFA INTO AN OUTPATIENT WORKFLOW">
      <data key="d0">PROSPECTIVE PILOT STUDY INTEGRATING TRACE LFA INTO AN OUTPATIENT WORKFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A prospective pilot validation study in which TRACE LFA was integrated into an outpatient clinical workflow. Rash swabs from 28 symptomatic individuals at high epidemiological risk for MPXV were split: one aliquot tested on-site by TRACE LFA and the other sent to a central lab for qPCR. The study assessed concordance, feasibility, and turnaround time for rapid MPXV case identification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PAIRED TRACE LFA AND CENTRAL LABORATORY QPCR TEST RESULTS FOR 28 OUTPATIENTS">
      <data key="d0">PAIRED TRACE LFA AND CENTRAL LABORATORY QPCR TEST RESULTS FOR 28 OUTPATIENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The specific set of 28 paired assay runs comprising TRACE LFA and central laboratory qPCR results for outpatients evaluated for suspected MPXV infection. These runs showed full concordance, correctly classifying 11 MPXV-positive and 17 non-MPXV cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PREVIOUS CRISPR-BASED MPXV ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">PREVIOUS CRISPR-BASED MPXV ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Previously reported CRISPR-based assay platforms for detecting monkeypox virus (MPXV), generally slower and less sensitive than TRACE LFA and typically lacking comprehensive clinical validation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TIME RESOLUTION-BASED TRACE DUPLEX ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">TIME RESOLUTION-BASED TRACE DUPLEX ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A duplex version of the TRACE assay that uses time-resolved detection intervals to distinguish signals from a host internal control and the MPXV pathogen target, enabling identification of potential false negatives caused by poor sample quality.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS/GRNA COMPLEXES">
      <data key="d0">CAS/GRNA COMPLEXES</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">General CRISPR effector–guide RNA complexes that recognize distinct dsDNA sequences; in multiplex CRISPR assays they often exhibit substantial cross-talk, limiting straightforward multiplexing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS VARIANTS WITH SELECTIVE TRANS-CLEAVAGE SEQUENCE PREFERENCES">
      <data key="d0">CAS VARIANTS WITH SELECTIVE TRANS-CLEAVAGE SEQUENCE PREFERENCES</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">Different Cas effector variants chosen or engineered for distinct trans-cleavage sequence preferences, used in attempts to reduce cross-talk between Cas/gRNA complexes in multiplex CRISPR assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS12A/GRNA RNP SPECIFIC FOR A HOST GENE">
      <data key="d0">CAS12A/GRNA RNP SPECIFIC FOR A HOST GENE</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A Cas12a ribonucleoprotein complex containing a guide RNA targeting a host gene, incorporated into the RPA stage of TRACE as an internal control to report on sample quality and detect potential false negatives.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RPA STAGE OF TRACE">
      <data key="d0">RPA STAGE OF TRACE</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">The recombinase polymerase amplification (RPA) step within the TRACE assay workflow, during which both host and pathogen targets are amplified at 37 °C and the Cas12a/host-gene RNP internal control is active.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPREHENSIVE CLINICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE LFA">
      <data key="d0">COMPREHENSIVE CLINICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A comprehensive clinical validation study supporting TRACE LFA, systematically evaluating its diagnostic performance for MPXV detection and distinguishing it from other CRISPR-based MPXV assays that lack such validation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DUPLEX INTERNAL-CONTROL CONCEPT">
      <data key="d0">DUPLEX INTERNAL-CONTROL CONCEPT</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The conceptual design of a duplex assay that includes a host-derived internal control to identify false-negative results arising from poor sample quality, motivated by issues observed during the COVID-19 pandemic.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENT SIGNAL INCREASES (ΔF1 AND LATER SIGNALS)">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENT SIGNAL INCREASES (ΔF1 AND LATER SIGNALS)</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescent reporter signal increases detected during the first and second stages of the TRACE duplex assay (ΔF1 and subsequent signals), used to temporally distinguish host internal control detection from pathogen target detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE DUPLEX ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">TRACE DUPLEX ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A two-stage CRISPR-based duplex detection platform (TRACE) that uses temperature-programmed activation and inactivation of RPA and distinct Cas enzymes to simultaneously detect MPXV J2L and the human RNase P internal control in a single-reporter fluorescence system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_29,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_44,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DUPLEX RPA REACTIONS">
      <data key="d0">DUPLEX RPA REACTIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Recombinase polymerase amplification reactions configured in duplex format during the first 37 °C stage of the TRACE assay to co-amplify both RNase P and MPXV J2L targets prior to CRISPR-based detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MPXV J2L">
      <data key="d0">MPXV J2L</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The J2L gene region of Monkeypox virus (MPXV), serving as the specific viral target sequence whose detection is reported as ΔF2 signal in the second, 64 °C stage of the TRACE duplex assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RNASE P GENE">
      <data key="d0">RNASE P GENE</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">The human RNase P gene used as a host internal control target in the TRACE duplex assay; its detection during the first 37 °C stage produces the ΔF1 fluorescent signal, confirming sample adequacy and proper assay function.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="293 CELL EXTRACTS">
      <data key="d0">293 CELL EXTRACTS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Cell extracts from human 293 cells used as a source of endogenous RNase P target in assay characterization, providing a prepared sample matrix for defining RNase P-positive ΔF1/ΔF2 signatures.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ΔF1 SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">ΔF1 SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The increment in fluorescent signal measured during the first 37 °C stage of the TRACE duplex assay, attributed to Cas12a-mediated detection of the RNase P gene and used to indicate host internal control positivity. | The increment in fluorescent signal measured during the second, higher-temperature (64 °C) stage of the TRACE duplex assay, attributed primarily to Cas12b/gRNA complexes detecting the MPXV J2L target.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">ΔF2 SIGNAL</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DUPLEX TRACE ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">DUPLEX TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A two-stage CRISPR-Cas12a-based duplex TRACE assay that simultaneously detects human RNase P and MPXV J2L gene targets. It uses RPA in stage-1 and temperature-controlled Cas12a activity (60 °C then 64 °C) to generate stage-specific fluorescent readouts (ΔF1 for RNase P and ΔF2 for MPXV J2L).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RNASE P GENE LOD: 10 COPIES/TEST">
      <data key="d0">RNASE P GENE LOD: 10 COPIES/TEST</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The analytical limit of detection of the duplex TRACE assay for the human RNase P gene, determined to be 10 copies per test under the optimized two-stage, 30-minute-per-stage protocol.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MPXV J2L GENE PERFORMANCE AT 10 COPIES/TEST">
      <data key="d0">MPXV J2L GENE PERFORMANCE AT 10 COPIES/TEST</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">Performance of the duplex TRACE assay for the MPXV J2L gene at an input level of 10 copies per test in cell lysate samples, where 95% of samples (19/20) were detected; this approximates the practical limit of detection for the MPXV J2L target under the tested conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CELL LYSATE SAMPLES SPIKED WITH 10 COPIES/TEST MPXV J2L GENE">
      <data key="d0">CELL LYSATE SAMPLES SPIKED WITH 10 COPIES/TEST MPXV J2L GENE</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">An analytical validation experiment in which cell lysate samples were spiked with 10 copies/test of the MPXV J2L gene to assess the duplex TRACE assay’s detection performance, achieving 95% positivity (19/20).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="12 MPXV-POSITIVE AND 11 MPXV-NEGATIVE CLINICAL SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">12 MPXV-POSITIVE AND 11 MPXV-NEGATIVE CLINICAL SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A clinical validation panel of 12 MPXV-positive and 11 MPXV-negative samples used to evaluate duplex TRACE assay performance, measuring RNase P (ΔF1) and MPXV J2L (ΔF2) signals to distinguish positive from negative cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="293 CELL NUCLEIC ACID EXTRACTS SPIKED WITH MPXV J2L DNA">
      <data key="d0">293 CELL NUCLEIC ACID EXTRACTS SPIKED WITH MPXV J2L DNA</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A spiking study using 293 cell nucleic acid extracts (103 ng/μL) with varying MPXV J2L DNA concentrations to characterize normalized ΔF1 and ΔF2 signals and target positivity rates for the duplex TRACE assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="293 CELL NUCLEIC ACID EXTRACTS">
      <data key="d0">293 CELL NUCLEIC ACID EXTRACTS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Nucleic acid extracts derived from 293 cells, prepared at 103 ng/μL and used as a matrix spiked with MPXV J2L DNA to assess duplex TRACE assay performance and signal normalization.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CELL LYSATE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">CELL LYSATE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Lysed cell samples used as a prepared matrix for spiking with defined MPXV J2L gene copy numbers (e.g., 10 copies/test) to evaluate the duplex TRACE assay’s sensitivity and detection rate.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENT CLEAVAGE SIGNAL (ΔF1)">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENT CLEAVAGE SIGNAL (ΔF1)</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The normalized ΔF1 fluorescent reporter signal in the duplex TRACE assay, primarily associated with RNase P target detection and used to quantify internal control amplification and assay performance. | Stage-1 fluorescence change attributed to the RNase P gene in the TRACE assay, used to judge clinical sample quality and RNase P-positivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL (ΔF1)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PORTABLE TRACE DUPLEX DEVICE">
      <data key="d0">PORTABLE TRACE DUPLEX DEVICE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A small, inexpensive, portable instrument developed to perform and analyze TRACE duplex assays. It uses an efficient thermal film for precise temperature control and a single-source, single-detector optics module, is powered by a rechargeable power bank, and is controlled via a smartphone for real-time data acquisition and automated analysis in low-resource settings.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QPCR SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">QPCR SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A conventional quantitative PCR instrument used as a reference platform to read TRACE duplex assay signals and provide benchmark classifications for comparison with the portable TRACE duplex device.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_28,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="J2L GENE TARGET">
      <data key="d0">J2L GENE TARGET</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">The MPXV J2L gene region that serves as the viral detection target in the TRACE duplex assay, producing a J2L signal at low copy numbers (e.g., 10 copies/test) in spiked lysate and MPXV-positive clinical specimens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RNASE P GENE TARGET">
      <data key="d0">RNASE P GENE TARGET</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">The human RNase P gene region used as an internal control target in the TRACE duplex assay to assess sample adequacy and nucleic acid integrity, detected in 22 of 23 rash swab samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="10 COPIES/TEST J2L GENE CONCENTRATION">
      <data key="d0">10 COPIES/TEST J2L GENE CONCENTRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">A tested low-concentration level of the J2L gene (10 copies per test) at which the TRACE duplex assay detected signal in 95% (19/20) of spiked cell lysate samples, representing a practical sensitivity benchmark for the J2L target under these conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE FLUORESCENT SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">TRACE FLUORESCENT SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The optical (likely fluorescent) reporter signal generated by the TRACE duplex assay for both J2L and RNase P channels, measured by the qPCR system and the portable TRACE duplex device using a single excitation source and detector.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RASH SWAB PROCESSING">
      <data key="d0">RASH SWAB PROCESSING</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">The collection, preservation, and preparation of rash swab specimens prior to TRACE duplex testing; inadequate processing is suggested by an RNase P-negative sample with very weak J2L signal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BIOBANK SAMPLE PROCESSING">
      <data key="d0">BIOBANK SAMPLE PROCESSING</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">The pre-analytical handling and preparation of 23 biobank samples that were tested with the TRACE duplex assay on both the qPCR system and the portable device, enabling platform comparison.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BENCH VALIDATION WITH SPIKED CELL LYSATE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">BENCH VALIDATION WITH SPIKED CELL LYSATE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">An analytical validation experiment in which cell lysate samples were spiked with 10 copies/test of the J2L gene target, yielding detectable J2L signal in 95% (19/20) of samples and establishing assay sensitivity for J2L.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLINICAL VALIDATION WITH RASH SWABS">
      <data key="d0">CLINICAL VALIDATION WITH RASH SWABS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A clinical validation study using 23 rash swab specimens from individuals with suspected MPXV infection, in which RNase P was detected in 22/23 samples and J2L signal was positive in all 12 MPXV-positive samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPARATIVE VALIDATION ON 23 BIOBANK SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">COMPARATIVE VALIDATION ON 23 BIOBANK SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A comparative validation in which TRACE duplex assay signals obtained on a qPCR system and on the portable TRACE duplex device for 23 biobank samples were highly similar and yielded concordant classifications, demonstrating agreement between platforms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE DUPLEX ASSAY RUN ON 23 BIOBANK SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">TRACE DUPLEX ASSAY RUN ON 23 BIOBANK SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A specific execution of the TRACE duplex assay on 23 biobank samples, with readout on both the qPCR system and the portable TRACE duplex device to generate data for comparative validation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE DUPLEX ASSAY RUN ON 23 RASH SWABS">
      <data key="d0">TRACE DUPLEX ASSAY RUN ON 23 RASH SWABS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A specific execution of the TRACE duplex assay on 23 rash swab specimens from suspected MPXV cases, producing RNase P and J2L signals used in the clinical validation analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE DUPLEX ASSAY DEVICE">
      <data key="d0">TRACE DUPLEX ASSAY DEVICE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A compact, portable TRACE duplex assay device with dual detection ports, smartphone communication, and external power bank support for on-site nucleic acid testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE ASSAY (J2L TARGET)">
      <data key="d0">TRACE ASSAY (J2L TARGET)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">TRACE-based nucleic acid detection assay targeting the J2L gene, run on clinical and biobank samples using the portable device.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAM SINGLE-PROBE OPTICAL DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">FAM SINGLE-PROBE OPTICAL DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescent reporter signal based on a single FAM-labeled probe detected by the device’s simplified optical system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DUAL DETECTION PORTS">
      <data key="d0">DUAL DETECTION PORTS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">The device’s two optical detection ports that allow simultaneous analysis of two samples using FAM-based fluorescence.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMARTPHONE-BASED ASSAY SETUP AND MONITORING">
      <data key="d0">SMARTPHONE-BASED ASSAY SETUP AND MONITORING</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Workflow in which a smartphone is used to configure the assay, monitor signals in real time, and interpret results from the TRACE device.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
