      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AMPLIFICATION STEP FOR SARS-COV-2 NUCLEIC ACIDS">
      <data key="d0">AMPLIFICATION STEP FOR SARS-COV-2 NUCLEIC ACIDS</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Nucleic acid amplification used upstream of CRISPR-based detection in streamlined SARS-CoV-2 assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MINIMIZED INTERFERENCE OF TARGET AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">MINIMIZED INTERFERENCE OF TARGET AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">An amplification strategy designed to reduce adverse interactions between amplification and CRISPR detection reactions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VISUAL READOUT REPORTER SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">VISUAL READOUT REPORTER SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A visually interpretable signal (e.g., fluorescence or color change) produced by CRISPR-based detection platforms such as Cas12aVDet.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PORTABLE MULTIPLEXED REPORTER SIGNALS">
      <data key="d0">PORTABLE MULTIPLEXED REPORTER SIGNALS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Reporter outputs from multiplexed CRISPR platforms that can be read in portable formats for field or point-of-care use.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT DUPLEX TRACE ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT DUPLEX TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A one-pot duplex configuration of the TRACE assay that performs simultaneous detection of a pathogen gene (J2L) and a host gene (RNase P) in a single reaction, enabling internal sample quality control in clinical and point-of-care testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GRNAS THAT RECOGNIZE SEQUENCES WITH SUBOPTIMAL OR MISSING PROTOSPACER ADJACENT MOTIFS">
      <data key="d0">GRNAS THAT RECOGNIZE SEQUENCES WITH SUBOPTIMAL OR MISSING PROTOSPACER ADJACENT MOTIFS</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">Guide RNAs designed to bind target sequences that have suboptimal or missing protospacer adjacent motifs, thereby attenuating Cas cis-cleavage activity to preserve target amplicons and improve one-pot NAA/CRISPR assay performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT NAA/CRISPR ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT NAA/CRISPR ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Integrated nucleic acid amplification and CRISPR-based detection assays performed in a single reaction vessel, whose performance can be limited by Cas cis-cleavage of target amplicons and improved by guide RNA design strategies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="J2L">
      <data key="d0">J2L</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A pathogen gene target, likely from an orthopoxvirus such as monkeypox virus, detected by the one-pot duplex TRACE assay as the pathogen-specific nucleic acid marker.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RNASE P">
      <data key="d0">RNASE P</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A human host gene used as an internal control for sample quality in diagnostic assays, including the one-pot duplex TRACE assay, indicating adequate sample collection and presence of amplifiable host nucleic acid.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS CIS-CLEAVAGE ACTIVITY">
      <data key="d0">CAS CIS-CLEAVAGE ACTIVITY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The target-specific (cis) cleavage activity of Cas enzymes on their bound nucleic acid substrates during an assay run, which in one-pot NAA/CRISPR assays can prematurely degrade amplicons and reduce amplification efficiency.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS TRANS-CLEAVAGE REACTION THAT GENERATES ASSAY SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">CAS TRANS-CLEAVAGE REACTION THAT GENERATES ASSAY SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The collateral (trans) cleavage activity of activated Cas enzymes on reporter molecules, producing a measurable signal (e.g., fluorescence) that indicates target detection in CRISPR-based assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTIPLEXED CRISPR-BASED MICROFLUIDIC PLATFORM FOR CLINICAL TESTING OF RESPIRATORY VIRUSES AND IDENTIFICATION OF SARS-COV-2 VARIANTS">
      <data key="d0">MULTIPLEXED CRISPR-BASED MICROFLUIDIC PLATFORM FOR CLINICAL TESTING OF RESPIRATORY VIRUSES AND IDENTIFICATION OF SARS-COV-2 VARIANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A microfluidic CRISPR-based platform capable of multiplexed clinical testing of respiratory viruses and identification of SARS-CoV-2 variants, using Cas effectors for high-throughput respiratory pathogen diagnostics.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLINICAL TO POINT-OF-CARE APPLICATIONS">
      <data key="d0">CLINICAL TO POINT-OF-CARE APPLICATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Use of the one-pot duplex TRACE assays across centralized clinical laboratories and decentralized point-of-care settings to evaluate diagnostic performance in real-world use.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RETROSPECTIVE AND PROSPECTIVE COHORTS OF CLINICAL SPECIMENS">
      <data key="d0">RETROSPECTIVE AND PROSPECTIVE COHORTS OF CLINICAL SPECIMENS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Validation cohorts consisting of previously collected (retrospective) and newly collected (prospective) clinical specimens used to assess the diagnostic accuracy and robustness of the one-pot duplex TRACE assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GRNA BLOCKING SEQUENCE">
      <data key="d0">GRNA BLOCKING SEQUENCE</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A guide RNA-associated blocking sequence used in the TRACE assay to delay or prevent Cas12b–gRNA complex activation during the nucleic acid amplification phase, thereby helping to temporally segregate amplification from Cas12b trans-cleavage in a one-pot reaction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_32,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT CRISPR ASSAYS WITH ATTENUATED CIS-CLEAVAGE">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT CRISPR ASSAYS WITH ATTENUATED CIS-CLEAVAGE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A class of one-pot CRISPR diagnostic assay formats that reduce Cas cis-cleavage activity to balance amplicon accumulation and consumption, but consequently also diminish trans-cleavage activity, limiting assay kinetics and sensitivity compared with two-step assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SHERLOCK V2 PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">SHERLOCK V2 PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">The SHERLOCK V2 platform is a multiplex CRISPR-based detection system that achieves four-plex detection by using multiple Cas proteins with distinct substrate preferences, thereby reducing interference from nonspecific trans-cleavage in multiplex assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS PROTEINS WITH DISTINCT SUBSTRATE PREFERENCES">
      <data key="d0">CAS PROTEINS WITH DISTINCT SUBSTRATE PREFERENCES</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">A set of Cas effector proteins with differing substrate preferences, employed in the SHERLOCK V2 platform to enable multiplexed detection while minimizing cross-reactive trans-cleavage between channels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT CRISPR ASSAYS THAT DETECT MPXV">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT CRISPR ASSAYS THAT DETECT MPXV</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Previously reported one-pot CRISPR assay configurations designed to detect monkeypox virus (MPXV) in a single reaction mixture, used as comparators for sensitivity and complexity relative to TRACE.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GRNA PHOTOACTIVATION STRATEGIES">
      <data key="d0">GRNA PHOTOACTIVATION STRATEGIES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">CRISPR assay designs that use photoactivatable guide RNAs to induce Cas12a activity only after completion of nucleic acid amplification, providing temporal control of nuclease activity as an alternative to the thermal and blocking-sequence strategy used in TRACE.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO RPA ANALOGS">
      <data key="d0">TWO RPA ANALOGS</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Two RPA-like isothermal amplification chemistries that are experimentally shown to be compatible with TRACE and operate in a similar temperature range and mechanistic framework as RPA.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROLLING CIRCLE AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">ROLLING CIRCLE AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Rolling circle amplification is an isothermal amplification method that generates long DNA products from circular templates and is demonstrated to be compatible with TRACE at temperatures similar to RPA. | Rolling circle amplification implemented via padlock probe ligation and phi29 polymerase extension to generate long DNA products from the MPXV J2L target prior to Cas12b detection. | An isothermal nucleic acid amplification method used in a lateral flow assay with capture ligand-modified oligonucleotides for nucleic acid detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b</data>
      <data key="d6">RCA,ROLLING CIRCLE AMPLIFICATION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENZYMATIC RECOMBINASE AMPLIFICATION (ERA)">
      <data key="d0">ENZYMATIC RECOMBINASE AMPLIFICATION (ERA)</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Enzymatic recombinase amplification (ERA) is an isothermal amplification assay operating at 37–42 °C, similar to RPA, and is proposed as a potentially compatible amplification method for TRACE.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STRAND DISPLACEMENT AMPLIFICATION (SDA)">
      <data key="d0">STRAND DISPLACEMENT AMPLIFICATION (SDA)</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Strand displacement amplification (SDA) is an isothermal amplification technique that efficiently amplifies target DNA at RPA-like temperatures and is considered potentially useful in TRACE assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUCLEIC ACID SEQUENCE-BASED AMPLIFICATION ASSAYS (NASBA)">
      <data key="d0">NUCLEIC ACID SEQUENCE-BASED AMPLIFICATION ASSAYS (NASBA)</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Nucleic acid sequence-based amplification (NASBA) is an isothermal amplification method that operates in the 37–42 °C range and is suggested as a candidate amplification strategy for integration into TRACE.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE DUPLEX ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">TRACE DUPLEX ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-based duplex nucleic acid detection platform that uses Cas12a and Cas12b in sequential temperature stages to distinguish signals from different target amplicons, reducing cross-reactivity without spatial separation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RNASE P GRNA">
      <data key="d0">RNASE P GRNA</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A guide RNA that targets the RNase P nucleic acid sequence and uniquely satisfies Cas12a binding criteria in the TRACE duplex assay, enabling Cas12a-mediated detection of the RNase P target during the first stage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="J2L GRNA">
      <data key="d0">J2L GRNA</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A Cas12b-specific guide RNA targeting the J2L sequence; in the TRACE duplex assay, it is sequestered by an ssDNA inhibitor during the first stage to attenuate Cas12b/gRNA complex formation and activity, allowing temporal separation of detection signals.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RNASE P TARGET">
      <data key="d0">RNASE P TARGET</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The RNase P nucleic acid target amplicon detected by Cas12a in the first stage of the TRACE duplex assay, serving as one of the distinct targets in the duplex detection scheme.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="J2L TARGET AMPLICON">
      <data key="d0">J2L TARGET AMPLICON</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The nucleic acid target amplicon corresponding to the J2L sequence that is detected by Cas12b in the second stage of the TRACE duplex assay once the J2L gRNA is released from ssDNA inhibition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISTINCT TARGET AMPLICONS">
      <data key="d0">DISTINCT TARGET AMPLICONS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The different nucleic acid amplicons (including RNase P and J2L targets) that are discriminated by TRACE duplex assays across two temperature stages, providing the basis for duplex detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIGNAL PRODUCED IN THE FIRST ASSAY STAGE">
      <data key="d0">SIGNAL PRODUCED IN THE FIRST ASSAY STAGE</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The reporter signal measured during the first temperature stage of the TRACE duplex assay, which exclusively reflects Cas12a-mediated recognition of the RNase P target due to Cas12b suppression.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REPORTER SIGNAL PRODUCED IN THE SECOND STAGE">
      <data key="d0">REPORTER SIGNAL PRODUCED IN THE SECOND STAGE</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The reporter signal measured during the second temperature stage of the TRACE duplex assay, which reflects activation of Cas12b and detection of its J2L target amplicon once the J2L gRNA is no longer inhibited.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SHERLOCK V2 SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">SHERLOCK V2 SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A multiplexed CRISPR-based detection platform (SHERLOCK V2) whose general framework is cited as a model that TRACE could be adapted to in order to increase multiplexing capacity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS VARIANTS">
      <data key="d0">CAS VARIANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">A general reference to newly discovered or engineered CRISPR effector enzymes with distinctive temperature preferences and trans-cleavage specificities that could be used to expand multiplexing in future TRACE assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="J2L TARGET">
      <data key="d0">J2L TARGET</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The nucleic acid target sequence at the J2L locus recognized by J2L-specific Cas12b/gRNA complexes in the TRACE assay; used as a host gene internal control to assess specimen quality.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE REPORTER">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE REPORTER</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A single type of reporter molecule used in the TRACE assay, which simplifies the design of the portable reader and reduces manufacturing cost while still supporting internal control detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VALIDATION STUDIES">
      <data key="d0">VALIDATION STUDIES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Experimental validation work for the TRACE assay, including assessment of coverage of reported MPXV strains; currently limited by geographic homogeneity of sample collection sites, which may not reflect the diversity of circulating MPXV lineages.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INTERNAL CONTROLS FOR SPECIMEN QUALITY">
      <data key="d0">INTERNAL CONTROLS FOR SPECIMEN QUALITY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The internal control strategy in the TRACE assay that uses concurrent detection of a host gene target (e.g., the J2L locus) to assess specimen quality, addressing the common lack of internal controls in many CRISPR assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PORTABLE DETECTION DEVICE">
      <data key="d0">PORTABLE DETECTION DEVICE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">The hardware device used to run the TRACE assay, incorporating a simple fluorescence detection module and designed to minimize equipment costs, though it currently lacks an active cooling system which limits throughput and usable range.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIMPLE FLUORESCENCE DETECTION MODULE">
      <data key="d0">SIMPLE FLUORESCENCE DETECTION MODULE</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The fluorescence-based signal detection component integrated into the portable detection device, used to measure the fluorescent reporter output generated by the TRACE assay upon target detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="99.5% DIAGNOSTIC ACCURACY">
      <data key="d0">99.5% DIAGNOSTIC ACCURACY</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The reported diagnostic performance of the TRACE assay, indicating approximately 99.5% overall diagnostic accuracy relative to qPCR in the evaluated setting.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE ASSAY VALIDATION IN LARGE INDEPENDENT COHORTS">
      <data key="d0">TRACE ASSAY VALIDATION IN LARGE INDEPENDENT COHORTS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The recommended validation of TRACE diagnostic performance in large, independent cohorts comprising distinct specimen types to confirm and generalize the reported accuracy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE ASSAY VALIDATION ACROSS DIVERSE MPXV LINEAGES">
      <data key="d0">TRACE ASSAY VALIDATION ACROSS DIVERSE MPXV LINEAGES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Planned or recommended validation of TRACE using MPXV lineages from a wider range of endemic geographic sites to assess assay reliability with genetically diverse strains.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POST-HOC TIME-TO-POSITIVITY ANALYSIS">
      <data key="d0">POST-HOC TIME-TO-POSITIVITY ANALYSIS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A post-hoc analytical approach used to estimate the time required for TRACE to achieve positive results, developed from a limited number of clinical specimens and potentially not fully representative of broader clinical diversity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE WORKFLOW TIME (25 MIN SAMPLE-TO-RESULT)">
      <data key="d0">TRACE WORKFLOW TIME (25 MIN SAMPLE-TO-RESULT)</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The reported end-to-end workflow time for TRACE, approximately 25 minutes from sample to result, substantially faster than the ~3-hour workflow for qPCR.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QPCR WORKFLOW TIME (3 HOURS)">
      <data key="d0">QPCR WORKFLOW TIME (3 HOURS)</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The approximate 3-hour sample-to-result workflow time for qPCR, used as a benchmark to highlight the faster turnaround of TRACE.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMARTPHONE CONNECTIVITY">
      <data key="d0">SMARTPHONE CONNECTIVITY</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The capability of the TRACE system to connect to a smartphone, enabling real-time data analysis and facilitating on-site epidemic surveillance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SENSOR OPTIMIZATION AND NOISE REDUCTION ALGORITHMS">
      <data key="d0">SENSOR OPTIMIZATION AND NOISE REDUCTION ALGORITHMS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Proposed signal processing and sensor optimization approaches to reduce signal variability in future versions of the TRACE portable detection device.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACTIVE COOLING SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">ACTIVE COOLING SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A proposed addition to the portable detection device to extend its usable temperature range and improve throughput and utility in real-world applications.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">TRACE ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">CRISPR-based diagnostic assays referred to as TRACE, designed for rapid detection of human pathogens (including MPXV), supporting duplex applications with internal quality control and use across clinical laboratories and resource-limited settings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE ASSAY FORMATS">
      <data key="d0">TRACE ASSAY FORMATS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">The benchtop and point-of-care implementations of the TRACE CRISPR diagnostic system, optimized for sensitive detection of MPXV in diverse patient specimen lysates and intended for translation from bench to bedside.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BENCHTOP TRACE ASSAY FORMATS">
      <data key="d0">BENCHTOP TRACE ASSAY FORMATS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Benchtop runs of TRACE assays used to detect MPXV in lysates of diverse patient specimen types, with performance compared against qPCR on nucleic acid extracts.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POINT-OF-CARE TRACE ASSAY FORMATS">
      <data key="d0">POINT-OF-CARE TRACE ASSAY FORMATS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Point-of-care runs of TRACE assays that sensitively detect MPXV in patient specimen lysates and are designed for rapid diagnosis in decentralized or resource-limited settings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RPA KIT">
      <data key="d0">RPA KIT</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A recombinase polymerase amplification (RPA) kit used as an isothermal nucleic acid amplification method that can be coupled to CRISPR-based TRACE assays for rapid pathogen detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTIENZYME ISOTHERMAL RAPID AMPLIFICATION KIT">
      <data key="d0">MULTIENZYME ISOTHERMAL RAPID AMPLIFICATION KIT</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A multienzyme isothermal rapid amplification kit providing an isothermal nucleic acid amplification method that can be integrated into CRISPR-based diagnostic workflows such as TRACE assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RECOMBINASE-AIDED AMPLIFICATION KIT">
      <data key="d0">RECOMBINASE-AIDED AMPLIFICATION KIT</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A recombinase-aided amplification (RAA) kit that performs isothermal nucleic acid amplification and can serve as a pre-amplification step for CRISPR-based detection platforms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AAPCAS12B">
      <data key="d0">AAPCAS12B</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">A Cas12b CRISPR effector enzyme used as a detection nuclease in CRISPR-based assays, exhibiting collateral cleavage activity upon target recognition and suitable for integration into TRACE-type platforms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_39,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_42,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LBCAS12A">
      <data key="d0">LBCAS12A</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">A Cas12a CRISPR effector enzyme (from Lachnospiraceae bacterium) used as a detection nuclease in CRISPR diagnostic assays, providing sequence-specific target recognition and collateral cleavage for signal generation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SAMPLE LYSIS BUFFER">
      <data key="d0">SAMPLE LYSIS BUFFER</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A defined lysis buffer containing Tris-HCl, Tween-20, NP-40, SDS, and PVP, used to lyse patient specimens and release nucleic acids prior to CRISPR-based detection in TRACE assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE LFA OUTPATIENT STUDY">
      <data key="d0">TRACE LFA OUTPATIENT STUDY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A real-world outpatient validation study in which TRACE LFA showed full agreement with qPCR while reducing diagnostic turnaround time by 83%, establishing its clinical performance for MPXV detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QPCR RESULTS DETECTED WITH NUCLEIC ACID EXTRACTS">
      <data key="d0">QPCR RESULTS DETECTED WITH NUCLEIC ACID EXTRACTS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Reference qPCR testing performed on nucleic acid extracts from patient specimens, used as the comparator method to validate the performance and concordance of TRACE assay formats for MPXV detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DAAPCAS12B">
      <data key="d0">DAAPCAS12B</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">A dAapCas12b CRISPR effector enzyme prepared in-house and used as the nuclease component in the CRISPR-based detection assay targeting MPXV.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR DETECTION STEP">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR DETECTION STEP</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">The CRISPR-based detection stage of the assay, which uses dAapCas12b and MPXV-specific gRNAs to recognize amplified targets and generate a detectable signal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ORTHOPOXVIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">ORTHOPOXVIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Non-MPXV orthopoxviruses included as non-target genomes in the in-silico reference database to evaluate cross-reactivity and specificity of primers and gRNAs.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HERPES SIMPLEX VIRUS TYPE 1">
      <data key="d0">HERPES SIMPLEX VIRUS TYPE 1</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Herpes simplex virus type 1 (HSV-1), a non-target virus whose genomes were included in the in-silico database to assess off-target amplification and CRISPR recognition. | Herpes simplex virus type 2 (HSV-2), a non-target virus included in the in-silico database to evaluate potential cross-reactivity of the assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">HERPES SIMPLEX VIRUS TYPE 2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VARICELLA-ZOSTER VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">VARICELLA-ZOSTER VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Varicella-zoster virus, a human herpesvirus included among non-MPXV genomes in the in-silico database to test the specificity of the designed primers and gRNAs.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PATHOGEN NUCLEIC ACID PANEL FOR SPECIFICITY ASSESSMENT">
      <data key="d0">PATHOGEN NUCLEIC ACID PANEL FOR SPECIFICITY ASSESSMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">A panel of nucleic acids from various pathogens prepared in a BSL-3 laboratory and used experimentally to assess the assay’s specificity and cross-reactivity against non-target organisms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IN-SILICO MPXV AND NON-MPXV REFERENCE DATABASE">
      <data key="d0">IN-SILICO MPXV AND NON-MPXV REFERENCE DATABASE</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">A computational reference database containing 2,525 complete MPXV genomes and 304 non-MPXV genomes (including orthopoxviruses, HSV-1, HSV-2, varicella-zoster virus, and related viruses) used to evaluate primer and gRNA specificity via BLAST alignment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PRIMERS">
      <data key="d0">PRIMERS</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">The primer set used in the nucleic acid amplification step (e.g., RPA) to selectively amplify MPXV target regions; their sequences were analyzed in silico for specificity against MPXV and non-MPXV genomes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT CRISPR/CAS12A OR CRISPR/CAS12B ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT CRISPR/CAS12A OR CRISPR/CAS12B ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A single-tube CRISPR-based detection platform that combines amplification and Cas12a or Cas12b-mediated fluorescence detection in one master reaction mix for target DNA.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENT REPORTER">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENT REPORTER</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A labeled oligonucleotide reporter whose fluorescence is unquenched upon collateral cleavage by activated Cas12a or Cas12b, providing the measurable readout of target detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_39,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_42,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SLAN-96 REAL-TIME FLUORESCENCE DETECTION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">SLAN-96 REAL-TIME FLUORESCENCE DETECTION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An instrument used to monitor and record the fluorescence signal from the CRISPR reactions in real time, functioning as the readout platform for the assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_39,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE-NEGATIVE">
      <data key="d0">TRACE-NEGATIVE</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A classification outcome for genomes that do not meet the mismatch-tolerant alignment criteria for both primers and gRNA, indicating a negative result in the TRACE assay framework.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ASSAY’S OVERALL SENSITIVITY AND SPECIFICITY">
      <data key="d0">ASSAY’S OVERALL SENSITIVITY AND SPECIFICITY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A performance characterization derived from classification outcomes of matched and unmatched genomes, quantifying how accurately the assay identifies target versus non-target sequences based on primer and gRNA alignment criteria.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR/CAS12A ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR/CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescence-based CRISPR/Cas12a detection assay using 50 nM gRNA, 1 μL activator, and 2.5 μL target DNA in a 25 μL reaction, incubated at 37 °C for 60 min with fluorescence read every minute. | Fluorescence-based CRISPR/Cas12b detection assay using AapCas12b with 50 nM gRNA, 1 μL activator, and 2.5 μL target DNA in a 25 μL reaction, incubated at 37 °C for 30 min then 60 °C for 30 min with fluorescence read every minute. | CRISPR–Cas12a-based nucleic acid detection assays used as biosensing platforms to detect influenza A viral genes, particularly HA and NA, via subtype-specific guide RNA design. | A CRISPR-based diagnostic platform using Cas12a as the effector nuclease, coupled to isothermal amplification and sample purification for rapid, sensitive detection of viral RNA such as avian influenza virus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">CRISPR/CAS12B ASSAY,CRISPR–CAS12A ASSAYS,CRISPR-CAS12A ASSAY</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RPA MASTER MIXTURE">
      <data key="d0">RPA MASTER MIXTURE</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Standalone recombinase polymerase amplification (RPA) reaction using forward and reverse primers (400 nM final), 1 μL activator, and J2L gene template (500 copies/test) in a 25 μL volume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT CRISPR/CAS12A SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT CRISPR/CAS12A SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Integrated RPA and CRISPR/Cas12a one-pot assay including RPA components, 50 nM gRNA, and 50 nM Cas12a for simultaneous amplification and detection. | Integrated RPA and CRISPR/Cas12b one-pot assay including RPA components, 50 nM gRNA, and 50 nM Cas12b for simultaneous amplification and detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">ONE-POT CRISPR/CAS12B SYSTEM</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GRNA (GENERAL)">
      <data key="d0">GRNA (GENERAL)</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">Guide RNA used at 50 nM in CRISPR/Cas12a, CRISPR/Cas12b, one-pot systems, and TRACE assays to direct Cas12 nucleases to specific DNA targets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE ASSAY GRNA">
      <data key="d0">TRACE ASSAY GRNA</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">Guide RNA sequences optimized for the TRACE assay to direct AapCas12b to the target DNA, with sequence variants evaluated for maximal fluorescence signal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RPA PRIMERS">
      <data key="d0">RPA PRIMERS</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Forward and reverse RPA primers (400 nM each) used to amplify target DNA prior to or during CRISPR-based detection in RPA, one-pot, and TRACE assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE RPA CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">TRACE RPA CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">RPA component of the TRACE assay, run at 37 °C for 10 or 30 min before a 60 °C Cas12b activation step, with primer and reaction time optimization.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GRNA-TO-BLOCKER RATIO OPTIMIZATION">
      <data key="d0">GRNA-TO-BLOCKER RATIO OPTIMIZATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Optimization experiments varying the gRNA-to-ssRNA blocker ratio (1:1 to 1:10) in TRACE to maximize fluorescence signal and assay performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RNP CONCENTRATION OPTIMIZATION">
      <data key="d0">RNP CONCENTRATION OPTIMIZATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Optimization of ribonucleoprotein (Cas12–gRNA) concentration at 50, 100, 200, or 400 nM to determine conditions yielding maximal fluorescence in TRACE.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RPA REACTION TIME OPTIMIZATION">
      <data key="d0">RPA REACTION TIME OPTIMIZATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Systematic variation of RPA reaction time (0–30 min) to evaluate its effect on maximum fluorescence signal in the TRACE assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PRIMER AND GRNA SEQUENCE OPTIMIZATION">
      <data key="d0">PRIMER AND GRNA SEQUENCE OPTIMIZATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Screening of different primer and gRNA sequences (per Supplementary Table 1) to identify designs that maximize fluorescence in the TRACE assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE ASSAY OPTIMIZATION STUDY">
      <data key="d0">TRACE ASSAY OPTIMIZATION STUDY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Systematic evaluation of RPA and CRISPR parameters (primer/gRNA sequences, RPA time, RNP concentration, gRNA-to-blocker ratio) based on maximum fluorescence to optimize TRACE performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AMPLICON ACCUMULATION EVALUATION">
      <data key="d0">AMPLICON ACCUMULATION EVALUATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Comparative assessment of amplicon accumulation in RPA-only, one-pot CRISPR/Cas12a, one-pot CRISPR/Cas12b, and TRACE systems at 37 °C for 0–30 min.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACE SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">ACE SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas12b-based nucleic acid detection platform that operates in a one-pot format combining RPA amplification with Cas12b-mediated detection; its performance is evaluated by gel-based amplicon yield and fluorescence readouts modulated by an ssRNA blocker.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Integrated reaction setups in which RPA amplification and Cas12b-based detection occur in a single 25 μL reaction, with relative amplicon yield calculated by comparing band intensities to standalone RPA at corresponding time points.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GRNA 1">
      <data key="d0">GRNA 1</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A 3′-FAM-labeled guide RNA (gRNA 1) that directs Cas12b to its target dsDNA; it can form a quenched complex with a 5′-BHQ1-labeled ssRNA blocker, enabling temperature-dependent control of fluorescence and Cas12b activation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SSRNA BLOCKER 1">
      <data key="d0">SSRNA BLOCKER 1</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A 5′-BHQ1-labeled single-stranded RNA blocker (blocker 1) that hybridizes with 3′-FAM-gRNA 1 to form a quenched complex, modulating gRNA availability and Cas12b cis-cleavage activity in a temperature-dependent manner.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENCE RECOVERY">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENCE RECOVERY</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The normalized fluorescence signal defined as the ratio of the fluorescence intensity of the 3′-FAM-gRNA 1/5′-BHQ1-ssRNA blocker 1 complex to that of free 3′-FAM-gRNA 1, reflecting the extent of blocker dissociation and gRNA de-quenching over time.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CIS-CLEAVAGE READOUT">
      <data key="d0">CIS-CLEAVAGE READOUT</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Band intensity patterns from 12% PAGE of a 5′-Cy5-labeled dsDNA substrate cleaved by Cas12b–gRNA complexes, quantified to determine relative cis-cleavage activity at different temperatures and blocker conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AAPCAS12B TRANS-CLEAVAGE ASSAY WITH FLUORESCENT REPORTER">
      <data key="d0">AAPCAS12B TRANS-CLEAVAGE ASSAY WITH FLUORESCENT REPORTER</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">In vitro CRISPR-Cas12b assay measuring trans-cleavage activity of AapCas12b on a fluorescent reporter in the presence of a dsDNA substrate, with or without a gRNA-bound blocker, across multiple temperatures.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DAAPCAS12B (E848A)">
      <data key="d0">DAAPCAS12B (E848A)</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">Catalytically deactivated AapCas12b variant carrying a single E848A mutation, expressed in E. coli BL21 (λDE3) and purified via His-tag affinity chromatography.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GRNA–BLOCKER COMPLEX (1:4)">
      <data key="d0">GRNA–BLOCKER COMPLEX (1:4)</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">Guide RNA pre-complexed with a blocker at a 1:4 ratio, used to modulate or inhibit AapCas12b trans-cleavage activity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CIS-CLEAVAGE ACTIVITY MEASUREMENT">
      <data key="d0">CIS-CLEAVAGE ACTIVITY MEASUREMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Measurement of AapCas12b cis-cleavage activity based on the percentage decrease in substrate band intensity on 12% PAGE between 0 and 2 minutes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRANS-CLEAVAGE ACTIVITY MEASUREMENT WITH KINETIC FLUORESCENCE READOUT">
      <data key="d0">TRANS-CLEAVAGE ACTIVITY MEASUREMENT WITH KINETIC FLUORESCENCE READOUT</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Time-course fluorescence assay where AapCas12b trans-cleavage activity is quantified as the maximum slope of fluorescence intensity over 20 minutes at various temperatures.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPRESSION AND PURIFICATION OF DAAPCAS12B">
      <data key="d0">EXPRESSION AND PURIFICATION OF DAAPCAS12B</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Workflow including cloning of E848A dAapCas12b into a pET vector, expression in E. coli BL21 (λDE3), induction with IPTG, lysis, Ni-resin affinity purification, and buffer exchange/concentration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">TRACE SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Five different formulations of the TRACE CRISPR-based assay, each prepared as a 20 μL master mix and lyophilized into CRISPR pellets, representing variant biosensor platform configurations evaluated for lyophilization performance and stability.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DCAS12B">
      <data key="d0">DCAS12B</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">A catalytically dead variant of Cas12b that forms RNP complexes with guide RNA for dsDNA binding studies without cleavage. It is used to characterize RNP binding affinity to dsDNA, informing CRISPR assay design.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GRNA-BLOCKER MIXTURE">
      <data key="d0">GRNA-BLOCKER MIXTURE</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">An annealed mixture of 5′-FAM-labeled gRNA and an ssRNA blocker in a 1:4 ratio, used to partially sequester the guide RNA and modulate its availability for AapCas12b binding in EMAS assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RPA PELLETS">
      <data key="d0">RPA PELLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Lyophilized recombinase polymerase amplification (RPA) reagent pellets stored at 37 °C and tested over 0–60 days, serving as the physical formulation of the isothermal amplification component that can be coupled with the TRACE CRISPR assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LYOPHILIZED CRISPR PELLETS">
      <data key="d0">LYOPHILIZED CRISPR PELLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">CRISPR reagent pellets obtained by freezing TRACE master mixes at -50 °C for 1 h followed by vacuum drying at -40 °C for 20 h. This lyophilization step yields stable, ready-to-use assay components for long-term storage and later rehydration in detection runs.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LYOPHILIZATION PERFORMANCE">
      <data key="d0">LYOPHILIZATION PERFORMANCE</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">An evaluation of how well different TRACE systems retain functional activity after the lyophilization process, used to validate formulation robustness and suitability for field-deployable CRISPR assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LONG-TERM STABILITY ASSESSMENT">
      <data key="d0">LONG-TERM STABILITY ASSESSMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation study in which lyophilized CRISPR and RPA pellets are stored at 37 °C and tested at defined time points from 0 to 60 days to evaluate their stability and performance over time.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMAS AAPCAS12B–GRNA BINDING ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">EMAS AAPCAS12B–GRNA BINDING ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An electrophoretic mobility analysis setup where varying concentrations of AapCas12b are incubated with 5′-FAM-labeled gRNA or gRNA-blocker mixture at 37 °C, followed by 4% polyacrylamide gel analysis to quantify RNP versus free gRNA and define binding efficiency.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMAS RNP–DSDNA BINDING ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">EMAS RNP–DSDNA BINDING ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An electrophoretic mobility analysis where varying concentrations of dCas12b/gRNA RNP are incubated with 5′-Cy5-labeled dsDNA in the presence or absence of ssRNA blocker, followed by 4% polyacrylamide gel analysis to quantify free dsDNA and define binding affinity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="5′-FAM-LABELED GRNA SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">5′-FAM-LABELED GRNA SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescent signal from 5′-FAM-labeled gRNA used in EMAS to distinguish free gRNA from RNP complexes on polyacrylamide gels for quantification of AapCas12b binding efficiency.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="5′-CY5-LABELED DSDNA SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">5′-CY5-LABELED DSDNA SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescent signal from 5′-Cy5-labeled dsDNA used in EMAS to quantify free dsDNA band intensity and assess RNP binding affinity in the presence or absence of ssRNA blocker.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE FLUORESCENCE-BASED ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">TRACE FLUORESCENCE-BASED ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR–Cas12b-based detection platform (TRACE) that uses lyophilized CRISPR and RPA pellets, a two-step temperature program (37 °C then 60 °C), and real-time fluorescence readout to detect target DNA.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE LFA ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">TRACE LFA ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A lateral-flow adaptation of the TRACE assay that uses the same CRISPR–Cas12b reaction but reads out results colorimetrically on lateral flow strips using FAM/biotin-labeled reporters and gold nanoparticle-conjugated antibodies.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RNASE P GRNA1–GRNA7">
      <data key="d0">RNASE P GRNA1–GRNA7</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">A panel of seven candidate guide RNAs targeting human RNase P, screened in the TRACE duplex assay to identify gRNAs with optimal performance for multiplex detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COLORIMETRIC READOUT VIA LATERAL FLOW STRIPS">
      <data key="d0">COLORIMETRIC READOUT VIA LATERAL FLOW STRIPS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The visual colorimetric signal on lateral flow strips in the TRACE LFA assay, interpreted by the presence and grayscale intensity of the test (T) and control (C) lines.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAM- AND BIOTIN-LABELED REPORTER">
      <data key="d0">FAM- AND BIOTIN-LABELED REPORTER</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A dual-labeled nucleic acid reporter (FAM and biotin) used in the TRACE LFA assay; its Cas12b-mediated cleavage and subsequent capture on the LFA strip generate the colorimetric signal pattern.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAM-SPECIFIC GOLD NANOPARTICLE-CONJUGATED ANTIBODIES STAINING AT THE STREPTAVIDIN-CONJUGATED C-LINE">
      <data key="d0">FAM-SPECIFIC GOLD NANOPARTICLE-CONJUGATED ANTIBODIES STAINING AT THE STREPTAVIDIN-CONJUGATED C-LINE</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The specific lateral-flow signal configuration where FAM-specific gold nanoparticle-conjugated antibodies bind reporter captured at the streptavidin-conjugated control (C) line, used to define optimal reporter concentration and specificity in the TRACE LFA assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUCLEIC ACID EXTRACTS FROM HUMAN 293 CELLS">
      <data key="d0">NUCLEIC ACID EXTRACTS FROM HUMAN 293 CELLS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Prepared nucleic acid extracts derived from human 293 cells, used as input material in the TRACE duplex assay to evaluate RNase P gRNA performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_44,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE DUPLEX ASSAY RUN">
      <data key="d0">TRACE DUPLEX ASSAY RUN</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An individual execution of the optimized TRACE duplex assay using defined concentrations of primers, Cas12a, Cas12b, guide RNAs, fluorescent reporter, ssRNA blocker, activator, and target DNA, with incubation at 37 °C then 64 °C and minute-by-minute fluorescence recording.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="J2L GENE TARGET DNA">
      <data key="d0">J2L GENE TARGET DNA</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Target DNA containing the J2L gene sequence, including samples spiked with 100 copies of the J2L gene, used as the analyte for J2L detection in the TRACE duplex assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RCA-BASED TRACE ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">RCA-BASED TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A variant of the TRACE assay that incorporates a rolling circle amplification (RCA) workflow using padlock probes, ligation, and phi29 polymerase prior to Cas12b-based detection of the MPXV J2L target.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL (ΔF2)">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL (ΔF2)</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Stage-2 fluorescence change attributed to the MPXV J2L gene in the TRACE assay, used to determine MPXV J2L-positivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PORTABLE READER FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">PORTABLE READER FLUORESCENCE SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescent readout captured by a portable reader as an alternative to the SLAN-96 real-time fluorescence detection system for the TRACE assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SLAN-96 REAL-TIME FLUORESCENCE DETECTION SYSTEM SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">SLAN-96 REAL-TIME FLUORESCENCE DETECTION SYSTEM SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescent readout recorded by the SLAN-96 real-time fluorescence detection system during TRACE assay runs.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BENCH VALIDATION WITH NEGATIVE CONTROLS AND MPXV-NEGATIVE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">BENCH VALIDATION WITH NEGATIVE CONTROLS AND MPXV-NEGATIVE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation procedure using negative controls and MPXV-negative samples to empirically define fluorescence thresholds T1 and T2 (mean + 3×SD) for positive RNase P and J2L signals in the TRACE assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE ASSAY RUN ON CLINICAL SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">TRACE ASSAY RUN ON CLINICAL SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Individual executions of the TRACE assay on clinical samples where ΔF1 and ΔF2 are compared to T1 and T2 to classify RNase P and MPXV J2L status and determine sample validity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RCA-BASED TRACE ASSAY RUN ON J2L TARGET">
      <data key="d0">RCA-BASED TRACE ASSAY RUN ON J2L TARGET</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A specific execution of the RCA-based TRACE workflow using 1000 copies per test of the J2L target, padlock ligation, RCA, and Cas12b/gRNA detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PHI29 AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">PHI29 AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Phi29-based amplification is an isothermal DNA amplification method in TRACE that uses phi29 polymerase, buffer, dNTPs, and primers to amplify target nucleic acids before or during CRISPR detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="J2L GENE REFERENCE STANDARD">
      <data key="d0">J2L GENE REFERENCE STANDARD</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The J2L gene reference standard is a defined nucleic acid standard corresponding to the MPXV J2L gene, used in serial dilution and repeat-measurement runs of TRACE to determine limit of detection and detection stability.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RNASE P REFERENCE STANDARD">
      <data key="d0">RNASE P REFERENCE STANDARD</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The RNase P reference standard is a human gene control nucleic acid standard used in TRACE assay runs to characterize the limit of detection and performance for the human internal control target.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOD OF TRACE">
      <data key="d0">LOD OF TRACE</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The limit of detection of TRACE is defined as the lowest concentration of J2L or RNase P reference standard that produces a reporter signal exceeding the positive threshold under optimal assay conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POSITIVE THRESHOLD OF TRACE">
      <data key="d0">POSITIVE THRESHOLD OF TRACE</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The positive threshold in TRACE is defined as the mean reporter signal of the negative reference sample plus three times its standard deviation, and is used as the decision boundary for calling positive detections and for LoD determination.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE SPECIFICITY PROFILE">
      <data key="d0">TRACE SPECIFICITY PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The specificity profile of TRACE is established by testing synthetic plasmids containing pathogen genes and extracted nucleic acids from various pathogens to assess cross-reactivity and analytical specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEAT INACTIVATION AT 56 °C FOR 30 MINUTES">
      <data key="d0">HEAT INACTIVATION AT 56 °C FOR 30 MINUTES</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Heat inactivation at 56 °C for 30 minutes is a pre-analytical sample preparation step applied to all clinical specimens before TRACE analysis to inactivate pathogens and help preserve nucleic acids. | A pre-analytical step in which clinical specimens are heat-inactivated at 56 °C for 30 minutes to inactivate infectious agents before storage and downstream nucleic acid testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">HEAT-INACTIVATION AT 56 °C FOR 30 MINUTES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STORAGE AT -80 °C">
      <data key="d0">STORAGE AT -80 °C</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Storage at -80 °C is a sample preservation step applied to clinical specimens after heat inactivation and prior to TRACE testing to maintain nucleic acid integrity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47,6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEPARATION OF PLASMA WITHIN 2 H">
      <data key="d0">SEPARATION OF PLASMA WITHIN 2 H</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Processing blood samples to separate plasma within 2 hours of collection is a pre-analytical handling step to obtain plasma for subsequent TRACE analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BENCH ANALYTICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE">
      <data key="d0">BENCH ANALYTICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The analytical validation of TRACE comprises bench studies that determine limit of detection, detection stability, and specificity using serially diluted J2L and RNase P reference standards and panels of pathogen-derived nucleic acids.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLINICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE AT SHENZHEN THIRD PEOPLE’S HOSPITAL">
      <data key="d0">CLINICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE AT SHENZHEN THIRD PEOPLE’S HOSPITAL</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The clinical validation of TRACE includes retrospective and prospective studies at Shenzhen Third People’s Hospital between June 2023 and August 2024 using clinical samples from MPXV-infected, MPXV-excluded, and suspected MPXV cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE REPORTER SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">TRACE REPORTER SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The TRACE reporter signal is the measurable fluorescence (or analogous) output generated by Cas12b-mediated cleavage of a reporter molecule, which is compared to the positive threshold to classify results as positive or negative.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANALYSIS STABILITY CRITERION OF TRACE">
      <data key="d0">ANALYSIS STABILITY CRITERION OF TRACE</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The analysis stability criterion for TRACE is defined as the lowest J2L gene reference standard concentration that achieves at least a 95% (19/20) detection probability across 20 repeated measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE DUPLEX SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">TRACE DUPLEX SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A duplex (dual-target) version of the TRACE assay using lyophilized reagents, run under the same temperature program as TRACE and compatible with fluorescence and lateral-flow readouts for MPXV detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MIXING WITH SAMPLE LYSIS BUFFER AT A 3:1 RATIO AND INCUBATION AT 80 °C FOR 5 MIN">
      <data key="d0">MIXING WITH SAMPLE LYSIS BUFFER AT A 3:1 RATIO AND INCUBATION AT 80 °C FOR 5 MIN</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A lysis procedure in which original clinical samples are mixed with sample lysis buffer at a 3:1 ratio and incubated at 80 °C for 5 minutes to release nucleic acids for TRACE LFA and TRACE duplex testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QPCR REFERENCE ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">QPCR REFERENCE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A commercial qPCR kit run in a clinical laboratory as the reference standard assay, using 3 μL of extracted nucleic acids to detect MPXV and classify samples as positive (Ct &lt; 40) or negative (Ct ≥ 40).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VISUAL INTERPRETATION USING LFA STRIPS">
      <data key="d0">VISUAL INTERPRETATION USING LFA STRIPS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A lateral-flow colorimetric readout mode in which results from TRACE LFA or the TRACE duplex system are interpreted visually on LFA strips as qualitative positive/negative outcomes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLINICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">CLINICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A clinical validation study at Shenzhen Third People’s Hospital (Dec 2024–Apr 2025) in which TRACE, TRACE LFA, and the TRACE duplex system were evaluated on specimens from suspected MPXV cases, with sample size calculated from prior reports.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QPCR REFERENCE VALIDATION">
      <data key="d0">QPCR REFERENCE VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The use of a commercial qPCR assay in a clinical laboratory as the reference standard against which the diagnostic performance of the TRACE-based assays was compared.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE ASSAY RUNS ON CLINICAL NUCLEIC ACID SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">TRACE ASSAY RUNS ON CLINICAL NUCLEIC ACID SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Blinded executions of the TRACE assay using 1 μL of extracted nucleic acid from clinical specimens, generating fluorescence or lateral-flow readouts for MPXV detection. | Individual executions of the commercial qPCR reference assay using 3 μL of extracted nucleic acids from clinical specimens to determine MPXV positivity based on Ct values.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
      <data key="d6">QPCR RUNS ON CLINICAL NUCLEIC ACID SAMPLES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE LFA RUNS ON ORIGINAL CLINICAL SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">TRACE LFA RUNS ON ORIGINAL CLINICAL SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Individual runs of the TRACE LFA format on original clinical samples after lysis-buffer treatment, producing visually interpreted LFA strip results for MPXV detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE ASSAY RUNS">
      <data key="d0">TRACE ASSAY RUNS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Individual experimental runs of the TRACE biosensor platform whose signals were analyzed using nonparametric tests, ANOVA, and correlation with qPCR results.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE SENSITIVITY">
      <data key="d0">TRACE SENSITIVITY</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The diagnostic sensitivity of the TRACE platform, with a target of 90% and an expected value of 98%, used in sample size calculation and performance evaluation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE SPECIFICITY">
      <data key="d0">TRACE SPECIFICITY</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The diagnostic specificity of the TRACE platform, with a target of 95% and an expected value of 100%, used in sample size calculation and performance evaluation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MONKEYPOX">
      <data key="d0">MONKEYPOX</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Monkeypox, used in the cited Lancet review as the overarching term for the monkeypox virus infection; in this context it denotes the pathogen/disease entity of interest in clinical and epidemiological research.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-CAS12A TARGET BINDING UNLEASHES INDISCRIMINATE SINGLE-STRANDED DNASE ACTIVITY (SCIENCE 2018)">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-CAS12A TARGET BINDING UNLEASHES INDISCRIMINATE SINGLE-STRANDED DNASE ACTIVITY (SCIENCE 2018)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas12a-based nucleic acid detection platform in which target binding activates indiscriminate single-stranded DNase activity, enabling signal generation from cleavable reporter molecules.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-CAS12A-ASSISTED NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION (CELL DISCOVERY 2018)">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-CAS12A-ASSISTED NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION (CELL DISCOVERY 2018)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas12a-assisted nucleic acid detection assay that leverages Cas12a collateral ssDNA cleavage for sensitive detection of target nucleic acids.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION WITH CRISPR-CAS13A/C2C2 (SCIENCE 2017)">
      <data key="d0">NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION WITH CRISPR-CAS13A/C2C2 (SCIENCE 2017)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas13a (C2c2)-based nucleic acid detection platform that uses target-activated collateral RNase activity to cleave reporter RNAs for signal readout.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS13A (C2C2)">
      <data key="d0">CAS13A (C2C2)</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">Cas13a, also known as C2c2, is an RNA-targeting CRISPR effector nuclease that displays collateral RNase activity upon target recognition, enabling RNA-based nucleic acid detection platforms. | An RNA-guided RNase used in CRISPR-based nucleic acid detection assays, exhibiting collateral cleavage of reporter RNAs upon target recognition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">CAS13A (C2C2)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR/CAS12A SARS-COV-2 VISUAL ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR/CAS12A SARS-COV-2 VISUAL ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A contamination-free, CRISPR/Cas12a-based visual detection assay for SARS-CoV-2 developed by Chen et al. (2020) in Biosensors and Bioelectronics, intended for point-of-care use.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VISUAL NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">VISUAL NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A visually interpretable reporter signal (e.g., colorimetric or fluorescence visible to the naked eye) generated by platforms such as Cas12aVDet to indicate the presence of target nucleic acids.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VISUAL SARS-COV-2 DETECTION SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">VISUAL SARS-COV-2 DETECTION SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A visual readout format used in the CRISPR/Cas12a SARS-CoV-2 assay to indicate the presence of SARS-CoV-2 nucleic acid, enabling interpretation without complex instrumentation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POINT-OF-CARE DETECTION CONTEXT">
      <data key="d0">POINT-OF-CARE DETECTION CONTEXT</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The intended application and evaluation context for the CRISPR/Cas12a SARS-CoV-2 visual assay, emphasizing suitability for decentralized, near-patient testing settings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STREAMLINED CAS13-BASED DETECTION OF SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d0">STREAMLINED CAS13-BASED DETECTION OF SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A streamlined CRISPR diagnostic workflow that combines sample inactivation, nucleic acid amplification, and Cas13-mediated detection to identify SARS-CoV-2 RNA.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SAMPLE INACTIVATION">
      <data key="d0">SAMPLE INACTIVATION</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sample preparation step in which viral particles or infectious material are rendered non-infectious prior to amplification and Cas13-based detection of SARS-CoV-2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION (UPSTREAM OF CAS13 DETECTION)">
      <data key="d0">NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION (UPSTREAM OF CAS13 DETECTION)</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A nucleic acid amplification step used upstream of Cas13-based detection to increase the amount of SARS-CoV-2 target RNA; the specific amplification chemistry is not specified in the excerpt.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-CAS12A DIAGNOSTIC ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-CAS12A DIAGNOSTIC ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas12a-based biosensor platform for fast and sensitive detection of viral RNA, including SARS-CoV-2, which can exploit suboptimal protospacer adjacent motifs, minimized interference from target amplification, and photocontrolled crRNA activation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR DETECTION WITH MINIMIZED AMPLIFICATION INTERFERENCE">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR DETECTION WITH MINIMIZED AMPLIFICATION INTERFERENCE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-based detection platform that achieves fast and sensitive readout by minimizing interference from target amplification steps, as described for general CRISPR detection workflows.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VEST-POCKET DIAGNOSTIC DEVICE">
      <data key="d0">VEST-POCKET DIAGNOSTIC DEVICE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A portable, ultrasensitive diagnostic device that performs single-step CRISPR-based detection of nucleic acids; in the cited work it is used for rapid detection of monkeypox virus within minutes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-CAS12A MEDIATED MONKEYPOX VIRUS ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-CAS12A MEDIATED MONKEYPOX VIRUS ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas12a–based nucleic acid detection platform developed for rapid laboratory detection of monkeypox virus, suitable for one-pot diagnostic workflows.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LABORATORY VALIDATION AND EVALUATION STUDY OF CRISPR-CAS12A MONKEYPOX ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">LABORATORY VALIDATION AND EVALUATION STUDY OF CRISPR-CAS12A MONKEYPOX ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A laboratory-based validation and evaluation study that establishes the analytical performance and diagnostic accuracy of the CRISPR-Cas12a–mediated assay for rapid monkeypox virus detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THERMALLY PROGRAMMED ONE-POT CRISPR ASSAY FOR ON-SITE PANDEMIC SURVEILLANCE">
      <data key="d0">THERMALLY PROGRAMMED ONE-POT CRISPR ASSAY FOR ON-SITE PANDEMIC SURVEILLANCE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-based one-pot assay described in the article title, designed for on-site surveillance of pandemic pathogens using thermally programmed reaction steps within a single reaction vessel.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_71</data>
      <data key="d5">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA">
      <data key="d0">HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) refers to virulent avian influenza A viruses that cause severe systemic disease in birds and can be transmitted via aerosols and droplets in poultry production environments. | Highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) viruses causing heterogeneous outbreaks across poultry and livestock, including dairy cattle, in the United States as of August 2025.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_0,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_27,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_68,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">HPAI</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5N1 CLADE 2.3.4.4B">
      <data key="d0">H5N1 CLADE 2.3.4.4B</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A contemporary HPAI H5N1 lineage (clade 2.3.4.4b) associated with widespread epizootics in US poultry and dairy production systems and zoonotic transmission events since early 2024. | A specific clade (2.3.4.4b) of highly pathogenic avian influenza A H5N1 virus that has recently expanded its host range to infect dairy cattle in addition to birds, with transmission in poultry via aerosols, fecal–oral routes, and contaminated fomites.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">H5N1 (CLADE 2.3.4.4B)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOLECULAR AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">MOLECULAR AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A general class of nucleic acid amplification techniques (such as PCR or isothermal amplification) proposed as one modality in multimodal sensing for in situ recognition of HPAI in poultry systems.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELECTROCHEMICAL DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">ELECTROCHEMICAL DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An electrochemical biosensing platform that measures changes in electrical properties to detect molecular signatures of pathogens such as HPAI in field or production-system samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACOUSTIC ANOMALY ANALYSIS">
      <data key="d0">ACOUSTIC ANOMALY ANALYSIS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A sensing platform that analyzes deviations in acoustic or sound patterns (for example, poultry vocalizations or barn noise) as a non-traditional modality for detecting disease states like HPAI in poultry houses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BEHAVIORAL AND PHYSIOLOGICAL SIGNAL INTEGRATION">
      <data key="d0">BEHAVIORAL AND PHYSIOLOGICAL SIGNAL INTEGRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A multimodal biosensing approach that integrates behavioral and physiological signals from poultry to improve the accuracy and robustness of HPAI biosurveillance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE HEALTH BIOSURVEILLANCE SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">ONE HEALTH BIOSURVEILLANCE SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Adaptive biosurveillance systems framed under the One Health concept that integrate animal, human, and environmental data streams for anticipatory and scalable field responses to HPAI outbreaks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA (HPAI)">
      <data key="d0">HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA (HPAI)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A group of avian influenza A viruses that cause severe disease in birds; in this context, refers to re-emergent HPAI strains circulating since early 2022 that have driven a biosurveillance and agrosecurity crisis in the United States. | Highly pathogenic avian influenza A (H5N1) is an avian influenza virus subtype that can be transmitted via aerosols and droplets between birds and occasionally humans, and is the focus of surveillance, prevention, control, and preparedness discussions in the cited Mayo Clinic Proceedings article.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_1,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA A (H5N1)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5N1">
      <data key="d0">H5N1</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Highly pathogenic avian influenza A/H5N1 virus, described as causing near-100% flock mortality within 48 hours post-exposure and driving large-scale agricultural, economic, and potential pandemic disruption, with significant zoonotic risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_3,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_10,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_14,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_18,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_19,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_24,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_42,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_46,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_51,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA A/H5NX VIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA A/H5NX VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A group of highly pathogenic avian influenza A viruses of the H5Nx subtype, evaluated for pathogenicity in avian and murine models and associated with severe disease and high mortality. | A virulent form of avian influenza virus (notably H5 and H7 subtypes) associated with severe disease in birds and potential airborne transmission; discussed in relation to haemagglutinin cleavage site motif evolution and acquisition of a polybasic cleavage site.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_3,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_72</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTIMODAL BIOSENSING PLATFORMS">
      <data key="d0">MULTIMODAL BIOSENSING PLATFORMS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Integrated biosensing systems that combine molecular, physiological, and behavioral signal streams to enable dynamic, real-time monitoring and early detection of infectious disease outbreaks, including HPAI.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SELF-SERVICE MULTIMODAL DETECTION OF SUBTYPE INFLUENZA A VIRUS H5N1 BY VISUAL PORTABLE MOLECULAR IMPRINTING SENSOR">
      <data key="d0">SELF-SERVICE MULTIMODAL DETECTION OF SUBTYPE INFLUENZA A VIRUS H5N1 BY VISUAL PORTABLE MOLECULAR IMPRINTING SENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A portable multimodal biosensing platform using molecular imprinting and visual readout for self-service detection of influenza A H5N1, exemplifying targeted pathogen identification capabilities.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TARGETED BIOSENSING DIAGNOSTICS">
      <data key="d0">TARGETED BIOSENSING DIAGNOSTICS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A class of biosensing platforms designed to directly identify specific viral biomarkers, such as viral RNA or antigens, with high sensitivity and specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS H5N1">
      <data key="d0">AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS H5N1</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A highly pathogenic avian influenza A subtype (H5N1) that can spread rapidly in poultry and at the animal–human–environment interface, and is a key target for early detection by multimodal biosensing platforms. | A low- and high-pathogenicity avian influenza A virus subtype (H5N2) studied for its transmission characteristics in poultry, including spread via respiratory and aerosol routes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_8,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_9,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_16,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_77,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_81,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_97</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">AVIAN INFLUENZA A VIRUS (H5N2)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS (GENERAL)">
      <data key="d0">AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS (GENERAL)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Avian influenza A viruses circulating in poultry populations, monitored for emerging disease using new technologies and big data.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRAL RNA BIOMARKERS">
      <data key="d0">VIRAL RNA BIOMARKERS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Nucleic acid biomarkers derived from viral genomes that serve as specific molecular signals detected by targeted biosensing diagnostics.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRAL ANTIGEN BIOMARKERS">
      <data key="d0">VIRAL ANTIGEN BIOMARKERS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Viral protein or antigenic components that function as specific molecular signals for targeted detection in biosensing diagnostics.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IMPEDANCE IMMUNOSENSOR BASED ON LOW-COST MICROELECTRODES AND SPECIFIC MONOCLONAL ANTIBODIES">
      <data key="d0">IMPEDANCE IMMUNOSENSOR BASED ON LOW-COST MICROELECTRODES AND SPECIFIC MONOCLONAL ANTIBODIES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A low-cost impedance-based immunosensor that uses microelectrodes and monoclonal antibodies for rapid, high-sensitivity and high-specificity detection of avian influenza virus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_8,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_9,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_77</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURFACE PLASMON RESONANCE (SPR) BIOSENSORS">
      <data key="d0">SURFACE PLASMON RESONANCE (SPR) BIOSENSORS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Label-free biosensor platforms that use surface plasmon resonance to detect binding events, referenced here for prevention and control of avian influenza virus through advanced diagnostics and surveillance. | An optical biosensor platform in which target binding at a thin metal film changes the local refractive index, shifting the surface plasmon resonance and enabling real-time, label-free measurement of association and dissociation kinetics.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">SURFACE PLASMON RESONANCE BIOSENSOR</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LABEL-FREE SERS MOLECULAR FINGERPRINTING">
      <data key="d0">LABEL-FREE SERS MOLECULAR FINGERPRINTING</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A label-free surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS) platform that generates molecular fingerprints of biological samples, used for rapid detection of disintegrated viral components such as SARS-CoV-2 in environmental dust.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_9,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THERMAL IMAGING FOR DETECTING FEBRILE RESPONSES">
      <data key="d0">THERMAL IMAGING FOR DETECTING FEBRILE RESPONSES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An infrared thermography-based platform that detects elevated body temperature as a general indicator of disease in domestic animals, used as a nontargeted surveillance modality.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACOUSTIC SURVEILLANCE FOR RESPIRATORY ANOMALIES">
      <data key="d0">ACOUSTIC SURVEILLANCE FOR RESPIRATORY ANOMALIES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An acoustic monitoring platform that analyzes respiratory sounds and vocalization rates to identify respiratory anomalies in animals, used as a nontargeted disease surveillance tool.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEWCASTLE DISEASE VIRUS (NDV)">
      <data key="d0">NEWCASTLE DISEASE VIRUS (NDV)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Newcastle Disease Virus (NDV), a high-consequence respiratory virus of poultry mentioned as a candidate for similar multimodal early-detection strategies within the unified sensing architecture.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUSES (AIVS)">
      <data key="d0">AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUSES (AIVS)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A group of avian influenza A viruses that infect birds, including H5N1; they are airborne respiratory pathogens central to the review’s surveillance and biosensing context. | Airborne avian influenza virus targeted by surveillance assays in poultry and wildlife, including pan-AIV and specific H5, H7, H9 subtypes.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_10,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_24,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS (AIV)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTIMODAL H5N1 BIOSENSOR">
      <data key="d0">MULTIMODAL H5N1 BIOSENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A self-service, portable molecular imprinting-based biosensor platform for subtype influenza A virus H5N1 that integrates fluorescence, UV-Vis, and colorimetric detection modes to enable cross-validated, highly sensitive detection in complex samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="11.6 FM">
      <data key="d0">11.6 FM</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">An ultra-low limit of detection (LoD) of 11.6 femtomolar reported for the multimodal H5N1 biosensor, indicating very high analytical sensitivity for H5N1 detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENCE">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENCE</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A fluorescence-based optical reporter signal used as one of the readout channels in the multimodal H5N1 biosensor for sensitive detection of target binding events. | The fluorescent readout generated upon cleavage of the labeled reporter (R), serving as the measurable signal indicating successful ANCA cycling and target nucleic acid detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_10,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b</data>
      <data key="d6">FLUORESCENCE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UV-VIS">
      <data key="d0">UV-VIS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A UV-Visible absorbance reporter signal modality used in the multimodal H5N1 biosensor, providing a spectrophotometric readout that complements fluorescence and colorimetric modes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COLORIMETRIC MODE">
      <data key="d0">COLORIMETRIC MODE</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A colorimetric reporter mode in the multimodal H5N1 biosensor that enables visual detection of H5N1 via color changes, supporting portable and self-service operation without complex instrumentation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPIKED SERUM">
      <data key="d0">SPIKED SERUM</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation matrix in which the multimodal H5N1 biosensor achieved 93–118% recovery in serum samples spiked with known amounts of target, demonstrating performance in a complex biological sample.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="93–118% RECOVERY">
      <data key="d0">93–118% RECOVERY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The reported recovery range (93–118%) obtained when testing the multimodal H5N1 biosensor in spiked serum, indicating accurate quantification and robustness of the assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEASONAL INFLUENZA">
      <data key="d0">SEASONAL INFLUENZA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Seasonal influenza comprises recurrent human influenza virus strains circulating in the population; its temporal circulation patterns are compared with HPAI occurrence in animals to examine spatiotemporal co-occurrence.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFLUENZA A">
      <data key="d0">INFLUENZA A</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Influenza A viruses predominating among influenza-positive tests reported to CDC by clinical and public health laboratories, with multiple circulating subtypes and lineages. | Influenza B viruses detected in CDC clinical and public health laboratory testing, contributing to the overall influenza burden alongside Influenza A.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_13,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_14,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_57,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">INFLUENZA B</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H1N1PDM09">
      <data key="d0">H1N1PDM09</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A pandemic-derived Influenza A H1N1 lineage (H1N1pdm09) identified in subtype and lineage analysis of circulating influenza viruses in public health surveillance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H3N2">
      <data key="d0">H3N2</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">An Influenza A H3N2 subtype reported as one of the major circulating viral lineages in CDC public health laboratory surveillance data.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_13,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_14,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFLUENZA B VICTORIA LINEAGE">
      <data key="d0">INFLUENZA B VICTORIA LINEAGE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The Victoria lineage of Influenza B viruses, identified as one of the circulating influenza B lineages in CDC public health laboratory data.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIVS">
      <data key="d0">AIVS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Avian influenza A viruses (AIVs), members of the Influenza A genus within the Orthomyxoviridae family, whose structural and genetic features inform diagnostic target selection and sensing strategy design.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUSES (LPAI)">
      <data key="d0">LOW PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUSES (LPAI)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Avian influenza A viruses that typically cause mild or subclinical infections in birds; defined in contrast to HPAI based on molecular markers and disease severity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUBTYPE-SPECIFIC GUIDE-RNA">
      <data key="d0">SUBTYPE-SPECIFIC GUIDE-RNA</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">Guide RNA molecules designed to specifically recognize influenza A HA and NA gene sequences, enabling subtype-specific detection in CRISPR–Cas12a assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HA GENE">
      <data key="d0">HA GENE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The hemagglutinin (HA) gene segment of influenza A virus, which defines subtype identity and serves as a primary molecular target for RT-qPCR and CRISPR–Cas12a assays. | The neuraminidase (NA) gene segment of influenza A virus, defining subtype identity and acting as a key target for subtype-specific RT-qPCR and CRISPR–Cas12a detection assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">NA GENE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MATRIX (M) GENE">
      <data key="d0">MATRIX (M) GENE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The matrix (M) gene of influenza A virus, highly conserved across lineages and used as a universal diagnostic marker for broad-spectrum molecular assays and immunosensors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NP GENE">
      <data key="d0">NP GENE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The nucleoprotein (NP) gene of influenza A virus, conserved across influenza A lineages and serving as a universal diagnostic marker for broad-spectrum molecular assays and immunosensors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BROAD-SPECTRUM MOLECULAR ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">BROAD-SPECTRUM MOLECULAR ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Molecular diagnostic assay platforms designed to detect a wide range of influenza A lineages by targeting conserved genes such as matrix (M) and NP.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELECTROCHEMICAL IMMUNOSENSORS">
      <data key="d0">ELECTROCHEMICAL IMMUNOSENSORS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Electrochemical immunosensor platforms, including paper-based formats, that detect influenza A viral proteins, leveraging conserved matrix (M) and NP antigens as universal diagnostic markers. | Biosensors employing a three-electrode configuration (working, reference, counter) for stable potentials and accurate current measurements, used for high-specificity pathogen detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">ELECTROCHEMICAL BIOSENSORS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMERGING H5N1 CLADE 2.3.4.4B VARIANTS">
      <data key="d0">EMERGING H5N1 CLADE 2.3.4.4B VARIANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Genetically distinct variants within the H5N1 avian influenza A lineage (clade 2.3.4.4b), characterized by sequence and structural changes in HA cleavage sites and NA stalk regions that inform rational biosensor target selection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HPAI AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">HPAI AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Highly pathogenic avian influenza A viruses circulating in poultry systems and transmitted via environmental interfaces such as air (aerosols, dust), water, fomites, and feed, serving as the primary viral target for the described biosensing and molecular detection strategies. | A broad grouping of avian influenza A viruses collectively targeted in the CRISPR/Cas13a lateral flow assay by Yang et al. for pan-avian influenza detection across multiple subtypes.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">PAN-AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELECTROCHEMICAL SENSORS (IMPEDANCE OR CAPACITIVE)">
      <data key="d0">ELECTROCHEMICAL SENSORS (IMPEDANCE OR CAPACITIVE)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Electrochemical biosensing platforms that measure impedance or capacitance changes to detect HPAI avian influenza virus or associated biomarkers in environmental and poultry system samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPTICAL METHODS (SERS, SPR)">
      <data key="d0">OPTICAL METHODS (SERS, SPR)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Optical biosensing platforms, including surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS) and surface plasmon resonance (SPR), used to detect HPAI avian influenza virus or related analytes via changes in optical signals.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BEHAVIORAL APPROACHES (ACOUSTIC MONITORING)">
      <data key="d0">BEHAVIORAL APPROACHES (ACOUSTIC MONITORING)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Behavioral monitoring approaches, specifically acoustic monitoring of poultry vocalizations or activity, used as an indirect biosensing modality to infer HPAI avian influenza infection or distress in flocks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOLECULAR ASSAYS FOR HPAI DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">MOLECULAR ASSAYS FOR HPAI DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A class of nucleic acid-based detection platforms, including RT-qPCR and CRISPR Cas12a assays, used to identify HPAI avian influenza viral RNA in diverse environmental and poultry-related samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5N8">
      <data key="d0">H5N8</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A highly pathogenic avian influenza A virus subtype (H5N8) associated with outbreaks in poultry and wild birds, capable of respiratory transmission and relevant for molecular, electrochemical, optical, and behavioral biosensing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_18,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H7N9">
      <data key="d0">H7N9</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">An avian influenza A virus subtype (H7N9), including highly pathogenic variants, that can spread via respiratory routes and is an important airborne pathogen target for diverse sensing modalities.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_18,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_19,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-CAS12A-BASED ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-CAS12A-BASED ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Laboratory CRISPR–Cas12a diagnostic assays used in avian influenza surveillance workflows, functioning as nucleic-acid-detection biosensor platforms that generate a signal upon recognition of viral RNA targets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTIPLEX QPCR">
      <data key="d0">MULTIPLEX QPCR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Modern high-throughput qPCR implementation that allows simultaneous interrogation of multiple influenza genomic targets (HA, NA, NP, M) in 96–384 well plate formats with internal amplification controls.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRAL RNA">
      <data key="d0">VIRAL RNA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Genomic RNA from influenza viruses present in clinical or surveillance samples that is quantified by qPCR-based assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HPAI STRAINS WITH POLYBASIC HA0 CLEAVAGE SITE INSERTIONS">
      <data key="d0">HPAI STRAINS WITH POLYBASIC HA0 CLEAVAGE SITE INSERTIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Highly pathogenic avian influenza virus strains characterized by polybasic insertions at the HA0 cleavage site, identified as pathogenicity-associated motifs by qPCR assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HA GENE TARGET">
      <data key="d0">HA GENE TARGET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Hemagglutinin (HA) gene segment of influenza viruses used as a genomic target in multiplex qPCR assays for detection and subtyping. | Matrix (M) gene segment of influenza viruses used as a genomic target in multiplex qPCR assays for detection and surveillance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">M GENE TARGET</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INTERNAL AMPLIFICATION CONTROLS">
      <data key="d0">INTERNAL AMPLIFICATION CONTROLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Control amplification reactions incorporated into qPCR assays to monitor assay performance, ensure robustness, and minimize false negatives.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RNA PURIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">RNA PURIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Sample preparation step involving extraction and purification of viral RNA prior to qPCR testing. | A nucleic-acid cleanup step to isolate DNA from other cellular components; omitted in the ANCA method to simplify and accelerate the diagnostic workflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b</data>
      <data key="d6">DNA PURIFICATION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANALYTICAL SENSITIVITY BELOW 10 RNA COPIES PER REACTION">
      <data key="d0">ANALYTICAL SENSITIVITY BELOW 10 RNA COPIES PER REACTION</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">Reported qPCR analytical sensitivity, with a limit of detection often below 10 viral RNA copies per reaction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIVA-COMPATIBLE QPCR DESIGNS">
      <data key="d0">DIVA-COMPATIBLE QPCR DESIGNS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Differentiating Infected from Vaccinated Animals (DIVA) qPCR assay designs that target genes absent from vaccine strains to distinguish infected from vaccinated animals.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONFIRMATORY QPCR TESTING">
      <data key="d0">CONFIRMATORY QPCR TESTING</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Laboratory-based qPCR testing used for confirmatory diagnosis, molecular epidemiology, and surveillance, often requiring 48–72 hours turnaround during outbreaks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ON-FARM ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">ON-FARM ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Field-deployable diagnostic assays used directly on farms, referenced as having lower per-sample costs compared to laboratory qPCR.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5 HEMAGGLUTININ GENE">
      <data key="d0">H5 HEMAGGLUTININ GENE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The H5 subtype hemagglutinin gene segment of H5N1 avian influenza virus, used as a specific nucleic acid target for RT-LAMP-based diagnosis of H5N1 infection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFLUENZA GENE SEGMENTS (HA, NP, M)">
      <data key="d0">INFLUENZA GENE SEGMENTS (HA, NP, M)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Influenza virus gene segments—hemagglutinin (HA), nucleoprotein (NP), and matrix (M)—that serve as nucleic acid targets for isothermal amplification assays to detect influenza infections.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REVERSE TRANSCRIPTION RECOMBINASE POLYMERASE AMPLIFICATION (RT-RPA)">
      <data key="d0">REVERSE TRANSCRIPTION RECOMBINASE POLYMERASE AMPLIFICATION (RT-RPA)</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">An isothermal amplification technique that couples reverse transcription with recombinase polymerase amplification at low, constant temperatures (around 37–42 °C), providing rapid, portable detection of RNA viruses including influenza.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ISOTHERMAL NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION TECHNIQUES">
      <data key="d0">ISOTHERMAL NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION TECHNIQUES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Assay platforms built around isothermal amplification chemistries (including RT-LAMP and RT-RPA) that function as portable diagnostic systems for detecting influenza gene segments without a thermocycler.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TURBIDITY READOUT">
      <data key="d0">TURBIDITY READOUT</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A change in solution cloudiness or optical density used as a detection signal in isothermal amplification assays, indicating successful amplification of influenza nucleic acids.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMARTPHONE-COMPATIBLE READOUT">
      <data key="d0">SMARTPHONE-COMPATIBLE READOUT</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A detection modality in which isothermal amplification signals (e.g., colorimetric or fluorescent) are captured and interpreted using a smartphone, supporting portable, on-farm diagnostics.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="10 TO 100 RNA COPIES PER REACTION">
      <data key="d0">10 TO 100 RNA COPIES PER REACTION</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">A detection threshold range for isothermal amplification assays targeting influenza gene segments, indicating that as few as 10–100 RNA copies in a reaction can be reliably detected.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_26,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-CAS12A ASSAY COMBINED WITH ANTI-NP ANTIBODY-BASED VIRAL RNA PURIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-CAS12A ASSAY COMBINED WITH ANTI-NP ANTIBODY-BASED VIRAL RNA PURIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An on-site H5Nx avian influenza diagnostic platform that integrates RPA amplification, PAM-independent Cas12a detection, and an anti-nucleoprotein antibody-based viral RNA purification step for enhanced specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PAPER-BASED LOOP-MEDIATED ISOTHERMAL AMPLIFICATION ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">PAPER-BASED LOOP-MEDIATED ISOTHERMAL AMPLIFICATION ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A paper-based LAMP diagnostic platform for highly pathogenic avian influenza, designed for rapid, portable, on-farm use with minimal equipment such as heat blocks or handheld devices and lyophilized reagents.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_27,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5NX AVIAN INFLUENZA">
      <data key="d0">H5NX AVIAN INFLUENZA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A group of highly pathogenic avian influenza viruses with H5 hemagglutinin and variable neuraminidase subtypes, targeted by the RPA and PAM-independent CRISPR-Cas12a assay for rapid on-site diagnosis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_27,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_88,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_89</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANTI-NP ANTIBODY-BASED VIRAL RNA PURIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">ANTI-NP ANTIBODY-BASED VIRAL RNA PURIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sample preparation step that uses antibodies against viral nucleoprotein (NP) to capture and purify viral RNA prior to CRISPR-Cas12a detection, improving assay specificity and sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_27,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_28,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_88,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_89</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT ISOTHERMAL NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION ASSISTED CRISPR/CAS DETECTION TECHNOLOGY">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT ISOTHERMAL NUCLEIC ACID AMPLIFICATION ASSISTED CRISPR/CAS DETECTION TECHNOLOGY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An integrated diagnostic format in which isothermal nucleic acid amplification and CRISPR/Cas-based detection occur in a single reaction vessel to simplify workflows and enhance specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_27,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ISOTHERMAL PLATFORMS">
      <data key="d0">ISOTHERMAL PLATFORMS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A general class of diagnostic platforms based on isothermal amplification methods, optimized for rapid, on-farm use but typically with reduced sensitivity, quantitative resolution, and specificity compared to qPCR.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MICROFLUIDIC CARTRIDGES">
      <data key="d0">MICROFLUIDIC CARTRIDGES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Cartridge-based microfluidic systems that can be integrated with isothermal and CRISPR/Cas assays to enable automated, multiplexed, and portable nucleic acid detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTIPLEXED DETECTION STRATEGIES">
      <data key="d0">MULTIPLEXED DETECTION STRATEGIES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Assay configurations that allow simultaneous detection of multiple nucleic acid targets, being combined with CRISPR/Cas and isothermal methods to improve surveillance during HPAI outbreaks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RT-RPA">
      <data key="d0">RT-RPA</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Reverse transcription recombinase polymerase amplification, an isothermal nucleic acid amplification method that converts viral RNA to DNA and amplifies it upstream of CRISPR-Cas12a detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_28,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_36,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_37,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_40,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_94</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIV">
      <data key="d0">AIV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Avian influenza virus, an airborne viral pathogen whose gene segments (such as HA and NP) are targeted by CRISPR-Cas12a assays for rapid diagnosis and subtyping.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_28,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_35,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HA GENE SEGMENT">
      <data key="d0">HA GENE SEGMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">The hemagglutinin (HA) gene region of avian influenza virus, used as a target for CRISPR guide RNAs to enable sequence-guided detection and subtyping of AIV. | The nucleoprotein (NP) gene region of avian influenza virus, used as a target for CRISPR guide RNAs to support specific detection of AIV in diagnostic assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">NP GENE SEGMENT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PAPER-BASED LATERAL FLOW STRIPS">
      <data key="d0">PAPER-BASED LATERAL FLOW STRIPS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A paper-based lateral flow format that converts Cas12a-mediated reporter cleavage into a visible colorimetric band pattern, supporting low-cost, instrument-free point-of-care readout.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMARTPHONE-INTEGRATED READOUTS">
      <data key="d0">SMARTPHONE-INTEGRATED READOUTS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Smartphone-based imaging or sensor readouts that capture and analyze Cas12a reporter signals (fluorescent or colorimetric), enabling portable and decentralized interpretation of assay results.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="2 COPIES/ΜL">
      <data key="d0">2 COPIES/ΜL</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">An approximate limit of detection indicating that CRISPR-based platforms can reliably detect as few as 2 nucleic acid copies per microliter, approaching the analytical sensitivity of qPCR.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&lt;60 MIN TIME-TO-RESULT">
      <data key="d0">&lt;60 MIN TIME-TO-RESULT</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An operational characteristic of the CRISPR-Cas12a assay indicating that the complete workflow from sample to result can typically be completed in under 60 minutes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELISA-BASED SEROLOGICAL ASSAYS FOR AVIAN INFLUENZA">
      <data key="d0">ELISA-BASED SEROLOGICAL ASSAYS FOR AVIAN INFLUENZA</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Centralized laboratory ELISA platforms (including IgM- and IgG-specific formats) used to detect antibodies against avian influenza virus antigens in poultry and other animals.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IGM-SPECIFIC ELISA">
      <data key="d0">IGM-SPECIFIC ELISA</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An ELISA format that specifically detects IgM antibodies against avian influenza virus, used to identify recent infections in birds and other animals.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IGG-BASED ELISA">
      <data key="d0">IGG-BASED ELISA</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An ELISA format that detects IgG antibodies against avian influenza virus, used to assess prior exposure history or vaccine-induced immunity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NON-VACCINE ANTIGEN-TARGETING ELISA (NP, M1)">
      <data key="d0">NON-VACCINE ANTIGEN-TARGETING ELISA (NP, M1)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">ELISA configurations that use non-vaccine antigens such as nucleoprotein (NP) and matrix protein 1 (M1) to differentiate naturally infected from vaccinated birds (DIVA capability).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEMAGGLUTINATION INHIBITION (HI) ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">HEMAGGLUTINATION INHIBITION (HI) ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A subtype-specific reference assay that measures neutralizing antibodies blocking hemagglutinin-mediated red blood cell agglutination; inexpensive and rapid but less sensitive than ELISA and with limited DIVA compatibility unless antigen panels are updated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5N1 HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">H5N1 HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A highly pathogenic H5N1 subtype of avian influenza A virus, for which isotype-specific antibody detection assays (e.g., fluorescent microsphere immunoassays) are used in epidemiological surveillance. | A group of highly pathogenic avian influenza A viruses of the H5 subtype, identified as the source of antibodies detected in raccoons in Tokachi District, Hokkaido, Japan.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_30,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_32,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_90,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_91,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_92</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">H5 SUBTYPE HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUSES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CENTRALIZED LABORATORY PROCESSING">
      <data key="d0">CENTRALIZED LABORATORY PROCESSING</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Assay execution context in which ELISA-based serological tests are performed in centralized labs by trained personnel, contributing to 2–3 hour turnaround times and delays due to sample transport and reporting.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELISA TURNAROUND TIME (2–3 HOURS)">
      <data key="d0">ELISA TURNAROUND TIME (2–3 HOURS)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Operational characteristic of ELISA-based serological assays, reflecting moderate assay duration that can contribute to diagnostic bottlenecks during outbreak surges.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HI ASSAY TURNAROUND TIME (~30 MINUTES)">
      <data key="d0">HI ASSAY TURNAROUND TIME (~30 MINUTES)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Operational characteristic of the hemagglutination inhibition assay, indicating a relatively rapid assay duration compared with ELISA.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPDATED ANTIGEN PANELS FOR HI ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">UPDATED ANTIGEN PANELS FOR HI ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Use of periodically updated hemagglutinin antigen panels in HI assays to improve DIVA compatibility and maintain subtype specificity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUBTYPE-SPECIFIC REFERENCE TESTING">
      <data key="d0">SUBTYPE-SPECIFIC REFERENCE TESTING</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The role of the HI assay as an internationally endorsed reference method for subtype-specific serological assessment of avian influenza.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LATERAL FLOW IMMUNOASSAY (LFA) PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">LATERAL FLOW IMMUNOASSAY (LFA) PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Immunochromatographic strip-based lateral flow assay platform used for portable, low-cost, rapid (10–20 min) detection of antibodies or viral antigens in avian influenza surveillance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANTIGEN DETECTION ELISA PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">ANTIGEN DETECTION ELISA PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay format used as an antigen detection platform for direct identification of avian influenza viral proteins such as HA and NP from poultry specimens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PAN-AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS AND H5/H7/H9 CRISPR/CAS13A LATERAL FLOW PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">PAN-AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS AND H5/H7/H9 CRISPR/CAS13A LATERAL FLOW PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">CRISPR/Cas13a-based lateral flow assay platform designed for rapid detection of pan-avian influenza virus and H5, H7, H9 subtypes, integrating CRISPR molecular recognition with a lateral flow readout.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NP-SPECIFIC IGG ANTIBODIES">
      <data key="d0">NP-SPECIFIC IGG ANTIBODIES</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Host immunoglobulin G antibodies specific to the conserved nucleoprotein (NP) of avian influenza virus, serving as a detectable immunological signal in some LFAs.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRAL PROTEINS HA AND NP">
      <data key="d0">VIRAL PROTEINS HA AND NP</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Avian influenza viral antigens hemagglutinin (HA) and nucleoprotein (NP) that are directly detected by antigen detection assays from poultry specimens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OROPHARYNGEAL SWAB PROCESSING">
      <data key="d0">OROPHARYNGEAL SWAB PROCESSING</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Collection and preparation of oropharyngeal swab specimens from poultry for direct antigen detection of avian influenza viral proteins.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLOACAL SWAB PROCESSING">
      <data key="d0">CLOACAL SWAB PROCESSING</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Collection and preparation of cloacal swab specimens from poultry for direct antigen detection of avian influenza viral proteins.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTRIVED NASAL SWAB SPECIMEN PREPARATION">
      <data key="d0">CONTRIVED NASAL SWAB SPECIMEN PREPARATION</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Preparation of contrived nasal swab samples spiked with H5N1 avian influenza virus for evaluating rapid antigen and point-of-care molecular tests.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LFA SPECIFICITY GREATER THAN 90%">
      <data key="d0">LFA SPECIFICITY GREATER THAN 90%</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">Performance characteristic of antigen detection platforms, including LFAs, showing specificity above 90% for avian influenza viral proteins in poultry specimens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LFA VARIABLE SENSITIVITY">
      <data key="d0">LFA VARIABLE SENSITIVITY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed variability in sensitivity of lateral flow antigen detection devices when used for identification of infected poultry during H5N1 outbreaks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAPID ANTIGEN AND POINT-OF-CARE MOLECULAR TEST EVALUATION">
      <data key="d0">RAPID ANTIGEN AND POINT-OF-CARE MOLECULAR TEST EVALUATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Validation study assessing detection of highly pathogenic avian influenza A(H5N1) in contrived nasal swab specimens using rapid antigen and point-of-care molecular assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR/CAS13A MOLECULAR RECOGNITION">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR/CAS13A MOLECULAR RECOGNITION</data>
      <data key="d1">CAS_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d2">Use of Cas13a nuclease in CRISPR-based detection of avian influenza viral RNA, coupled to a lateral flow readout for pan-AIV and H5/H7/H9 subtype detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA (HPAI) SUBTYPES">
      <data key="d0">HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA (HPAI) SUBTYPES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Highly pathogenic avian influenza A virus subtypes, exemplified by H5N1, that are detected and characterized by virus isolation for phenotypic and genotypic analysis. | A highly pathogenic avian influenza A H5N6 virus strain implicated in poultry outbreaks, with transmission occurring via respiratory droplets, aerosols, and contaminated farm environments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA (HPAI) H5N6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BIOSENSORS">
      <data key="d0">BIOSENSORS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">General biosensor devices referenced as rapid detection modalities that can be aligned with different sample matrices to detect avian influenza virus in surveillance and outbreak settings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">An airborne sample matrix listed among commonly used matrices (swabs, blood, feces, aerosols, water, feed) that require pretreatments such as filtration, lysis, or centrifugal enrichment before detection assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FILTRATION">
      <data key="d0">FILTRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A pretreatment step applied to sample matrices to remove debris and concentrate viral particles, optimizing viral recovery and reducing matrix interference prior to detection assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LYSIS">
      <data key="d0">LYSIS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sample pretreatment step used to disrupt viral particles or host cells in matrices, releasing nucleic acids for downstream detection by amplification- or CRISPR-based methods. | A sample preparation step that disrupts bacterial cells to release nucleic acids; in the ANCA method, this is not performed as a separate step because cell disruption occurs during the high-temperature reaction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b</data>
      <data key="d6">LYSIS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CENTRIFUGAL ENRICHMENT">
      <data key="d0">CENTRIFUGAL ENRICHMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A concentration step for sample matrices that enhances viral recovery by spinning down particles before molecular or biosensor-based detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ASSAY VALIDATION">
      <data key="d0">ASSAY VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The process of benchmarking and confirming the performance of diagnostic assays using reference virus strains obtained via virus isolation, supporting surveillance and emerging platforms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-CAS–BASED METHODS">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-CAS–BASED METHODS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">CRISPR-Cas–based methods are next-generation molecular diagnostic platforms that leverage CRISPR-Cas systems and guide RNAs for rapid, sequence-specific nucleic acid detection of influenza viruses, including avian influenza.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PROGRAMMABLE GUIDE RNAS">
      <data key="d0">PROGRAMMABLE GUIDE RNAS</data>
      <data key="d1">GUIDE_RNA</data>
      <data key="d2">Programmable guide RNAs are customizable CRISPR RNA components that direct CRISPR-Cas effectors to specific influenza viral nucleic acid sequences, providing target specificity in CRISPR-based diagnostic assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COLLATERAL CLEAVAGE-BASED READOUTS">
      <data key="d0">COLLATERAL CLEAVAGE-BASED READOUTS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Collateral cleavage-based readouts are reporter signals generated when activated CRISPR effectors nonspecifically cleave labeled reporter molecules, producing a measurable output that indicates the presence of target influenza viral nucleic acids.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TARGETED BIOSENSING &amp; DIAGNOSTICS">
      <data key="d0">TARGETED BIOSENSING &amp; DIAGNOSTICS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Targeted Biosensing &amp; Diagnostics is the high-specificity confirmation track in the integrated avian influenza sensing architecture, encompassing molecular assay workflows such as RT-qPCR and CRISPR-based diagnostics used to confirm AIV infection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NONTARGETED ANOMALY DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">NONTARGETED ANOMALY DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Nontargeted Anomaly Detection is the broad, early-stage screening track in the avian influenza sensing architecture, focused on detecting unusual patterns or anomalies that may indicate emerging AIV presence prior to targeted confirmation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_35,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5 SUBTYPE AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">H5 SUBTYPE AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A highly pathogenic H5 subtype avian influenza virus targeted by RT-LAMP, RT-RPA, RT-qPCR, and CRISPR-Cas12a–based assays for rapid detection and subtyping in poultry-related samples. | Avian influenza A viruses of the H9 hemagglutinin subtype, targeted by the CRISPR/Cas13a lateral flow assay for rapid subtype-specific avian influenza detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_36,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_40,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_91,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_94</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">H9 SUBTYPE AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-CAS12A + RT-RPA ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-CAS12A + RT-RPA ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A molecular diagnostic platform that combines RT-RPA amplification with CRISPR-Cas12a detection to provide rapid, on-site, and visual detection of H5 subtype avian influenza virus in poultry samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="6.7 COPIES/ΜL LIMIT OF DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">6.7 COPIES/ΜL LIMIT OF DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The analytical sensitivity of the CRISPR-Cas12a + RT-RPA assay, corresponding to a limit of detection as low as 6.7 viral RNA copies per microliter of reaction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&gt;97% CONCORDANCE WITH RRT-PCR AND VIRUS ISOLATION">
      <data key="d0">&gt;97% CONCORDANCE WITH RRT-PCR AND VIRUS ISOLATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation metric indicating that the CRISPR-Cas12a + RT-RPA assay shows greater than 97% agreement with reference rRT-PCR and virus isolation methods when tested on poultry samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OROPHARYNGEAL SWABS">
      <data key="d0">OROPHARYNGEAL SWABS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Collection of oropharyngeal swab specimens from birds, used as input samples for RT-LAMP and RT-RPA diagnostic assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLOACAL SWABS">
      <data key="d0">CLOACAL SWABS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Collection of cloacal swab specimens from birds, used as input samples for RT-LAMP and RT-RPA diagnostic assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="30–60 MIN ASSAY RUNTIME">
      <data key="d0">30–60 MIN ASSAY RUNTIME</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The operational runtime of RT-LAMP and RT-RPA assays performed by trained personnel using portable incubators, typically returning results within approximately 30–60 minutes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-POT RT-RPA–CAS12A PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">ONE-POT RT-RPA–CAS12A PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An integrated CRISPR-Cas12a diagnostic platform that combines reverse transcription, recombinase polymerase amplification (RT-RPA), and Cas12a-based detection in a single closed reaction for miniaturized, on-site nucleic acid testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAS13A PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">CAS13A PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas13a-based diagnostic platform that performs nucleic acid detection within enclosed, miniaturized formats for on-site use.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIOD-CRISPR">
      <data key="d0">AIOD-CRISPR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An all-in-one dual CRISPR-Cas12a assay platform that integrates amplification and CRISPR detection in a single reaction, enabling ultrasensitive and visual nucleic acid detection with sub-10-copy-per-microliter sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUB-10-COPY-PER-MICROLITER SENSITIVITY">
      <data key="d0">SUB-10-COPY-PER-MICROLITER SENSITIVITY</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">A limit of detection indicating that fewer than 10 copies of target nucleic acid per microliter can be reliably detected by platforms such as SHERLOCK, DETECTR, and AIOD-CRISPR.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENCLOSED CARTRIDGES">
      <data key="d0">ENCLOSED CARTRIDGES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Miniaturized, closed diagnostic cartridge formats that integrate amplification and CRISPR-based detection, reducing transfer steps and contamination risk for on-site testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMARTPHONE-ASSISTED READERS">
      <data key="d0">SMARTPHONE-ASSISTED READERS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Portable, smartphone-based reader systems used to interpret fluorescence, colorimetric, or lateral-flow outputs from CRISPR-based diagnostic assays in non-laboratory settings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PORTABLE FLUORIMETERS">
      <data key="d0">PORTABLE FLUORIMETERS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Compact fluorescence detection instruments used to read fluorescent signals from CRISPR-based diagnostic assays at the point of care.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FIELD-DEPLOYABLE CRISPR–CAS12A SYSTEMS INTEGRATED WITH ISOTHERMAL AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">FIELD-DEPLOYABLE CRISPR–CAS12A SYSTEMS INTEGRATED WITH ISOTHERMAL AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Portable CRISPR–Cas12a diagnostic systems that combine isothermal nucleic acid amplification (RT-RPA or RT-LAMP) with Cas12a-based detection, requiring only simple equipment for field deployment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMARTPHONE-BASED FLUORESCENT DIAGNOSTIC SYSTEM FOR HIGHLY PATHOGENIC H5N1 VIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">SMARTPHONE-BASED FLUORESCENT DIAGNOSTIC SYSTEM FOR HIGHLY PATHOGENIC H5N1 VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A smartphone-based fluorescent diagnostic platform for detecting highly pathogenic H5N1 avian influenza viruses, using a smartphone as the fluorescence reader for point-of-care testing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGHLY PATHOGENIC H5N1 VIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">HIGHLY PATHOGENIC H5N1 VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Highly pathogenic avian influenza H5N1 viruses, airborne viral pathogens relevant to poultry production and targeted by a smartphone-based fluorescent diagnostic system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_96</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FIELD STUDIES">
      <data key="d0">FIELD STUDIES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">On-farm and field evaluations of CRISPR-based diagnostics for AIV screening that assess performance, feasibility, and agreement with RT-qPCR under real-world conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMARTPHONE-BASED READER">
      <data key="d0">SMARTPHONE-BASED READER</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A smartphone-based optical readout modality used to capture and interpret fluorescence or other visual signals generated by portable diagnostic assays, including CRISPR–Cas12a and H5N1 fluorescent systems.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HANDHELD FLUORIMETER">
      <data key="d0">HANDHELD FLUORIMETER</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A portable fluorescence reader used to detect fluorescent reporter signals produced by CRISPR–Cas12a diagnostic assays after target recognition and collateral cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VISUAL DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">VISUAL DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A qualitative or semi-quantitative readout mode in which assay results are interpreted visually, often via fluorescence or color change, enabling instrument-light field deployment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&gt;95% AGREEMENT WITH RT-QPCR">
      <data key="d0">&gt;95% AGREEMENT WITH RT-QPCR</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A reported performance metric from field studies indicating that CRISPR-based diagnostics show greater than 95% concordance with RT-qPCR for on-farm AIV screening.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="45–60 MIN TOTAL ASSAY TIME">
      <data key="d0">45–60 MIN TOTAL ASSAY TIME</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The typical total runtime of the CRISPR-based diagnostic workflow, including RNA extraction and isothermal amplification, reported as approximately 45–60 minutes per test.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="USD 3–7 PER TEST">
      <data key="d0">USD 3–7 PER TEST</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The approximate reagent and consumable cost per CRISPR-based diagnostic test, reported as around USD 3–7 per assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BASIC SAMPLE HANDLING AND PIPETTING TRAINING">
      <data key="d0">BASIC SAMPLE HANDLING AND PIPETTING TRAINING</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Minimal operator training requirements for field-deployable CRISPR-based diagnostics, limited to basic sample handling and pipetting skills suitable for veterinary or extension personnel.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AVIAN (H5N1) INFLUENZA">
      <data key="d0">AVIAN (H5N1) INFLUENZA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Highly pathogenic avian influenza A(H5N1) virus, discussed as a target pathogen present in water and aerosols and challenging to detect at low viral concentrations during early infection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_39,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_40,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_43,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="E. COLI">
      <data key="d0">E. COLI</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Escherichia coli bacteria, mentioned as a co-target detected in aerosols by a capacitive, impedance-based biosensor platform. | Escherichia coli, a bacterial species referenced from prior literature as a target for integrated thermal lysis and LAMP assays on paper substrates.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_39,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_43,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,8cd80207-0825-48ce-af82-eed721eee13b</data>
      <data key="d6">E. COLI</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAPACITIVE BIOSENSOR FOR RAPID DETECTION OF AVIAN (H5N1) INFLUENZA AND E. COLI IN AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">CAPACITIVE BIOSENSOR FOR RAPID DETECTION OF AVIAN (H5N1) INFLUENZA AND E. COLI IN AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A capacitive, impedance-based biosensor platform designed for rapid detection of avian (H5N1) influenza virus and E. coli in aerosol samples, representative of optimized impedance-based biosensors.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_39,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_46,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_47,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_51,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_79</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LATERAL-FLOW FORMATS">
      <data key="d0">LATERAL-FLOW FORMATS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Conventional lateral-flow immunoassay devices used for rapid antigen detection, noted as having limited sensitivity at viral concentrations below 10³ copies mL⁻¹ in water and aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IMPEDANCE-BASED BIOSENSORS">
      <data key="d0">IMPEDANCE-BASED BIOSENSORS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A class of biosensor platforms that measure electrical impedance changes upon target binding, cited as capable of detecting viruses at concentrations below 10³ copies mL⁻¹ in water and aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRAL CONCENTRATIONS DURING EARLY INFECTION BELOW 10³ COPIES ML⁻¹ IN WATER AND AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">VIRAL CONCENTRATIONS DURING EARLY INFECTION BELOW 10³ COPIES ML⁻¹ IN WATER AND AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">A low viral load regime (&lt;10³ copies mL⁻¹) typical of early infection in water and aerosols, used as a benchmark concentration range to compare the detection capabilities and practical limits of various assay formats.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="E. COLI IN AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">E. COLI IN AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Escherichia coli bacteria present in aerosol form, mentioned as a target for rapid detection by a capacitive biosensor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEWCASTLE DISEASE VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">NEWCASTLE DISEASE VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The causative viral agent of Newcastle disease in poultry, implicitly targeted in automatic disease detection using sound technology and deep learning.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAPACITIVE AIRBORNE BIOSENSOR">
      <data key="d0">CAPACITIVE AIRBORNE BIOSENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A capacitive airborne biosensor that samples aerosols to rapidly detect pathogens such as avian influenza H5N1 and E. coli, reporting results in about 5 minutes as a biosecurity layer for real-time environmental monitoring.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ESCHERICHIA COLI (AEROSOLIZED)">
      <data key="d0">ESCHERICHIA COLI (AEROSOLIZED)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosolized Escherichia coli bacteria serving as a bacterial airborne pathogen target for the capacitive airborne biosensor in environmental biosecurity monitoring.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELECTROCHEMICAL DEVICES">
      <data key="d0">ELECTROCHEMICAL DEVICES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Electrochemical biosensing platforms that detect viral RNA or antigens directly from swabbed or environmental matrices in under one hour, complementing molecular assays in targeted surveillance workflows.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPR APTASENSOR">
      <data key="d0">SPR APTASENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A surface plasmon resonance aptamer-based biosensor designed for detection of avian influenza virus H5N1, capable of resolving a broad range of viral loads in approximately 1.5 hours.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HANDHELD NANOPORE PLATFORMS">
      <data key="d0">HANDHELD NANOPORE PLATFORMS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Portable nanopore sequencing platforms operated by laboratory staff or mobile veterinary teams that generate same-day genomic data for detection and molecular epidemiology of avian influenza A viruses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELECTROCHEMICAL IMPEDANCE BIOSENSORS FOR AIV">
      <data key="d0">ELECTROCHEMICAL IMPEDANCE BIOSENSORS FOR AIV</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Electrochemical impedance-based biosensing platforms designed for avian influenza virus (AIV) detection, typically implemented as screen-printed or 3D-printed single-use cartridges.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPTICAL BIOSENSORS FOR AIV">
      <data key="d0">OPTICAL BIOSENSORS FOR AIV</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Optical biosensing platforms for avian influenza virus (AIV) detection that rely on precise optical alignment and refractive-index stability, and are more sensitive to mechanical vibration and dust.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ON-FARM OR FIELD TESTING CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">ON-FARM OR FIELD TESTING CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Operational assay conditions in on-farm or field environments where environmental variables such as mechanical vibration, dust, and temperature are monitored and compensated during biosensor use.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE-USE CARTRIDGE FORMAT">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE-USE CARTRIDGE FORMAT</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Assay implementation format in which electrochemical impedance biosensors are used as disposable cartridges to avoid regeneration, enhance reproducibility, and prevent cross-contamination.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REGENERATED LABORATORY PROTOTYPE USE (3–5 CYCLES)">
      <data key="d0">REGENERATED LABORATORY PROTOTYPE USE (3–5 CYCLES)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Laboratory assay usage mode where electrochemical impedance biosensor prototypes are regenerated and reused 3–5 times with less than 10% signal loss.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENVIRONMENTAL OR SWAB SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">ENVIRONMENTAL OR SWAB SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Sample input context for AIV biosensing assays, referring to environmental matrices or swab-derived samples that require handling to avoid cross-contamination.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.4</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MONITORING AND COMPENSATION OF ENVIRONMENTAL VARIABLES">
      <data key="d0">MONITORING AND COMPENSATION OF ENVIRONMENTAL VARIABLES</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Operational step in which environmental factors such as mechanical vibration, dust, and thermal drift are monitored and compensated to ensure reliable biosensor performance in the field.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ASSAY TIME OF 30–60 MINUTES">
      <data key="d0">ASSAY TIME OF 30–60 MINUTES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Total assay runtime for electrochemical impedance biosensors, including incubation and readout, typically ranging from 30 to 60 minutes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FABRICATION COST OF USD 1–5 PER TEST">
      <data key="d0">FABRICATION COST OF USD 1–5 PER TEST</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Per-test cost metric for screen-printed or 3D-printed electrochemical impedance biosensor electrodes, typically between 1 and 5 US dollars.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.4</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELECTROCHEMICAL IMPEDANCE SPECTROSCOPY (EIS) SENSORS">
      <data key="d0">ELECTROCHEMICAL IMPEDANCE SPECTROSCOPY (EIS) SENSORS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Label-free electrochemical impedance biosensor platform used for rapid, on-farm avian influenza virus (AIV) surveillance, offering 10¹–10³ copies mL⁻¹ sensitivity, 30–60 min assay time, and low per-test cost.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURFACE-ENHANCED RAMAN SPECTROSCOPY (SERS) MOLECULAR FINGERPRINTING">
      <data key="d0">SURFACE-ENHANCED RAMAN SPECTROSCOPY (SERS) MOLECULAR FINGERPRINTING</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Label-free SERS-based biosensing platform that captures molecular fingerprints from environmental samples such as air, dust, and condensate for nontargeted anomaly detection of infection-related perturbations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACOUSTIC MONITORING OF RESPIRATORY/VOCAL ANOMALIES">
      <data key="d0">ACOUSTIC MONITORING OF RESPIRATORY/VOCAL ANOMALIES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Non-contact biosensing platform using microphones and acoustic feature analysis to detect respiratory and vocal anomalies in poultry, indicating respiratory distress up to ~48 hours before overt clinical signs.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 IN ENVIRONMENTAL DUST">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 IN ENVIRONMENTAL DUST</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne respiratory virus whose disintegrated components in environmental dust can be detected via machine learning-driven SERS fingerprinting.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EIS SENSOR LIMIT OF DETECTION (10¹–10³ COPIES ML⁻¹)">
      <data key="d0">EIS SENSOR LIMIT OF DETECTION (10¹–10³ COPIES ML⁻¹)</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">Analytical sensitivity range of EIS sensors, capable of detecting target nucleic acid or viral copies at concentrations between 10¹ and 10³ copies per milliliter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EIS ASSAY RUN (30–60 MIN TOTAL ASSAY TIME)">
      <data key="d0">EIS ASSAY RUN (30–60 MIN TOTAL ASSAY TIME)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Operational profile of an EIS-based assay, including incubation and readout, with a total turnaround time of 30–60 minutes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EIS LABORATORY PROTOTYPE REGENERATION">
      <data key="d0">EIS LABORATORY PROTOTYPE REGENERATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Use of regenerable EIS laboratory prototypes that can be reused 3–5 times with less than 10% signal loss, although disposable formats are preferred for field deployment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ISOTHERMAL AMPLIFICATION PLATFORMS">
      <data key="d0">ISOTHERMAL AMPLIFICATION PLATFORMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">Nucleic acid amplification methods operating at constant temperature; EIS sensors have lower per-test cost than these platforms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-BASED DETECTION PLATFORMS">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-BASED DETECTION PLATFORMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">CRISPR-associated nucleic acid detection platforms; EIS sensors offer lower per-test cost compared with these CRISPR platforms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURFACE PLASMON RESONANCE (SPR)">
      <data key="d0">SURFACE PLASMON RESONANCE (SPR)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Optical biosensing platform used as a benchmark; EIS sensors provide faster turnaround than SPR assays.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NONTARGETED ANOMALY DETECTION TRACK">
      <data key="d0">NONTARGETED ANOMALY DETECTION TRACK</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Surveillance track that flags infection-related perturbations without prior knowledge of the causative agent, integrating SERS molecular fingerprinting and acoustic monitoring.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-BASED NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-BASED NUCLEIC ACID DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">CRISPR-based nucleic acid detection workflows, typically coupled to amplification, referenced as molecular diagnostics that are complemented by biosensors for environmental surveillance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR">
      <data key="d0">AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">An environmental matrix (air/aerosols) from which samples are collected and conditioned prior to biosensor-based detection within the surveillance stack.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WATER">
      <data key="d0">WATER</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">An environmental matrix (water) that can be sampled and processed as part of sample preparation for biosensor-based environmental surveillance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.4</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DUST">
      <data key="d0">DUST</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">An environmental matrix (dust) that can be collected and processed as part of sample preparation for biosensor-based environmental surveillance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.4</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ON-FARM CONFIRMATION ASSAY RUNS">
      <data key="d0">ON-FARM CONFIRMATION ASSAY RUNS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Execution of biosensor assays directly on farms to confirm anomalies flagged by nontargeted screens, representing real-world assay runs on environmental samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TARGETED BIOSENSING AND MOLECULAR DIAGNOSTICS">
      <data key="d0">TARGETED BIOSENSING AND MOLECULAR DIAGNOSTICS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A targeted diagnostic platform combining electrochemical and optical biosensors with isothermal amplification ± CRISPR and RT-qPCR to provide high-specificity pathogen detection and subtyping from swabs, water, surfaces, and targeted air concentrates.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FUSION AND TRIAGE DECISION NODE">
      <data key="d0">FUSION AND TRIAGE DECISION NODE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A decision node that integrates outputs from targeted and nontargeted platforms using rule sets (e.g., anomaly alert triggers confirmatory testing) to reduce false alarms and shorten time-to-action.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPTICAL BIOSENSORS">
      <data key="d0">OPTICAL BIOSENSORS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Biosensors that use optical readouts to detect pathogens and enable subtyping as part of the targeted diagnostic platform.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-BASED DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-BASED DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">CRISPR-associated nucleic acid detection used in conjunction with isothermal amplification (± CRISPR) to enhance specificity for pathogen detection and subtyping.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACOUSTIC MONITORING OF COUGHS, SNEEZES, AND VOCAL ANOMALIES">
      <data key="d0">ACOUSTIC MONITORING OF COUGHS, SNEEZES, AND VOCAL ANOMALIES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An acoustic sensing platform using distributed microphones to monitor coughs, sneezes, and vocal anomalies for nontargeted anomaly detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELECTROCHEMICAL IMPEDANCE SPECTROSCOPY (EIS)">
      <data key="d0">ELECTROCHEMICAL IMPEDANCE SPECTROSCOPY (EIS)</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An electrochemical technique widely used in electrochemical biosensors for label-free, low-power pathogen detection by measuring impedance changes at the sensor interface.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAPACITIVE BIOSENSOR INTEGRATED WITH A WET-CYCLONE BIOAEROSOL SAMPLER">
      <data key="d0">CAPACITIVE BIOSENSOR INTEGRATED WITH A WET-CYCLONE BIOAEROSOL SAMPLER</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A capacitive, impedance-based biosensing platform coupled to a wet-cyclone bioaerosol sampler, enabling near real-time detection of airborne pathogens such as H5N1 influenza in aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE H5N1">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE H5N1</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosolized H5N1 avian influenza virus present in air, serving as a target pathogen for near real-time detection by the capacitive biosensor–wet cyclone platform.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POULTRY SAMPLE ASSAY RUNS">
      <data key="d0">POULTRY SAMPLE ASSAY RUNS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Assay executions performed on common poultry-related sample types, including oropharyngeal/cloacal swabs, tracheal swabs, drinking water, and surface wipes, to detect avian influenza virus using impedance-based biosensing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WET-CYCLONE BIOAEROSOL SAMPLER">
      <data key="d0">WET-CYCLONE BIOAEROSOL SAMPLER</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A wet-cyclone based bioaerosol sampling and concentration step that collects airborne particles into a liquid phase prior to capacitive biosensor measurement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IMPEDANCE-BASED QUANTITATIVE SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">IMPEDANCE-BASED QUANTITATIVE SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">An impedance-derived quantitative readout across a range of frequencies, reflecting changes in the electrical double layer upon target binding and reporting both presence and approximate concentration of analytes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAPACITIVE BIOSENSOR SYSTEM FOR AIRBORNE H5N1 DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">CAPACITIVE BIOSENSOR SYSTEM FOR AIRBORNE H5N1 DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An electrochemical capacitive biosensor platform using a Prussian-blue/graphene-oxide (PB/GO) sensing interface, functionalized with aptamers or antibodies, designed to rapidly detect airborne H5N1 influenza and E. coli from aerosol samples with quasi-quantitative readouts in under 5 minutes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PB/GO-BASED SENSOR">
      <data key="d0">PB/GO-BASED SENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">The Prussian-blue/graphene-oxide (PB/GO)-based capacitive sensor element in which PB and GO are co-deposited to form a redox-active capacitive layer used for molecular recognition of airborne pathogens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WET CYCLONE PARTICLE SAMPLER">
      <data key="d0">WET CYCLONE PARTICLE SAMPLER</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A wet cyclone-based aerosol particle sampler used to capture aerosols containing pathogens released from infected animals, providing a liquid sample input for the downstream capacitive biosensing unit.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-BASED NUCLEIC ACID ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-BASED NUCLEIC ACID ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-based nucleic acid detection assay suggested as an orthogonal molecular confirmation method alongside qPCR to validate capacitive biosensor results for airborne pathogen detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LAB-GENERATED H5N1 AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">LAB-GENERATED H5N1 AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Laboratory-generated aerosols containing H5N1 used as test samples in experimental runs to characterize the performance and linearity of the capacitive biosensor system, instead of real poultry-house air.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AGREEMENT WITH PCR">
      <data key="d0">AGREEMENT WITH PCR</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Validation outcome indicating that biosensor readouts were consistent with PCR results, supporting the analytical accuracy of the capacitive biosensor measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REPLICATE MEASUREMENTS">
      <data key="d0">REPLICATE MEASUREMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Multiple repeated runs of the capacitive biosensor assay on similar aerosol samples, showing consistent results and supporting the reproducibility of the platform.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QUASI-QUANTIFICATION OF H5N1 DIRECTLY FROM AIR SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">QUASI-QUANTIFICATION OF H5N1 DIRECTLY FROM AIR SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Performance characterization indicating that the capacitive biosensor can provide semi-quantitative measurements of H5N1 viral load directly from captured air samples, supported by linear response across serial dilutions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STRONG LINEARITY ACROSS SERIAL DILUTIONS (R² ≥ 0.95)">
      <data key="d0">STRONG LINEARITY ACROSS SERIAL DILUTIONS (R² ≥ 0.95)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Validation result showing that the biosensor’s capacitive readout scales linearly with H5N1 concentration over serial dilutions, with coefficient of determination R² ≥ 0.95, indicating robust analytical performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="READOUTS IN &lt;5 MIN">
      <data key="d0">READOUTS IN &lt;5 MIN</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Measured time-to-result of under 5 minutes for the capacitive biosensor when detecting airborne H5N1 and E. coli from aerosol samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BASELINE CAPACITANCE SHIFTS DUE TO ENVIRONMENTAL FACTORS">
      <data key="d0">BASELINE CAPACITANCE SHIFTS DUE TO ENVIRONMENTAL FACTORS</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">Description of how environmental factors such as particle size, humidity, and co-collected particulates can alter baseline capacitance in the capacitive biosensor, potentially affecting specificity and necessitating orthogonal molecular confirmation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5N1 BIOSENSOR LIMIT OF DETECTION (LOD)">
      <data key="d0">H5N1 BIOSENSOR LIMIT OF DETECTION (LOD)</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The experimentally determined limit of detection for H5N1 using the capacitive biosensor, serving as the decision threshold for classifying samples as positive or negative based on normalized ΔC%.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WET CYCLONE SAMPLER">
      <data key="d0">WET CYCLONE SAMPLER</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">An aerosol collection and concentration step that captures airborne particles, including H5N1, into a liquid medium prior to analysis by the capacitive biosensor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SERIAL DILUTIONS IN PBS">
      <data key="d0">SERIAL DILUTIONS IN PBS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation procedure in which H5N1 is serially diluted in phosphate-buffered saline to generate a concentration series for assessing biosensor sensitivity, linearity (R² ≥ 0.95), and statistical significance (t-test, p &lt; 0.01).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QUASI-QUANTIFICATION OF H5N1 AEROSOLS COLLECTED VIA THE WET CYCLONE SAMPLER">
      <data key="d0">QUASI-QUANTIFICATION OF H5N1 AEROSOLS COLLECTED VIA THE WET CYCLONE SAMPLER</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A decision workflow and associated assay runs in which aerosol samples collected by a wet cyclone sampler are tested undiluted, 10× diluted, and 100× diluted to classify airborne H5N1 concentrations relative to the biosensor’s limit of detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NORMALIZED ΔC% RESPONSE">
      <data key="d0">NORMALIZED ΔC% RESPONSE</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The normalized percentage change in capacitance (ΔC%) measured by the capacitive biosensor, used as the quantitative electrochemical reporter signal for H5N1 detection, sensitivity assessment, and quasi-quantification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASKLESS, LASER-PATTERNED PMMA MICROFLUIDIC APTASENSOR WITH INTEGRATED ELECTRODES">
      <data key="d0">MASKLESS, LASER-PATTERNED PMMA MICROFLUIDIC APTASENSOR WITH INTEGRATED ELECTRODES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A microfluidic aptamer-based electrochemical biosensor fabricated on PMMA using maskless laser patterning with integrated electrodes, designed for quantitative detection of H5N1-target DNA sequences.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FE₃O₄@TMU-8 NANOCOMPOSITE REDOX-RECYCLING AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">FE₃O₄@TMU-8 NANOCOMPOSITE REDOX-RECYCLING AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">An electrochemical signal amplification strategy in the PMMA microfluidic aptasensor that uses an Fe₃O₄@TMU-8 nanocomposite to catalyze redox recycling of [Ru(NH₃)₆]³⁺ (RuHex), thereby enhancing the measurable electrochemical response for H5N1-target DNA detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MICROFLUIDIC ELECTROCHEMICAL CHIP USING CATALYTIC REDOX-RECYCLING FOR INFLUENZA VIRUS DNA">
      <data key="d0">MICROFLUIDIC ELECTROCHEMICAL CHIP USING CATALYTIC REDOX-RECYCLING FOR INFLUENZA VIRUS DNA</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A microfluidic electrochemical biosensor platform that uses an Fe₃O₄@TMU-8 nanocomposite to catalytically redox-recycle RuHex for quantitative detection of H5N1-target DNA sequences, achieving high sensitivity, good reproducibility, and long-term stability, and positioned as a high-sensitivity confirmatory channel in avian influenza virus workflows.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5N1 AVIAN INFLUENZA A VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">H5N1 AVIAN INFLUENZA A VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">An avian influenza A virus subtype (H5N1), an RNA virus that can be transmitted via aerosols and whose genome-derived DNA sequences are the specific nucleic-acid targets detected by the described microfluidic electrochemical chip.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LIMIT OF DETECTION 0.16 FM">
      <data key="d0">LIMIT OF DETECTION 0.16 FM</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The reported limit of detection (0.16 femtomolar) for the microfluidic electrochemical chip when quantifying H5N1-target DNA sequences under optimized conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LINEAR RANGE 1 FM–1 NM">
      <data key="d0">LINEAR RANGE 1 FM–1 NM</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The quantitative dynamic range of the microfluidic electrochemical chip for H5N1-target DNA, spanning concentrations from 1 femtomolar to 1 nanomolar under optimized assay conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REVERSE TRANSCRIPTION">
      <data key="d0">REVERSE TRANSCRIPTION</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A preparatory step converting H5N1 viral RNA into complementary DNA prior to detection, required because the microfluidic electrochemical chip detects DNA targets rather than RNA.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THERMAL DENATURATION">
      <data key="d0">THERMAL DENATURATION</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sample-preparation step in which nucleic acids are thermally denatured to separate strands, enabling subsequent hybridization of H5N1-target sequences on the electrochemical chip.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NUCLEIC-ACID HYBRIDIZATION AT APTAMER INTERFACE">
      <data key="d0">NUCLEIC-ACID HYBRIDIZATION AT APTAMER INTERFACE</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A nucleic-acid hybridization step at the aptamer-functionalized interface of the chip that enables sequence-specific binding of H5N1-target DNA and modulates the RuHex redox-recycling current for quantitative readout.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RUHEX ELECTROCHEMICAL SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">RUHEX ELECTROCHEMICAL SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The electrochemical current generated by catalytic redox-recycling of the RuHex complex bound to the nucleic-acid phosphate backbone, which is modulated by target hybridization and used as the quantitative reporter signal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPIKED FOOD MATRICES">
      <data key="d0">SPIKED FOOD MATRICES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation context in which the microfluidic electrochemical chip was tested using food samples spiked with H5N1-target nucleic acids to demonstrate applicability, reproducibility, and long-term stability in complex sample backgrounds.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTIMODAL AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS WORKFLOW">
      <data key="d0">MULTIMODAL AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS WORKFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A broader diagnostic workflow for avian influenza virus that integrates multiple sensing modalities, within which the described microfluidic electrochemical chip is positioned as a high-sensitivity confirmatory channel rather than a frontline on-farm screen.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENCE-BASED BIOSENSOR ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENCE-BASED BIOSENSOR ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An optical biosensing format where targets are reported by emission from fluorescent dyes or nanoprobes; binding events modulate fluorescence intensity or lifetime, enabling very high sensitivity down to the attomolar range but susceptible to quenching, spectral overlap, and autofluorescence in complex matrices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_53</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPTICAL REPORTER EMISSION (DYE OR NANOPROBE)">
      <data key="d0">OPTICAL REPORTER EMISSION (DYE OR NANOPROBE)</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescent emission from dyes or nanoprobes used as the readout in fluorescence-based biosensor assays, where changes in intensity or lifetime indicate target binding events.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_53</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURFACE PLASMON RESONANCE OPTICAL SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">SURFACE PLASMON RESONANCE OPTICAL SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The resonance shift in reflected light intensity or angle caused by refractive index changes at a thin metal film in SPR biosensors, used as a label-free optical readout of target binding kinetics.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_53</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ATTOMOLAR DETECTION SENSITIVITY">
      <data key="d0">ATTOMOLAR DETECTION SENSITIVITY</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">A very low limit of detection achievable by fluorescence-based biosensor assays, corresponding to detection of analyte concentrations in the attomolar range.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_53</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MINIATURIZED 3D PRINTED SPR BIOSENSOR">
      <data key="d0">MINIATURIZED 3D PRINTED SPR BIOSENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A miniaturized, 3D-printed surface plasmon resonance (SPR) biosensor platform that provides optical readouts for rapid detection of H5N1 avian influenza virus in PBS-diluted culture medium, with a reported limit of detection of 4.3 × 10⁴ copies/mL and assay time under 12 minutes. It is designed for potential portable use but currently depends on stable optical alignment and specialized readout instrumentation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H1N1">
      <data key="d0">H1N1</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">An influenza A virus subtype (H1N1) used as a non-target control virus in specificity testing of the H5N1-focused SPR biosensor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="4.3 × 10⁴ COPIES/ML">
      <data key="d0">4.3 × 10⁴ COPIES/ML</data>
      <data key="d1">LIMIT_OF_DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d2">The reported limit of detection (LoD) of the miniaturized 3D printed SPR biosensor for H5N1 avian influenza virus, corresponding to 4.3 × 10⁴ viral copies per milliliter of sample.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5N1 SPECIFICITY PROFILE WITH H1N1, H3N2, AND H7N9 CONTROLS">
      <data key="d0">H5N1 SPECIFICITY PROFILE WITH H1N1, H3N2, AND H7N9 CONTROLS</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">The specificity profile of the H5N1-targeting SPR biosensor, evaluated using PBS-diluted culture medium containing non-target influenza A subtypes H1N1, H3N2, and H7N9 to assess cross-reactivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PBS-DILUTED CULTURE MEDIUM (CELL-CULTURE FLUID) SPIKED WITH H5N1 AIV">
      <data key="d0">PBS-DILUTED CULTURE MEDIUM (CELL-CULTURE FLUID) SPIKED WITH H5N1 AIV</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sample preparation step in which cell-culture fluid is diluted with PBS and spiked with H5N1 avian influenza virus, providing a controlled matrix for evaluating the biosensor’s analytical performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PBS-DILUTED CULTURE MEDIUM CONTAINING H1N1, H3N2, AND H7N9">
      <data key="d0">PBS-DILUTED CULTURE MEDIUM CONTAINING H1N1, H3N2, AND H7N9</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A prepared sample matrix consisting of PBS-diluted culture medium containing non-target influenza A subtypes H1N1, H3N2, and H7N9, used as specificity control samples for the H5N1 SPR biosensor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEAR-INFRARED (NIR) ORGANIC PHOTODETECTOR">
      <data key="d0">NEAR-INFRARED (NIR) ORGANIC PHOTODETECTOR</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">An organic photodetector operating in the near-infrared range that is coupled to the SPR biosensor to transduce its optical response into an electrical signal, enabling compact optical readout.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ORGANIC PHOTODETECTOR OPTIMIZED FOR 980 NM WAVELENGTH">
      <data key="d0">ORGANIC PHOTODETECTOR OPTIMIZED FOR 980 NM WAVELENGTH</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">A configuration of the NIR organic photodetector tuned to a 980 nm wavelength, which enhances responsivity and signal-to-noise performance for the SPR biosensor’s optical output.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BENCH VALIDATION WITH SPIKED LIQUID SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">BENCH VALIDATION WITH SPIKED LIQUID SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Laboratory validation of the SPR biosensor using PBS-diluted culture medium spiked with H5N1 and with non-target influenza subtypes, to characterize limit of detection and specificity under controlled conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EIS-BASED BIOSENSOR">
      <data key="d0">EIS-BASED BIOSENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) biosensor platform used for decentralized AIV surveillance, sensitive to nonspecific impedance drift from environmental factors and biointerface instability.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPTICAL BIOSENSOR PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">OPTICAL BIOSENSOR PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Optical biosensing platform requiring stable optical alignment and refractive index control for AIV-related measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENCE BIOSENSOR READOUT">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENCE BIOSENSOR READOUT</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Fluorescence-based reporter signal used in biosensor assays, affected by quenching and autofluorescence in complex matrices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COLORIMETRIC BIOSENSOR READOUT">
      <data key="d0">COLORIMETRIC BIOSENSOR READOUT</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Colorimetric reporter signal format for biosensor assays, subject to subjective thresholding in dusty or complex sample matrices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISPOSABLE CARTRIDGE WITH ON-BOARD FILTRATION OR ENRICHMENT">
      <data key="d0">DISPOSABLE CARTRIDGE WITH ON-BOARD FILTRATION OR ENRICHMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Integrated sample preparation step in disposable cartridges that perform on-board filtration or enrichment to reduce matrix-induced interference for biosensors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ON-BOARD POSITIVE AND NEGATIVE CONTROLS WITH INTERNAL STANDARDS">
      <data key="d0">ON-BOARD POSITIVE AND NEGATIVE CONTROLS WITH INTERNAL STANDARDS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Built-in assay controls and internal standards incorporated into biosensor workflows to support calibration, drift correction, and quality assurance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CALIBRATION TRANSFER AND DRIFT CORRECTION PROTOCOL">
      <data key="d0">CALIBRATION TRANSFER AND DRIFT CORRECTION PROTOCOL</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Operational protocol layer that applies calibration transfer and drift correction to biosensor measurements to maintain accuracy over time and across devices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BLINDED BENCHMARKING AGAINST QUANTITATIVE PCR">
      <data key="d0">BLINDED BENCHMARKING AGAINST QUANTITATIVE PCR</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Validation procedure where biosensor outputs are compared in a blinded fashion to quantitative PCR results on spiked and field poultry house samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BLINDED BENCHMARKING AGAINST CRISPR ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">BLINDED BENCHMARKING AGAINST CRISPR ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Validation procedure where biosensor outputs are compared in a blinded fashion to CRISPR-based molecular assay results on spiked and field poultry house samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LABEL-FREE SERS ANOMALY DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">LABEL-FREE SERS ANOMALY DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Label-free surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy platform that generates holistic vibrational fingerprints from barn aerosols and dust for nontargeted anomaly detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACOUSTIC MONITORING ANOMALY DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">ACOUSTIC MONITORING ANOMALY DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Acoustic monitoring platform that quantifies respiratory and vocal changes in poultry for nontargeted anomaly detection of potential AIV infection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLASSIFIER SCORE FOR NONTARGETED SCREENING">
      <data key="d0">CLASSIFIER SCORE FOR NONTARGETED SCREENING</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Quantitative classifier output derived from label-free SERS and acoustic monitoring signals, used to trigger targeted diagnostic tests when thresholds are exceeded.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LABEL-FREE SERS PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">LABEL-FREE SERS PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS) biosensing platform that uses plasmonic nanostructures to generate ultrasensitive, non-targeted molecular fingerprints from aerosol or dust samples, enabling detection and classification of infection-induced biochemical signatures without virus-specific probes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SERS RAMAN SPECTRAL FINGERPRINT">
      <data key="d0">SERS RAMAN SPECTRAL FINGERPRINT</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The complex Raman spectral pattern generated from laser interrogation of aerosol or dust samples on plasmonic nanostructures, serving as a unique molecular fingerprint that reflects the presence of virus particles or infection-induced host metabolic changes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MACHINE-LEARNING-BASED SERS VIRUS CLASSIFIER">
      <data key="d0">MACHINE-LEARNING-BASED SERS VIRUS CLASSIFIER</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">An assay run in which SERS-generated Raman spectral fingerprints from aerosol or dust samples are processed by machine learning algorithms to classify and distinguish multiple respiratory viruses with high accuracy, typically exceeding 90% in classification tasks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-ACCURACY SERS VIRUS CLASSIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-ACCURACY SERS VIRUS CLASSIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Performance characterization of the machine-learning-based SERS virus classifier, demonstrating often greater than 90% accuracy in distinguishing multiple respiratory viruses without the use of virus-specific antibodies or primers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LABEL-FREE SERS DETECTION OF PATHOGENIC ENVELOPED VIRUSES USING MACHINE LEARNING DATA ANALYTICS">
      <data key="d0">LABEL-FREE SERS DETECTION OF PATHOGENIC ENVELOPED VIRUSES USING MACHINE LEARNING DATA ANALYTICS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A label-free biosensing platform that uses surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS) combined with machine-learning-based spectral classification to detect and differentiate pathogenic enveloped viruses in complex samples (e.g., aerosols, dust, animal samples) without virus-specific antibodies or primers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MACHINE LEARNING-DRIVEN SERS FINGERPRINTING OF DISINTEGRATED VIRAL COMPONENTS FOR RAPID DETECTION OF SARS-COV-2 IN ENVIRONMENTAL DUST">
      <data key="d0">MACHINE LEARNING-DRIVEN SERS FINGERPRINTING OF DISINTEGRATED VIRAL COMPONENTS FOR RAPID DETECTION OF SARS-COV-2 IN ENVIRONMENTAL DUST</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A specific implementation of a SERS-based biosensor in which viral particles in environmental dust are gently lysed, their components concentrated into SERS hotspots on a nanostructured substrate, and the resulting Raman fingerprints are analyzed by multivariate machine learning to rapidly detect and classify SARS-CoV-2 and other viruses in dust samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRION DISINTEGRATION">
      <data key="d0">VIRION DISINTEGRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sample preparation step in which intact virions in aerosol or dust samples are broken into constituent proteins, lipids, and nucleic acids, enhancing the richness and detectability of the Raman signal for SERS-based detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GENTLE LYSIS PROTOCOL">
      <data key="d0">GENTLE LYSIS PROTOCOL</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A mild lysis procedure applied to aerosol or dust samples to achieve virion disintegration without extensive degradation, releasing viral proteins, lipids, and nucleic acids that contribute to stronger and more informative SERS spectra.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONCENTRATION INTO DENSELY PACKED HOTSPOTS ON A NANOSTRUCTURED SERS SUBSTRATE">
      <data key="d0">CONCENTRATION INTO DENSELY PACKED HOTSPOTS ON A NANOSTRUCTURED SERS SUBSTRATE</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sample preparation step in which released viral components are localized and concentrated into densely packed electromagnetic hotspots on a nanostructured SERS substrate, increasing local analyte density and boosting SERS sensitivity to trace viral levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OVER 86% CLASSIFICATION ACCURACY">
      <data key="d0">OVER 86% CLASSIFICATION ACCURACY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation performance metric indicating that the SERS–machine learning method can distinguish SARS-CoV-2, influenza A, and Zika virus signatures within a mixed environmental dust matrix with more than 86% multi-class classification accuracy. | A reported performance level indicating that label-free SERS detection combined with machine learning can achieve high accuracy, often exceeding 90% in virus classification tasks when used as a broad surveillance tool in animal populations without virus-specific antibodies or primers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
      <data key="d6">OVER 90% CLASSIFICATION ACCURACY</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SERS-BASED VIRAL DETECTION WORKFLOW IN CLEAN CELL SUPERNATANT">
      <data key="d0">SERS-BASED VIRAL DETECTION WORKFLOW IN CLEAN CELL SUPERNATANT</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS) workflow applied to clean cell supernatant, using average SERS spectra and PCA-LDA to differentiate SARS-CoV-2, Influenza A, and Zika virus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SERS-BASED VIRAL DETECTION WORKFLOW IN ENVIRONMENTAL DUST MATRIX">
      <data key="d0">SERS-BASED VIRAL DETECTION WORKFLOW IN ENVIRONMENTAL DUST MATRIX</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A SERS workflow applied to a complex environmental dust matrix, where distinct spectral fingerprints, PCA-LDA scores, and confusion-matrix analysis enable successful identification of viruses despite a noisy background.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SERS ANALYSIS OF POULTRY HOUSE AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">SERS ANALYSIS OF POULTRY HOUSE AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Application of SERS to poultry house aerosols, where complex poultry dust (dander, feed, microbes, chemical fumes) contributes to Raman background, requiring advanced computational deconvolution to distinguish virus-positive spectra from baseline barn air.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE-SHOT SERS SENSOR WITH MACHINE LEARNING">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE-SHOT SERS SENSOR WITH MACHINE LEARNING</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A single-shot, receptor-free SERS sensor that uses machine learning to rapidly detect and classify multiple respiratory viruses, including influenza, in patient swab samples with approximately 97% accuracy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POULTRY HOUSE AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">POULTRY HOUSE AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Collected aerosols from poultry houses, containing poultry dust with dander, feed, microbes, and chemical fumes, serving as a complex sample matrix for SERS-based viral detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENVIRONMENTAL DUST MATRIX">
      <data key="d0">ENVIRONMENTAL DUST MATRIX</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A complex environmental dust sample used for SERS-based viral detection, characterized by a noisy Raman background that must be computationally deconvolved.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLEAN CELL SUPERNATANT">
      <data key="d0">CLEAN CELL SUPERNATANT</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A relatively simple, low-background matrix used to demonstrate SERS-based differentiation of SARS-CoV-2, Influenza A, and Zika virus via average spectra and PCA-LDA.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BASELINE BARN AIR">
      <data key="d0">BASELINE BARN AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Background air in poultry barns that provides the baseline SERS spectral profile against which virus-positive spectra are differentiated using pattern recognition algorithms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISTINCT SPECTRAL FINGERPRINTS">
      <data key="d0">DISTINCT SPECTRAL FINGERPRINTS</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Unique SERS spectral patterns generated by different viruses, enabling their identification and classification in both clean and dusty matrices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AVERAGE SERS SPECTRA">
      <data key="d0">AVERAGE SERS SPECTRA</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Processed SERS spectral signals averaged over measurements, used as input features for PCA-LDA to differentiate SARS-CoV-2, Influenza A, and Zika virus in clean matrices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PCA-LDA SCORES">
      <data key="d0">PCA-LDA SCORES</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Numerical outputs from principal component analysis followed by linear discriminant analysis applied to SERS spectra, providing class-separating features for virus identification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONFUSION MATRIX SHOWING HIGH CLASSIFICATION ACCURACY">
      <data key="d0">CONFUSION MATRIX SHOWING HIGH CLASSIFICATION ACCURACY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A performance evaluation output summarizing true and predicted virus classes for the SERS-based workflow in dust matrices, demonstrating high classification accuracy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="APPROXIMATELY 97% ACCURACY CLASSIFICATION OF MULTIPLE RESPIRATORY VIRUSES IN PATIENT SWAB SAMPLES">
      <data key="d0">APPROXIMATELY 97% ACCURACY CLASSIFICATION OF MULTIPLE RESPIRATORY VIRUSES IN PATIENT SWAB SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Reported validation result for a single-shot, receptor-free SERS sensor with machine learning, indicating approximately 97% accuracy in classifying multiple respiratory viruses, including influenza, from patient swab samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PORTABLE SERS-BASED AEROSOL SENSOR">
      <data key="d0">PORTABLE SERS-BASED AEROSOL SENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A portable surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS) aerosol sensing platform that continuously samples air in poultry houses, acquires Raman spectra from airborne biological particles, and uses machine-learning analysis of spectral fingerprints for early warning of respiratory viral infections such as avian influenza.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MACHINE-LEARNING-ENABLED SERS PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">MACHINE-LEARNING-ENABLED SERS PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A SERS sensing platform integrated with machine learning algorithms that learn spectral differences in complex biological media to rapidly detect and classify multiple respiratory viruses from aerosols in near real-time, without requiring receptor-based targeting.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AVIAN INFLUENZA">
      <data key="d0">AVIAN INFLUENZA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">An airborne respiratory viral pathogen affecting poultry; in this context it is a target for early detection in chicken houses using SERS-based aerosol surveillance to provide early outbreak warnings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_59,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_75,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_85,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_86,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_89</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FIVE RESPIRATORY VIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">FIVE RESPIRATORY VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A group of five distinct respiratory viruses that were rapidly detected and classified in a single shot by a machine-learning-integrated SERS sensing platform, demonstrating multiplex viral detection capability in aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRADITIONAL QPCR">
      <data key="d0">TRADITIONAL QPCR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A targeted nucleic acid amplification-based diagnostic platform used as a confirmatory test to identify specific pathogens after non-targeted SERS surveillance flags abnormal spectral fingerprints in air samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANTIGEN ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">ANTIGEN ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Targeted immunoassay platforms that detect specific viral antigens; in this context they are used as confirmatory tests following broad, non-targeted SERS-based aerosol surveillance that first detects abnormal spectral signatures.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SERS-BASED BIOSENSING FOR BIOLOGICAL AND ENVIRONMENTAL MATRICES">
      <data key="d0">SERS-BASED BIOSENSING FOR BIOLOGICAL AND ENVIRONMENTAL MATRICES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A surface-enhanced Raman scattering (SERS) biosensor platform applied to aerosols on filters, surface wipes, fecal suspensions, and liquid extracts from oropharyngeal or cloacal swabs, enabling near real-time Tier 1 early warning of infection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PORTABLE RAMAN SPECTROMETERS WITH FLEXIBLE NANOSTRUCTURED SUBSTRATES">
      <data key="d0">PORTABLE RAMAN SPECTROMETERS WITH FLEXIBLE NANOSTRUCTURED SUBSTRATES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An on-farm SERS biosensing setup combining portable Raman spectrometers with flexible gold- or silver-nanostructured substrates in sealed cartridges, providing minute- to hour-level response times under moderate field conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CHEMOMETRIC AND MACHINE-LEARNING SPECTRAL CLASSIFIERS">
      <data key="d0">CHEMOMETRIC AND MACHINE-LEARNING SPECTRAL CLASSIFIERS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Data-driven analysis layer for SERS that classifies spectral fingerprints using chemometric or machine-learning models to distinguish true viral signatures from environmental background and improve diagnostic accuracy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACOUSTIC MONITORING OF FLOCK SOUNDSCAPES">
      <data key="d0">ACOUSTIC MONITORING OF FLOCK SOUNDSCAPES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A noninvasive biosensing platform that analyzes poultry flock soundscapes, decomposing vocal and respiration-related bioacoustic signals into time–frequency features and classifying health states with machine learning for early detection of respiratory and behavioral changes associated with infection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE VIRAL PATHOGENS IN POULTRY ENVIRONMENTS">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE VIRAL PATHOGENS IN POULTRY ENVIRONMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Viral agents present in aerosols and environmental matrices in poultry settings, whose spectral signatures can be detected by SERS-based biosensing for early warning of infection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY INFECTIONS IN POULTRY FLOCKS">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY INFECTIONS IN POULTRY FLOCKS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory disease conditions in poultry, including those caused by airborne viral pathogens, that manifest as changes in flock vocalizations and respiration-related sounds detectable by acoustic monitoring.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SERS SPECTRAL FINGERPRINT SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">SERS SPECTRAL FINGERPRINT SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">The enhanced Raman spectral fingerprint generated from biological and environmental matrices on gold- or silver-nanostructured substrates, used to identify viral signatures against environmental background.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BIOACOUSTIC TIME–FREQUENCY FEATURE SIGNAL">
      <data key="d0">BIOACOUSTIC TIME–FREQUENCY FEATURE SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Time–frequency features extracted from flock vocal emissions and respiration-related sounds, serving as the reporter signal for machine-learning-based health state classification in acoustic monitoring.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SERS NEAR REAL-TIME ANALYSIS WORKFLOW (10–30 MIN)">
      <data key="d0">SERS NEAR REAL-TIME ANALYSIS WORKFLOW (10–30 MIN)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The end-to-end SERS analysis process from specimen collection to result, typically requiring 10–30 minutes and enabling near real-time Tier 1 early warning in field settings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ON-FARM ACOUSTIC HEALTH STATE CLASSIFICATION RUN">
      <data key="d0">ON-FARM ACOUSTIC HEALTH STATE CLASSIFICATION RUN</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The operational run of the acoustic monitoring system that continuously records flock soundscapes via distributed microphones and applies machine-learning models to classify health states.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SERS PERFORMANCE UNDER MODERATE FIELD CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">SERS PERFORMANCE UNDER MODERATE FIELD CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Empirical demonstration that SERS using gold- or silver-nanostructured substrates in sealed cartridges yields reproducible performance under moderate field conditions despite influences from humidity, dust, and matrix turbidity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IMPROVED SERS DIAGNOSTIC ACCURACY VIA ML CLASSIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">IMPROVED SERS DIAGNOSTIC ACCURACY VIA ML CLASSIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">Validation evidence that classifying SERS spectral fingerprints with chemometric or machine-learning models improves accuracy by better distinguishing true viral signatures from environmental background.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOLS COLLECTED ON FILTERS">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLS COLLECTED ON FILTERS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sampling and preparation step in which airborne particles are captured on filters to provide aerosol samples for SERS analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURFACE WIPES">
      <data key="d0">SURFACE WIPES</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A sampling step where environmental surfaces are wiped to collect residues and contaminants for subsequent SERS-based detection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FECAL SUSPENSIONS">
      <data key="d0">FECAL SUSPENSIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Prepared suspensions of fecal material used as a matrix for SERS-based detection of pathogens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LIQUID EXTRACTS FROM OROPHARYNGEAL OR CLOACAL SWABS">
      <data key="d0">LIQUID EXTRACTS FROM OROPHARYNGEAL OR CLOACAL SWABS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Liquid sample preparations obtained by extracting material from oropharyngeal or cloacal swabs, serving as input matrices for SERS analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CHICKEN SOUND CONVOLUTIONAL NEURAL NETWORK (CSCNN) ASSAY RUN">
      <data key="d0">CHICKEN SOUND CONVOLUTIONAL NEURAL NETWORK (CSCNN) ASSAY RUN</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A deep-learning-based diagnostic run that uses a chicken sound convolutional neural network and spectrogram inputs to classify individual chickens as avian influenza virus (AIV) infected or healthy, achieving 93.01%, 95.05%, and 97.43% accuracy on days 2, 4, and 6 post-inoculation in a controlled AIV challenge.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS (AIV) IN CHICKENS">
      <data key="d0">AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS (AIV) IN CHICKENS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory avian influenza virus infection in chickens, including highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI), which alters pulmonary and syrinx biomechanics and leads to measurable changes in vocal patterns such as coughing, stertorous respiration, inspiratory gasping, reduced vocalization rate, and increased entropy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECTROGRAM-BASED ACOUSTIC BIOSENSING PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">SPECTROGRAM-BASED ACOUSTIC BIOSENSING PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An AI-powered acoustic monitoring platform that converts chicken vocalizations into spectrograms and applies convolutional neural networks to detect disease-related and distress-related vocal anomalies in real time under farm conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BARN-SCALE COMPACT CNN DISTRESS-CALL DETECTION ASSAY RUN">
      <data key="d0">BARN-SCALE COMPACT CNN DISTRESS-CALL DETECTION ASSAY RUN</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">A barn-scale deep-learning assay run using a compact CNN (light VGG11) trained on 5336 one-second audio segments from two commercial flocks to automatically detect chicken distress calls under real farm noise, achieving about 95% accuracy with 94.58% precision and 94.89% recall.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACOUSTIC MONITORING PLATFORM FOR POULTRY RESPIRATORY DISTRESS">
      <data key="d0">ACOUSTIC MONITORING PLATFORM FOR POULTRY RESPIRATORY DISTRESS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A sound-based biosensing platform that uses microphones and deep learning models to automatically identify chicken distress vocalizations, sneezes, and coughs at the group level in noisy multi-bird poultry houses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW-COST MICROPHONES WITH EDGE COMPUTING">
      <data key="d0">LOW-COST MICROPHONES WITH EDGE COMPUTING</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A distributed hardware implementation of the acoustic monitoring system using inexpensive microphones and on-site edge computing devices to scale monitoring across poultry houses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AUTOMATED IDENTIFICATION OF CHICKEN DISTRESS VOCALIZATIONS USING DEEP LEARNING MODELS">
      <data key="d0">AUTOMATED IDENTIFICATION OF CHICKEN DISTRESS VOCALIZATIONS USING DEEP LEARNING MODELS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation study demonstrating that deep learning models can automatically identify chicken distress vocalizations, supporting the feasibility and performance of acoustic monitoring as a biosensing approach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GROUP-LEVEL SNEEZE AND COUGH DETECTION IN NOISY MULTI-BIRD CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">GROUP-LEVEL SNEEZE AND COUGH DETECTION IN NOISY MULTI-BIRD CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation study showing that the acoustic monitoring platform can detect sneezes and coughs at the flock level under realistic, noisy multi-bird poultry house conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY INFECTION IN POULTRY (COUGHS AND INSPIRATORY SOUNDS)">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY INFECTION IN POULTRY (COUGHS AND INSPIRATORY SOUNDS)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory disease states in poultry manifested as coughs and inspiratory sounds, treated here as the airborne infectious condition targeted by the acoustic monitoring platform.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EARLY DETECTION WINDOW (1–2 DAYS BEFORE VISIBLE MORBIDITY)">
      <data key="d0">EARLY DETECTION WINDOW (1–2 DAYS BEFORE VISIBLE MORBIDITY)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Operational performance of the acoustic monitoring system, enabling detection of respiratory distress one to two days before visible morbidity, allowing earlier isolation, sanitation, and molecular confirmation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SENSITIVITY OF 60–90% IN HIGH-NOISE POULTRY HOUSES">
      <data key="d0">SENSITIVITY OF 60–90% IN HIGH-NOISE POULTRY HOUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">Reported performance range of the acoustic monitoring platform under high-noise conditions, where background signals from ventilation fans, augers, and human activity reduce sensitivity to approximately 60–90% depending on infection stage, sensor fidelity, and environmental entropy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NOISE MITIGATION VIA SPECTRAL SUBTRACTION OR WIENER FILTERING">
      <data key="d0">NOISE MITIGATION VIA SPECTRAL SUBTRACTION OR WIENER FILTERING</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Digital signal processing steps applied to recorded audio, such as spectral subtraction and Wiener filtering, to reduce environmental noise and improve detection of low-amplitude respiratory sounds.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ADAPTIVE BEAMFORMING WITH SMALL MICROPHONE ARRAYS">
      <data key="d0">ADAPTIVE BEAMFORMING WITH SMALL MICROPHONE ARRAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A spatial filtering step using small microphone arrays to focus on sound sources of interest and suppress background noise before classification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SOURCE SEPARATION TO ISOLATE RESPIRATORY TRANSIENTS">
      <data key="d0">SOURCE SEPARATION TO ISOLATE RESPIRATORY TRANSIENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">Signal processing to separate overlapping sound sources in barn audio, isolating transient respiratory events such as coughs and sneezes from machinery and human speech.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NOISE-AWARE TRAINING WITH AUGMENTED BARN SOUNDSCAPES">
      <data key="d0">NOISE-AWARE TRAINING WITH AUGMENTED BARN SOUNDSCAPES</data>
      <data key="d1">SAMPLE_PREP_STEP</data>
      <data key="d2">A data preparation and model-training step that augments training datasets with barn machinery noise and human speech to improve classifier robustness in noisy environments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR-CAS PLATFORMS">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR-CAS PLATFORMS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Emerging CRISPR-Cas-based diagnostic platforms for avian influenza detection, combining sub-10-copy analytical sensitivity with simplified reagent formats and growing portability (TRL 6–8). | An electrical CRISPR-based biosensor platform developed by Hajian et al. that uses immobilized dCas9 and single-guide RNA to enable sensitive, fast electrical detection of target nucleic acids without requiring an amplification step.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b,4b595dc6-a258-44ed-89fc-c349fc64a77f</data>
      <data key="d6">CRISPR-CHIP PLATFORM</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPTICAL SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">OPTICAL SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Optical detection platforms for avian influenza that show strong analytical performance in laboratory settings but face challenges in alignment stability and field deployment (TRL 5–6).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SERS SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">SERS SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Surface-enhanced Raman scattering (SERS)–based systems for avian influenza detection with high analytical performance in controlled laboratory conditions, yet limited by field adaptation issues (TRL 5–6).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BEHAVIORAL SENSING THROUGH ACOUSTIC MONITORING">
      <data key="d0">BEHAVIORAL SENSING THROUGH ACOUSTIC MONITORING</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A behavioral sensing modality that uses flock-level acoustic monitoring to provide continuous, non-invasive early warning of avian influenza–associated respiratory distress in poultry (TRL 8–9).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WEARABLE ULTRASOUND">
      <data key="d0">WEARABLE ULTRASOUND</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A prospective wearable ultrasound sensing technology for individual-level, continuous monitoring of poultry to detect respiratory distress and support precision avian influenza surveillance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLEXIBLE ACOUSTIC PATCH TECHNOLOGIES">
      <data key="d0">FLEXIBLE ACOUSTIC PATCH TECHNOLOGIES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Emerging flexible acoustic patch sensors envisioned for continuous, individual-level monitoring of poultry respiratory status, extending flock-level acoustic surveillance to personalized health tracking.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RT-QPCR SAMPLING">
      <data key="d0">RT-QPCR SAMPLING</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A confirmatory reverse transcription quantitative PCR diagnostic workflow performed by veterinary personnel on collected samples as a Tier 3 laboratory-grade test to validate positive on-site CRISPR assay results for HPAI.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="1-HOUR TURNAROUND">
      <data key="d0">1-HOUR TURNAROUND</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_RUN</data>
      <data key="d2">The operational run profile of the on-site CRISPR assay, indicating that a single execution from targeted environmental air sampling to result readout is completed in approximately one hour.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE BIOSENSOR DATA">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE BIOSENSOR DATA</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An environmental sensing component that collects and analyzes airborne samples in poultry houses to provide early biosensor-based signals potentially indicative of highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELECTROCHEMICAL IMPEDANCE ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">ELECTROCHEMICAL IMPEDANCE ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Rapid electrochemical biosensor assays that measure impedance changes in samples to provide Tier 2 confirmatory signals for suspected HPAI cases within 30–60 minutes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TIER 1 ON-FARM HPAI SURVEILLANCE">
      <data key="d0">TIER 1 ON-FARM HPAI SURVEILLANCE</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">The first tier of the on-farm HPAI surveillance workflow, integrating continuous behavioral sensing (for example, acoustic distress signatures) and environmental sensing (including airborne biosensor data) to generate early anomaly alerts within minutes to hours.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TIER 2 RAPID MOLECULAR AND ELECTROCHEMICAL ASSAYS">
      <data key="d0">TIER 2 RAPID MOLECULAR AND ELECTROCHEMICAL ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">The second tier of the on-farm HPAI surveillance workflow, combining rapid molecular assays (RT-LAMP or CRISPR-Cas12a-based) with electrochemical impedance biosensor assays to provide confirmatory results within 30–60 minutes after Tier 1 anomalies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TIER 3 LABORATORY VALIDATION">
      <data key="d0">TIER 3 LABORATORY VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">The third tier of the on-farm HPAI surveillance workflow, in which laboratory methods such as RT-qPCR, virus isolation, or sequencing are used to validate and confirm HPAI infection status within one to two days.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TEXAS DAIRY CATTLE H5N1 VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">TEXAS DAIRY CATTLE H5N1 VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">An H5N1 influenza virus strain associated with Texas dairy cattle, described as having superior replication, pathogenicity, and immune evasion compared with other H5N1 viruses, making it a notable airborne pathogen variant.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_72,de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_73</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HISTORICAL AVIAN H5N1 ISOLATE">
      <data key="d0">HISTORICAL AVIAN H5N1 ISOLATE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A previously characterized avian-origin H5N1 virus isolate used as a comparator to the Texas dairy cattle H5N1 virus in terms of replication, pathogenicity, and immune evasion. It serves as a reference strain for understanding changes in virulence and potential airborne transmissibility.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_73</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BOVINE H5N1 CLADE 2.3.4.4B">
      <data key="d0">BOVINE H5N1 CLADE 2.3.4.4B</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A specific clade (2.3.4.4b) of highly pathogenic avian influenza A H5N1 virus associated with infections in bovine hosts and studied for its pathogenesis and potential for respiratory (airborne) transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5 BIRD FLU">
      <data key="d0">H5 BIRD FLU</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A general term for avian influenza A viruses of the H5 subtype, encompassing multiple clades of highly pathogenic strains that spread among birds primarily through airborne and environmental routes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFLUENZA A VIRUS H5N1">
      <data key="d0">INFLUENZA A VIRUS H5N1</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A highly pathogenic subtype of influenza A virus (H5N1) that can be transmitted via respiratory droplets and aerosols, and is a key target for surveillance and early detection in both human and avian hosts.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_76</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VISUAL PORTABLE MOLECULAR IMPRINTING SENSOR">
      <data key="d0">VISUAL PORTABLE MOLECULAR IMPRINTING SENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A self-service, portable molecular imprinting-based biosensor that enables visual, multimodal detection of influenza A virus subtype H5N1, suitable for field or point-of-care applications.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_76</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MACHINE LEARNING-DRIVEN SERS FINGERPRINTING OF DISINTEGRATED VIRAL COMPONENTS">
      <data key="d0">MACHINE LEARNING-DRIVEN SERS FINGERPRINTING OF DISINTEGRATED VIRAL COMPONENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A biosensor platform that uses surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS) to obtain spectral fingerprints of disintegrated viral components and applies machine learning algorithms to rapidly detect SARS-CoV-2 in environmental dust samples.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_77</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ESCHERICHIA COLI (E. COLI)">
      <data key="d0">ESCHERICHIA COLI (E. COLI)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Escherichia coli bacteria used as a bacterial target in the capacitive biosensor assay, detected in aerosolized form as a model or indicator airborne pathogen in air monitoring applications.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_79</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS ANTIGENS">
      <data key="d0">AVIAN INFLUENZA VIRUS ANTIGENS</data>
      <data key="d1">SPECIFICITY_PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d2">Avian influenza virus antigens are specific viral proteins or epitopes from avian influenza viruses that constitute the molecular targets recognized by the paper-based electrochemical immunosensor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_80</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PAPER-BASED ELECTROCHEMICAL IMMUNOSENSOR">
      <data key="d0">PAPER-BASED ELECTROCHEMICAL IMMUNOSENSOR</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A paper-based electrochemical immunosensor employing flexible screen-printed carbon nanotube–polydimethylsiloxane electrodes, designed for label-free detection of multiple avian influenza virus antigens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_80</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5 HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA CLADE 2.3.4.4 (H5N8 AND H5N2)">
      <data key="d0">H5 HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA CLADE 2.3.4.4 (H5N8 AND H5N2)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Highly pathogenic avian influenza A viruses of clade 2.3.4.4, including H5N8 and H5N2 subtypes, associated with efficient respiratory and contact transmission in poultry such as Pekin ducks and Chinese geese.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_86</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFLUENZA A/H5N1 VIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">INFLUENZA A/H5N1 VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Highly pathogenic avian influenza A viruses of the H5N1 subtype, capable of respiratory transmission in birds and with documented transmission potential in mammals.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_86</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLADE 2.3.4.4B H5N1 HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA GENOTYPE">
      <data key="d0">CLADE 2.3.4.4B H5N1 HIGHLY PATHOGENIC AVIAN INFLUENZA GENOTYPE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A specific clade (2.3.4.4B) of highly pathogenic H5N1 avian influenza virus detected in Europe in 2021, representing a distinct genotype of surveillance concern.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_87</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5 HEMAGGLUTININ GENE-SPECIFIC LOOP-MEDIATED ISOTHERMAL AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">H5 HEMAGGLUTININ GENE-SPECIFIC LOOP-MEDIATED ISOTHERMAL AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AMPLIFICATION_METHOD</data>
      <data key="d2">A loop-mediated isothermal amplification (LAMP) assay specifically targeting the influenza H5 hemagglutinin gene, developed for rapid molecular diagnosis of H5N1 avian influenza virus infection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_87</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NATIONAL PROFICIENCY TESTING FOR AVIAN INFLUENZA RRT-PCR (2020–2022)">
      <data key="d0">NATIONAL PROFICIENCY TESTING FOR AVIAN INFLUENZA RRT-PCR (2020–2022)</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A national proficiency testing program conducted between 2020 and 2022 to statistically evaluate the performance of local veterinary laboratories in molecular detection of avian influenza virus using rRT-PCR.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_87</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RPA AND PAM-INDEPENDENT CRISPR-CAS12A ASSAY COMBINED WITH ANTI-NP ANTIBODY-BASED VIRAL RNA PURIFICATION">
      <data key="d0">RPA AND PAM-INDEPENDENT CRISPR-CAS12A ASSAY COMBINED WITH ANTI-NP ANTIBODY-BASED VIRAL RNA PURIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An integrated on-site diagnostic platform for H5Nx avian influenza that combines recombinase polymerase amplification (RPA), a PAM-independent Cas12a-based CRISPR assay, and anti-nucleoprotein (NP) antibody-based viral RNA purification.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_88</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PAM-INDEPENDENT CRISPR-CAS12A ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">PAM-INDEPENDENT CRISPR-CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR-Cas12a-based nucleic acid detection platform that does not require a canonical protospacer adjacent motif (PAM) for target recognition, used together with RPA and anti-NP antibody-based viral RNA purification for rapid, specific on-site diagnosis of H5Nx avian influenza.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_89</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STREAMLINED CRISPR-BASED ASSAYS FOR DETECTION AND SUBTYPING OF AVIAN INFLUENZA">
      <data key="d0">STREAMLINED CRISPR-BASED ASSAYS FOR DETECTION AND SUBTYPING OF AVIAN INFLUENZA</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A set of simplified CRISPR-based diagnostic assay designs described in a preprint, intended for detection and subtype discrimination of avian influenza viruses, likely integrating CRISPR effectors with nucleic acid amplification in a more efficient workflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_89</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR/CAS TECHNOLOGY FOR THE DIAGNOSIS OF ANIMAL INFECTIOUS DISEASES">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR/CAS TECHNOLOGY FOR THE DIAGNOSIS OF ANIMAL INFECTIOUS DISEASES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A broad class of CRISPR/Cas-based diagnostic platforms discussed in the cited article, covering nucleic-acid-based detection methods for a range of animal infectious diseases, including viral pathogens such as avian influenza.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_89</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SENSING OF COVID-19 ANTIBODIES VIA AEROSOL JET NANOPRINTED REDUCED-GRAPHENE-OXIDE-COATED 3D ELECTRODES">
      <data key="d0">SENSING OF COVID-19 ANTIBODIES VIA AEROSOL JET NANOPRINTED REDUCED-GRAPHENE-OXIDE-COATED 3D ELECTRODES</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An electrochemical biosensing platform that uses aerosol jet nanoprinted, reduced-graphene-oxide-coated 3D electrodes to rapidly detect antibodies against SARS-CoV-2 (COVID-19) in seconds, representing a high-speed serological biosensor for a respiratory pathogen.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_89</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="N1 NA ANTIBODY-SPECIFIC ENZYME-LINKED LECTIN ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">N1 NA ANTIBODY-SPECIFIC ENZYME-LINKED LECTIN ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">An enzyme-linked lectin assay designed to detect antibodies against the N1 neuraminidase (NA) of H5N1 highly pathogenic avian influenza virus in vaccinated birds, functioning as a serological biosensing platform.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_90</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENT MICROSPHERE IMMUNOASSAY FOR ISOTYPE-SPECIFIC H5N1 ANTIBODY DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENT MICROSPHERE IMMUNOASSAY FOR ISOTYPE-SPECIFIC H5N1 ANTIBODY DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A fluorescent microsphere-based immunoassay used to detect isotype-specific antibodies against H5N1 in serum and milk samples from dairy cattle, intended as a tool for epidemiological surveillance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_90</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EVALUATION OF N1 NA ANTIBODY-SPECIFIC ENZYME-LINKED LECTIN ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">EVALUATION OF N1 NA ANTIBODY-SPECIFIC ENZYME-LINKED LECTIN ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A validation study assessing the performance of an N1 NA antibody-specific enzyme-linked lectin assay for detecting H5N1 highly pathogenic avian influenza virus infection in vaccinated birds.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_90</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLUORESCENT MICROSPHERE IMMUNOASSAY SURVEILLANCE STUDY IN DAIRY CATTLE">
      <data key="d0">FLUORESCENT MICROSPHERE IMMUNOASSAY SURVEILLANCE STUDY IN DAIRY CATTLE</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A study validating the use of a fluorescent microsphere immunoassay for isotype-specific H5N1 antibody detection in serum and milk samples from dairy cattle for epidemiological surveillance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_90</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DETECTION OF ANTIBODIES AGAINST H5 SUBTYPE HPAI VIRUSES IN RACCOONS">
      <data key="d0">DETECTION OF ANTIBODIES AGAINST H5 SUBTYPE HPAI VIRUSES IN RACCOONS</data>
      <data key="d1">ASSAY_VALIDATION</data>
      <data key="d2">A study reporting the detection of antibodies against H5 subtype highly pathogenic avian influenza viruses in multiple raccoons in Tokachi District, Hokkaido, Japan, from 2022 to 2023, implying validation of serological detection methods in wildlife.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_90</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CRISPR/CAS13A LATERAL FLOW ASSAY">
      <data key="d0">CRISPR/CAS13A LATERAL FLOW ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">A CRISPR/Cas13a-based nucleic acid detection platform with lateral flow readout, developed by Yang et al. for rapid detection of pan-avian influenza A viruses and H5, H7, and H9 subtypes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_91</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAPID ANTIGEN TESTS FOR H5N1">
      <data key="d0">RAPID ANTIGEN TESTS FOR H5N1</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Point-of-care antigen-based diagnostic assays evaluated by Bassit et al. for detecting highly pathogenic avian influenza A(H5N1) in contrived nasal swab specimens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_91</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POINT-OF-CARE MOLECULAR TESTS FOR H5N1">
      <data key="d0">POINT-OF-CARE MOLECULAR TESTS FOR H5N1</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Near-patient molecular diagnostic assays assessed alongside rapid antigen tests by Bassit et al. for detection of highly pathogenic avian influenza A(H5N1) in contrived nasal swab specimens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_91</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LATERAL FLOW DEVICES FOR H5N1 OUTBREAKS">
      <data key="d0">LATERAL FLOW DEVICES FOR H5N1 OUTBREAKS</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Lateral flow immunoassay devices evaluated by Slomka et al. for identifying poultry infected during H5N1 highly pathogenic avian influenza outbreaks in Vietnam using swab and feather specimens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_91</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="H5 HEMAGGLUTININ ANTIBODIES">
      <data key="d0">H5 HEMAGGLUTININ ANTIBODIES</data>
      <data key="d1">REPORTER_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d2">Host antibodies directed against the H5 hemagglutinin antigen of avian influenza viruses; in the cited competitive ELISA study, these antibodies constitute the analyte whose presence is inferred via an immunochemical signal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_92</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LATERAL FLOW DEVICES FOR H5N1 DETECTION">
      <data key="d0">LATERAL FLOW DEVICES FOR H5N1 DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">BIOSENSOR_PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d2">Immunochromatographic lateral flow assay devices evaluated for identification of poultry infected with H5N1 highly pathogenic avian influenza using swab and feather specimens during outbreaks in Vietnam.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b_chunk_92</data>
      <data key="d5">de3c3a3b-6855-4b40-bff9-eef9df2e0d4b</data>
    </node>
