      <data key="d8">CAS12A</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d10">Two-step CRISPR workflows can incorporate Cas12a as the effector nuclease in the detection step, leveraging its collateral cleavage activity on reporter molecules after amplification has been completed.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.6</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STEP CRISPR ASSAYS" target="ONE-POT CRISPR–NAA ASSAYS">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STEP CRISPR ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d8">ONE-POT CRISPR–NAA ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d9">OUTPERFORMS</data>
      <data key="d10">Two-step CRISPR assays typically exhibit higher sensitivity than one-pot CRISPR–NAA assays because amplification is completed before Cas12a-mediated detection, avoiding competition between amplification and target cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
