      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">NTC GROUP (0 COPY/TEST)</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE assay uses a no-template control group with 0 copy/test to define the positive signal threshold (mean + 3×SD), contributing to its analytical validation and specificity assessment.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="DIAGNOSTIC PERFORMANCE EVALUATION WITH 118 QPCR-POSITIVE AND 80 NEGATIVE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">DIAGNOSTIC PERFORMANCE EVALUATION WITH 118 QPCR-POSITIVE AND 80 NEGATIVE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The optimized 40-minute TRACE assay is clinically validated in a blinded diagnostic performance study using 118 qPCR-positive and 80 MPXV-negative samples, establishing its sensitivity, specificity, and predictive values.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="99% SENSITIVITY AND 100% SPECIFICITY">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">99% SENSITIVITY AND 100% SPECIFICITY</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_SPECIFICITY</data>
      <data key="d10">In the described validation cohort, the TRACE assay achieves a performance profile of 99% sensitivity and 100% specificity, reflecting high accuracy in distinguishing MPXV-positive from MPXV-negative samples.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="40-MIN PROTOCOL">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">40-MIN PROTOCOL</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The 40-minute operational protocol represents the specific TRACE assay run configuration whose diagnostic performance is evaluated and validated in the study.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="MPXV LYSIS PROTOCOL">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">MPXV LYSIS PROTOCOL</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">The one-pot TRACE assay uses specimens processed by the MPXV lysis protocol, which releases viral DNA and generates lysates suitable for direct assay input.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.88</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="CRUDE LYSATES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">CRUDE LYSATES</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">The one-pot TRACE assay directly accepts crude lysates generated by the MPXV lysis protocol as its input matrix for MPXV detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.86</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="TRACE SAMPLE PROCESSING STUDIES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">TRACE SAMPLE PROCESSING STUDIES</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE assay’s compatibility with crude lysates and varied specimen matrices is established by the sample processing studies that optimized the MPXV lysis protocol.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.78</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="TRACE VS QPCR COMPARISON IN TWO MPXV CASES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">TRACE VS QPCR COMPARISON IN TWO MPXV CASES</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The comparison of TRACE assay outputs with qPCR in serial specimens validates the assay’s ability to track MPXV viral load dynamics.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.84</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="LYOPHILIZED TRACE REAGENTS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">LYOPHILIZED TRACE REAGENTS</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">The underlying TRACE assay chemistry is provided in a lyophilized reagent format for use in the lateral flow implementation. | The TRACE assay can be implemented using lyophilized TRACE reagents, whose stability and behavior under various storage conditions are critical for deployment in real-world and resource-limited settings.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="RASH AND SALIVA SPECIMENS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">RASH AND SALIVA SPECIMENS</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE assay is applied to rash and saliva specimens from MPXV cases, which are processed via the lysis protocol before detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="PLASMA AND URINE SPECIMENS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">PLASMA AND URINE SPECIMENS</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">Sample processing studies show that the TRACE assay can be used with plasma and urine specimens, including those with low viral titers, after lysis.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.78</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="ONE-POT DUPLEX TRACE ASSAY">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">ONE-POT DUPLEX TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d9">OUTPERFORMS</data>
      <data key="d10">The one-pot duplex configuration of the TRACE assay represents an enhanced implementation of the TRACE platform, demonstrating strong diagnostic performance in clinical and point-of-care applications compared to simpler configurations.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.6</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="GRNA BLOCKING SEQUENCE">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">GRNA BLOCKING SEQUENCE</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE assay uses a gRNA blocking sequence to control the timing of Cas12b–gRNA complex activation, ensuring that nucleic acid amplification and Cas12b trans-cleavage occur in distinct phases within the same reaction.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="ONE-POT CRISPR ASSAYS WITH ATTENUATED CIS-CLEAVAGE">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">ONE-POT CRISPR ASSAYS WITH ATTENUATED CIS-CLEAVAGE</data>
      <data key="d9">OUTPERFORMS</data>
      <data key="d10">By segregating amplification and trans-cleavage via temperature control and gRNA blocking, the TRACE assay avoids the reduced NAA efficiency and coupled loss of trans-cleavage activity seen in one-pot CRISPR assays that attenuate cis-cleavage, leading to improved kinetics and sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="J2L GRNA">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">J2L GRNA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE assay incorporates a Cas12b-specific J2L gRNA to form Cas12b/gRNA complexes that recognize the J2L target and mediate target-specific cleavage in the second stage.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="REPORTER SIGNAL">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">REPORTER SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">In the second stage of the TRACE assay, all reporter signal is generated by Cas12b recognition of the J2L target, providing a measurable readout of successful detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="SINGLE REPORTER">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">SINGLE REPORTER</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE assay is designed around a single reporter type, which simplifies the portable reader and reduces manufacturing cost while still enabling internal control detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="VALIDATION STUDIES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">VALIDATION STUDIES</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The performance and MPXV strain coverage of the TRACE assay are being established through validation studies, although current studies are limited by geographically homogeneous sample collection sites.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="INTERNAL CONTROLS FOR SPECIMEN QUALITY">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">INTERNAL CONTROLS FOR SPECIMEN QUALITY</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE assay addresses the lack of internal controls in many CRISPR assays by incorporating concurrent detection of a host gene target (the J2L locus) to validate specimen quality within each assay run.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="SHERLOCK V2 SYSTEM">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">SHERLOCK V2 SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE assay design is proposed to be adaptable to the general multiplexing framework employed by the SHERLOCK V2 system, which is referenced as a guiding framework rather than a direct performance benchmark.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.4</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE ASSAY" target="CAS VARIANTS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">CAS VARIANTS</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d10">Future versions of the TRACE assay are expected to use newly discovered or engineered Cas variants with distinctive temperature preferences and trans-cleavage specificities to expand multiplexing capacity.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.75</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
