      <data key="d8">J2L GENE</data>
      <data key="d9">DETECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">The guide RNA is designed to be complementary to the MPXV J2L gene sequence, enabling specific recognition of this target and subsequent activation of Cas12b in the TRACE assay.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.82</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="GRNA" target="MPXV J2L">
      <data key="d7">GRNA</data>
      <data key="d8">MPXV J2L</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">A subset of the gRNAs in the assay is designed to target the MPXV J2L region, guiding Cas12b to this viral sequence during the second stage.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.78</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="GRNA" target="RNASE P GENE">
      <data key="d7">GRNA</data>
      <data key="d8">RNASE P GENE</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">Another subset of the gRNAs is designed to target the human RNase P gene, guiding Cas12a to this host control sequence during the first stage.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.78</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="GRNA" target="MPXV">
      <data key="d7">GRNA</data>
      <data key="d8">MPXV</data>
      <data key="d9">DETECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">The gRNA sequences are designed to specifically recognize MPXV genomic regions, directing dAapCas12b to MPXV targets for sequence-specific detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STAGE INCUBATION PROCEDURE" target="LOW-TEMPERATURE STAGE">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STAGE INCUBATION PROCEDURE</data>
      <data key="d8">LOW-TEMPERATURE STAGE</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-stage incubation procedure in TRACE includes a low-temperature stage that favors RPA and suppresses Cas12b:gRNA complex formation and target cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.86</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STAGE INCUBATION PROCEDURE" target="HIGH-TEMPERATURE STAGE">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STAGE INCUBATION PROCEDURE</data>
      <data key="d8">HIGH-TEMPERATURE STAGE</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-stage incubation procedure in TRACE includes a high-temperature stage that inactivates RPA, promotes gRNA:ssRNA dissociation, and activates Cas12b for target recognition and probe degradation.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.86</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="LOW-TEMPERATURE STAGE" target="RECOMBINASE POLYMERASE AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d7">LOW-TEMPERATURE STAGE</data>
      <data key="d8">RPA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">During the low-temperature stage of TRACE, RPA is active and efficiently amplifies the nucleic acid target while Cas12b activity is suppressed.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="LOW-TEMPERATURE STAGE" target="CRISPR/CAS12A">
      <data key="d7">LOW-TEMPERATURE STAGE</data>
      <data key="d8">CRISPR/CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d10">In the low-temperature stage of TRACE, Cas12b remains largely inactive due to temperature and ssRNA blocker effects, preventing premature target cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.82</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HIGH-TEMPERATURE STAGE" target="CRISPR/CAS12A">
      <data key="d7">HIGH-TEMPERATURE STAGE</data>
      <data key="d8">CRISPR/CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d10">During the high-temperature stage of TRACE, Cas12b becomes active, forms ribonucleoprotein complexes with gRNA, and mediates target recognition and probe cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.92</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HIGH-TEMPERATURE STAGE" target="RECOMBINASE POLYMERASE AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d7">HIGH-TEMPERATURE STAGE</data>
      <data key="d8">RPA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">In the high-temperature stage of TRACE, RPA is effectively inactivated, preventing further amplification while Cas12b-mediated detection proceeds.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY" target="MONKEYPOX VIRUS (MPXV)">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">MONKEYPOX VIRUS (MPXV)</data>
      <data key="d9">DETECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-step Cas12a assay detects MPXV by first amplifying the J2L region with RPA and then using Cas12a guided by a J2L-specific gRNA to recognize and report viral nucleic acid.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY" target="CAS12A">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">CAS12A</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-step assay uses Cas12a as the core detection enzyme in the second step, where it is activated by binding to the MPXV J2L target sequence via the specific gRNA.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY" target="MPXV J2L GRNA">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">MPXV J2L GRNA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-step Cas12a assay employs the MPXV J2L-specific gRNA to program Cas12a for recognition of the amplified J2L target.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY" target="RECOMBINASE POLYMERASE AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">RPA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">In the two-step format, RPA is used as a separate upstream amplification step to generate abundant J2L amplicons that are subsequently detected by Cas12a. | The two-step assay uses RPA as a preamplification step to increase the amount of target DNA before CRISPR-based fluorescence detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY" target="2.5 COPIES/TEST">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">2.5 COPIES/TEST</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_LOD</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-step Cas12a assay achieves a limit of detection of 2.5 copies/test for MPXV J2L targets.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY" target="EMPIRICAL PERFORMANCE PROFILE OF TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">EMPIRICAL PERFORMANCE PROFILE OF TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_SPECIFICITY</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-step Cas12a assay is characterized by an empirical performance profile demonstrating high sensitivity and strong specificity for MPXV J2L detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY" target="ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d9">OUTPERFORMS</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-step Cas12a assay outperforms the one-pot Cas12a assay in analytical sensitivity for MPXV detection, achieving 2.5 copies/test versus 100 copies/test due to the absence of Cas12a-mediated inhibition of RPA in the separated format.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY" target="LBCAS12A">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STEP CRISPR/CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">LBCAS12A</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-step assay employs LbCas12a as the CRISPR effector nuclease in the second-stage CRISPR reaction to mediate target-dependent collateral cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY" target="GRNA">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STEP CRISPR/CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">GRNA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-step assay includes a guide RNA in the CRISPR reaction to direct LbCas12a to the specific target DNA sequence.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY" target="FLUORESCENT REPORTER">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STEP CRISPR/CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">FLUORESCENT REPORTER</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-step assay generates a fluorescent signal by Cas12a-mediated cleavage of a fluorescent reporter, which serves as the measurable output of target detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-STEP CAS12A ASSAY" target="SLAN-96 REAL-TIME FLUORESCENCE DETECTION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d7">TWO-STEP CRISPR/CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">SLAN-96 REAL-TIME FLUORESCENCE DETECTION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">The fluorescence generated by the two-step assay is monitored and recorded by the SLAN-96 real-time fluorescence detection system, which captures the kinetic fluorescence signal.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY" target="MONKEYPOX VIRUS (MPXV)">
      <data key="d7">ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">MONKEYPOX VIRUS (MPXV)</data>
      <data key="d9">DETECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">The one-pot Cas12a assay detects MPXV in a single reaction by combining RPA amplification and Cas12a-based detection of the J2L target, albeit with reduced sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY" target="CAS12A">
      <data key="d7">ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">CAS12A</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d10">The one-pot assay incorporates Cas12a directly into the combined amplification-detection reaction, where its activity both enables detection and inhibits RPA at higher activity levels. | The optimized one-pot RPA/Cas12b assay configuration, which uses Cas12b instead of Cas12a, demonstrates improved sensitivity (10 copies/test), indicating that the Cas12b-based platform outperforms the prior Cas12a-based setup under the same assay concept.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY" target="MPXV J2L GRNA">
      <data key="d7">ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">MPXV J2L GRNA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">The one-pot Cas12a assay uses the MPXV J2L gRNA to guide Cas12a within the single-tube reaction, coupling target recognition to signal generation.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY" target="RECOMBINASE POLYMERASE AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d7">ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">RPA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">The one-pot assay uses RPA within the same reaction as Cas12a to amplify MPXV targets, though Cas12a activity partially inhibits RPA and reduces amplification efficiency. | The assay incorporates recombinase polymerase amplification (RPA) as the nucleic acid amplification step, using its temperature optimum to temporally separate amplification from Cas12b-mediated cleavage in a one-pot format.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.96</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY" target="100 COPIES/TEST">
      <data key="d7">ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">100 COPIES/TEST</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_LOD</data>
      <data key="d10">The one-pot Cas12a assay has a limit of detection of 100 copies/test for MPXV J2L targets, indicating substantially reduced sensitivity compared to the two-step assay. | The optimized one-pot RPA/Cas12b assay achieves a limit of detection of 10 copies per test after implementing sequential 37 °C and 60 °C incubations, reflecting improved analytical sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY" target="CAS12B">
      <data key="d7">ONE-POT RPA/CAS12B ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d10">The one-pot RPA/Cas12b assay employs Cas12b as its CRISPR effector nuclease, leveraging its cis- and trans-cleavage activities and broad temperature range to enable staged amplification and detection in a single reaction.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.98</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="ONE-POT CAS12A ASSAY" target="REPORTER SIGNAL">
      <data key="d7">ONE-POT RPA/CAS12B ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">REPORTER SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">Upon target recognition and activation of Cas12b, the one-pot RPA/Cas12b assay generates a fluorescence reporter signal via Cas12b trans-cleavage of a reporter substrate; weak signal at the end of the first incubation stage indicates residual Cas12b activity during amplification.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CAS12B" target="CAS12A">
      <data key="d7">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d8">CAS12A</data>
      <data key="d9">OUTPERFORMS</data>
      <data key="d10">In the described assay context, Cas12b functionally outperforms Cas12a by enabling a broader temperature range and better separation of amplification and cleavage steps, leading to enhanced sensitivity in the one-pot RPA/Cas12b platform.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CAS12B" target="GRNA">
      <data key="d7">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d8">GRNA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">Cas12b forms a ribonucleoprotein (RNP) complex with the guide RNA, which directs Cas12b to its dsDNA target; this interaction is confirmed by electrophoretic mobility shift assays showing reduced free gRNA band intensity. | Cas12b forms a ribonucleoprotein complex with the gRNA, which directs Cas12b to its DNA target; this complex formation is modulated by ssRNA blockers complementary to the gRNA spacer.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CAS12B" target="REPORTER SIGNAL">
      <data key="d7">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d8">REPORTER SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">Activated Cas12b exhibits trans-cleavage activity on a fluorescent reporter substrate, producing the measurable reporter signal used to quantify cleavage kinetics and assay sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.88</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CAS12B" target="SSRNA BLOCKER">
      <data key="d7">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d8">SSRNA BLOCKER</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">Cas12b activity is regulated by an ssRNA blocker that is complementary to the gRNA spacer, transiently preventing formation of active Cas12b/gRNA RNP and RNP-DNA complexes during the 37 °C amplification phase.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CAS12B" target="POLY T REPORTER">
      <data key="d7">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d8">POLY T REPORTER</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">Upon activation by gRNA-target binding to MPXV DNA, Cas12b exhibits collateral nuclease activity that cleaves the poly T reporter, resulting in the fluorescent signal used for detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CAS12B" target="ΔF1 SIGNAL">
      <data key="d7">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d8">ΔF2 SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">Cas12b, once activated at 64 °C after ssRNA blocker release, generates the MPXV J2L–specific ΔF2 fluorescent signal.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CAS12B" target="J2L GRNA">
      <data key="d7">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d8">J2L GRNA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">Cas12b USES_GUIDE the J2L gRNA as its targeting RNA in the TRACE duplex assay, forming the Cas12b/gRNA complex responsible for second-stage detection once ssDNA-mediated inhibition is relieved.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CAS12B" target="J2L TARGET AMPLICON">
      <data key="d7">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d8">J2L TARGET AMPLICON</data>
      <data key="d9">DETECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">Cas12b DETECTS the J2L target amplicon in the second stage of the TRACE duplex assay when guided by the J2L gRNA after it is released from ssDNA inhibition.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CAS12B" target="REPORTER SIGNAL PRODUCED IN THE SECOND STAGE">
      <data key="d7">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d8">REPORTER SIGNAL PRODUCED IN THE SECOND STAGE</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">Cas12b PRODUCES_SIGNAL the reporter signal measured in the second stage of the TRACE duplex assay when its J2L gRNA is no longer sequestered by the ssDNA inhibitor and the Cas12b/gRNA complex becomes active.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CAS12B" target="GRNA 1">
      <data key="d7">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d8">GRNA 1</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">Cas12b forms a ribonucleoprotein complex with gRNA 1 to achieve sequence-specific recognition and cis-cleavage of the Cy5-labeled dsDNA substrate.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CAS12B" target="CIS-CLEAVAGE READOUT">
      <data key="d7">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d8">CIS-CLEAVAGE READOUT</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">Cas12b activity on the Cy5-labeled dsDNA substrate produces cleavage products whose band intensities on PAGE constitute the cis-cleavage readout.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="SSRNA GRNA BLOCKER" target="GRNA">
      <data key="d7">SSRNA GRNA BLOCKER</data>
      <data key="d8">GRNA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">The ssRNA gRNA blocker is designed to hybridize with the guide RNA, sequestering or blocking it and thereby reducing formation of the Cas12b–gRNA RNP complex and modulating cleavage efficiency.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.78</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="SSRNA GRNA BLOCKER" target="CAS12B">
      <data key="d7">SSRNA GRNA BLOCKER</data>
      <data key="d8">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d10">The functional role of the ssRNA gRNA blocker is defined in the context of Cas12b-based reactions, where it indirectly modulates Cas12b cis- and trans-cleavage activity by interfering with Cas12b–gRNA complex formation.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-POT RPA/CAS12A ASSAY" target="CAS12A">
      <data key="d7">TWO-POT RPA/CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">CAS12A</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-pot RPA/Cas12a assay uses Cas12a as the detection nuclease in a reaction separate from the RPA amplification step.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TWO-POT RPA/CAS12A ASSAY" target="RECOMBINASE POLYMERASE AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d7">TWO-POT RPA/CAS12A ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d8">RPA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">The two-pot RPA/Cas12a assay incorporates RPA as its nucleic acid amplification method prior to Cas12a-based detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="DIAGNOSTIC PERFORMANCE EVALUATION WITH 118 QPCR-POSITIVE AND 80 NEGATIVE SAMPLES" target="99% SENSITIVITY AND 100% SPECIFICITY">
      <data key="d7">DIAGNOSTIC PERFORMANCE EVALUATION WITH 118 QPCR-POSITIVE AND 80 NEGATIVE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d8">99% SENSITIVITY AND 100% SPECIFICITY</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_SPECIFICITY</data>
      <data key="d10">The diagnostic performance evaluation of the TRACE assay on 118 qPCR-positive and 80 negative samples yields 99% sensitivity and 100% specificity, summarizing the assay’s diagnostic accuracy in this study.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="MPXV">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">MPXV</data>
      <data key="d9">DETECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE biosensor platform is used to detect MPXV infection in clinical specimens from participants classified as MPXV or non-MPXV cases. | TRACE detects MPXV nucleic acid in patient specimens, including rash and saliva samples, with time-to-threshold (Tt) values ≤30 min for all TRACE-positive samples and high classification accuracy under the 18-min protocol. | By comparison to other one-pot CRISPR assays that detect MPXV, TRACE is positioned as a platform capable of detecting MPXV with higher analytical sensitivity. | TRACE is designed to detect MPXV nucleic acids in clinical specimens including rash fluid, oral and rectal swabs, saliva, blood, and urine.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.96</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="TIME-TO-THRESHOLD (TT) FOR POSITIVE SIGNAL">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">TIME-TO-THRESHOLD (TT) FOR POSITIVE SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE generates a measurable time-to-threshold (Tt) for positive signal in MPXV patient samples, used to determine the minimum time required to identify MPXV-infected individuals.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="POSITIVE SIGNAL IN MPXV PATIENT SAMPLES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">POSITIVE SIGNAL IN MPXV PATIENT SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">In MPXV patient samples, TRACE produces a positive signal when MPXV nucleic acid is present, and this signal is quantified via time-to-threshold analysis across a range of qPCR Ct values.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="11 MIN TIME-TO-THRESHOLD FOR 70% OF SAMPLES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">11 MIN TIME-TO-THRESHOLD FOR 70% OF SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The finding that 70% of MPXV-positive samples reach the TRACE positive signal threshold within 11 minutes supports validation of the assay’s rapid detection capability.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="RETROSPECTIVE STUDY OF 74 PARTICIPANTS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">RETROSPECTIVE STUDY OF 74 PARTICIPANTS</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE performance is evaluated in a retrospective cohort of 74 participants whose MPXV status was defined by qPCR, providing validation data on assay performance in stored clinical samples.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="REMAINING NUCLEIC ACID FROM THE QPCR ANALYSIS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">REMAINING NUCLEIC ACID FROM THE QPCR ANALYSIS</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE uses remaining nucleic acid from prior qPCR analysis as input material, indicating that nucleic acid extraction from clinical specimens is a prerequisite sample preparation step.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="CLINICAL SPECIMENS USED FOR TRACE-BASED ANALYSES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">CLINICAL SPECIMENS USED FOR TRACE-BASED ANALYSES</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE can be run on processed clinical specimens, indicating that specimen processing constitutes a sample preparation step feeding the assay.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="QPCR">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">QPCR</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE performance is benchmarked against qPCR, with TRACE reporter signals and Tt values showing strong negative correlation with qPCR Ct values (r = -0.8036, p &lt; 0.0001 for Ct 25–40), indicating concordant detection dynamics relative to the qPCR amplification method.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.78</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="REPORTER SIGNAL AT 18-MIN TRACE ENDPOINT">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">REPORTER SIGNAL AT 18-MIN TRACE ENDPOINT</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE platform produces a reporter signal measured at the 18-minute endpoint, which is used to classify samples as TRACE-positive and to support semi-quantitative estimation of MPXV viral load based on its correlation with qPCR Ct values.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="GUIDELINE FOR MPXV DETECTION">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">GUIDELINE FOR MPXV DETECTION</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE assay configuration, when run under the 18-min protocol, is evaluated against and shown to meet the guideline for MPXV detection by correctly identifying 95% of tested samples, thereby satisfying the specified regulatory performance criterion.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.86</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="CAS12B">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">CAS12B</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE uses Cas12b as its CRISPR effector nuclease to perform temperature-controlled trans-cleavage of reporter substrates after nucleic acid amplification, enabling sequence-specific detection. | TRACE employs Cas12b as its CRISPR effector nuclease within a Cas12b/gRNA ribonucleoprotein complex to mediate target-dependent reporter cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="GRNA BLOCKING SEQUENCE">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">GRNA BLOCKING SEQUENCE</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE incorporates a gRNA blocking sequence to modulate guide RNA activity, preventing Cas12b activation during the amplification phase and thereby temporally segregating amplification and trans-cleavage.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="RECOMBINASE POLYMERASE AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">RPA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE is designed to be compatible with RPA, leveraging its 37–42 °C operating range to perform nucleic acid amplification prior to Cas12b-mediated detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="TWO RPA ANALOGS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">TWO RPA ANALOGS</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE is experimentally shown to be compatible with two RPA analogs, which function similarly to RPA and allow flexible selection of amplification chemistry within the platform.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="ROLLING CIRCLE AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">ROLLING CIRCLE AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE can employ rolling circle amplification as an alternative isothermal amplification method, expanding the range of nucleic acid targets and assay designs.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="ENZYMATIC RECOMBINASE AMPLIFICATION (ERA)">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">ENZYMATIC RECOMBINASE AMPLIFICATION (ERA)</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">ERA is proposed as a compatible amplification method for TRACE due to its similar temperature range to RPA, enabling efficient target DNA amplification within the TRACE workflow.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="STRAND DISPLACEMENT AMPLIFICATION (SDA)">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">STRAND DISPLACEMENT AMPLIFICATION (SDA)</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">SDA is identified as a potential amplification method for TRACE, as it amplifies DNA efficiently at temperatures comparable to RPA, fitting the thermal constraints of the platform.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="NUCLEIC ACID SEQUENCE-BASED AMPLIFICATION ASSAYS (NASBA)">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">NUCLEIC ACID SEQUENCE-BASED AMPLIFICATION ASSAYS (NASBA)</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">NASBA is suggested as another amplification strategy that could be integrated into TRACE, leveraging its 37–42 °C operating range for efficient nucleic acid amplification.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="TWO-STEP CRISPR ASSAYS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">TWO-STEP RPA/CRISPR ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d9">OUTPERFORMS</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE achieves analytical sensitivity comparable to two-step RPA/CRISPR assays while offering a simpler, more integrated workflow, indicating performance parity with reduced complexity.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.75</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="ONE-POT CRISPR ASSAYS THAT DETECT MPXV">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">ONE-POT CRISPR ASSAYS THAT DETECT MPXV</data>
      <data key="d9">OUTPERFORMS</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE demonstrates greater analytical sensitivity than previously reported one-pot CRISPR assays that detect MPXV, indicating superior detection performance for monkeypox virus.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="GRNA PHOTOACTIVATION STRATEGIES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">GRNA PHOTOACTIVATION STRATEGIES</data>
      <data key="d9">OUTPERFORMS</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE is described as a simpler, less expensive, and more broadly applicable solution than reported gRNA photoactivation strategies used to induce Cas12a activity after amplification, indicating practical advantages in implementation.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="MONKEYPOX VIRUS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">MONKEYPOX VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d9">DETECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE is discussed in the context of CRISPR assays for monkeypox virus detection, implying its application to MPXV or similar viral targets, with sensitivity compared to MPXV-detecting assays.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.6</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="GRNA">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">GRNA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_GUIDE</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE uses a guide RNA paired with Cas12b to provide sequence-specific recognition of target nucleic acids, enabling specific activation of Cas12b.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="PHI29 AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">PHI29 AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE incorporates phi29-based isothermal amplification, using phi29 polymerase, buffer, dNTPs, and primers, to amplify target nucleic acids prior to or during CRISPR-based detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="LOD OF TRACE">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">LOD OF TRACE</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_LOD</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE has a defined limit of detection, specified as the lowest concentration of J2L or RNase P reference standards that yields a reporter signal above the positive threshold under optimal assay conditions.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="POSITIVE THRESHOLD OF TRACE">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">POSITIVE THRESHOLD OF TRACE</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_LOD</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE uses a positive threshold, defined as the mean negative-sample reporter signal plus three standard deviations, as part of its limit-of-detection determination and decision rule for positive calls.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="TRACE SPECIFICITY PROFILE">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">TRACE SPECIFICITY PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_SPECIFICITY</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE has an analytical specificity profile established by testing synthetic plasmids and extracted nucleic acids from multiple pathogens to evaluate cross-reactivity.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="HEAT INACTIVATION AT 56 °C FOR 30 MINUTES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">HEAT INACTIVATION AT 56 °C FOR 30 MINUTES</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE analysis is performed on clinical specimens that have undergone heat inactivation at 56 °C for 30 minutes as a standard pre-analytical safety and stabilization step.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="STORAGE AT -80 °C">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">STORAGE AT -80 °C</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE testing is conducted on specimens that have been stored at -80 °C after heat inactivation, ensuring preservation of nucleic acids until analysis.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="SEPARATION OF PLASMA WITHIN 2 H">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">SEPARATION OF PLASMA WITHIN 2 H</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">For blood samples, TRACE relies on plasma that has been separated within 2 hours of collection, defining the pre-analytical handling for this specimen type.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="BENCH ANALYTICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">BENCH ANALYTICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE is analytically validated through bench studies that determine limit of detection, detection stability, and specificity using serial dilutions of J2L and RNase P standards and pathogen panels.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="CLINICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE AT SHENZHEN THIRD PEOPLE’S HOSPITAL">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">CLINICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE AT SHENZHEN THIRD PEOPLE’S HOSPITAL</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE is clinically validated in retrospective and prospective studies at Shenzhen Third People’s Hospital using clinical samples from MPXV-infected, MPXV-excluded, and suspected MPXV cases.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE" target="TRACE REPORTER SIGNAL">
      <data key="d7">TRACE</data>
      <data key="d8">TRACE REPORTER SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">Upon successful target detection, TRACE produces a reporter signal whose magnitude is compared to the positive threshold to determine positive or negative results.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="MPXV">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">MPXV</data>
      <data key="d9">DETECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE LFA, the lateral-flow format of TRACE, is deployed on-site to detect MPXV in symptomatic individuals with epidemiological histories consistent with MPXV infection. | The TRACE LFA detects MPXV in clinical sample lysates, though it produced false negatives for three MPXV-positive samples with Ct values &gt; 33 in the evaluation. | TRACE LFA is used as a rapid diagnostic platform to detect MPXV infection status in symptomatic outpatients, using rash swab samples to distinguish MPXV-positive from non-MPXV cases. | TRACE LFA is configured to detect MPXV nucleic acids in clinical samples for rapid case identification. | The TRACE lateral-flow assay format detects MPXV in outpatient settings, enabling rapid on-site identification of MPXV cases. | The TRACE LFA format is used on original clinical samples from suspected MPXV cases, detecting MPXV targets via a lateral-flow readout.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.98</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="RETROSPECTIVE STUDY OF 74 PARTICIPANTS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">RETROSPECTIVE STUDY OF 74 PARTICIPANTS</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE LFA is tested on remaining nucleic acid and/or specimens from the 74 retrospectively studied participants, contributing to validation of its diagnostic performance against qPCR-defined MPXV status.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="PROSPECTIVE STUDY OF 28 SYMPTOMATIC INDIVIDUALS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">PROSPECTIVE STUDY OF 28 SYMPTOMATIC INDIVIDUALS</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE LFA is used on-site in a prospective cohort of 28 symptomatic individuals, validating its performance in real-time clinical screening against reference qPCR results.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="OFF-SITE CENTRAL LABORATORY QPCR TEST">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">OFF-SITE CENTRAL LABORATORY QPCR TEST</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">Results from the off-site central laboratory qPCR test on prospective samples serve as the reference against which the on-site TRACE LFA run is compared.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.75</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="ON-SITE TRACE LFA RUN ON PROSPECTIVE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">ON-SITE TRACE LFA RUN ON PROSPECTIVE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The on-site TRACE LFA run on prospectively collected samples provides empirical performance data for the TRACE LFA platform under real-world clinical conditions.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.75</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="REMAINING NUCLEIC ACID FROM THE QPCR ANALYSIS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">REMAINING NUCLEIC ACID FROM THE QPCR ANALYSIS</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE LFA can be run on remaining nucleic acid derived from qPCR analysis, showing that pre-extracted nucleic acid is an acceptable prepared input for this lateral-flow format.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.75</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="CLINICAL SPECIMENS USED FOR TRACE-BASED ANALYSES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">CLINICAL SPECIMENS USED FOR TRACE-BASED ANALYSES</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE LFA uses prepared clinical specimens as input material, reflecting the need for specimen handling and preparation before lateral-flow detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="SENSITIVITY 86% (95% CI, 65–97) FOR SAMPLES WITH CT ≥ 31">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">SENSITIVITY 86% (95% CI, 65–97) FOR SAMPLES WITH CT ≥ 31</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The performance of the TRACE LFA for higher-Ct MPXV-positive samples (Ct ≥ 31) is characterized by a validation analysis reporting 86% sensitivity with a 95% confidence interval of 65–97.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="SENSITIVITY 95% (95% CI, 85–97) FOR ALL MPXV-POSITIVE SAMPLES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">SENSITIVITY 95% (95% CI, 85–97) FOR ALL MPXV-POSITIVE SAMPLES</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The overall sensitivity of the TRACE LFA across all MPXV-positive samples is established by a validation analysis reporting 95% sensitivity with a 95% confidence interval of 85–97.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="SPECIFICITY 100% (95% CI, 92–100) FOR MPXV CLASSIFICATION">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">SPECIFICITY 100% (95% CI, 92–100) FOR MPXV CLASSIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_SPECIFICITY</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE LFA shows 100% specificity with a 95% confidence interval of 92–100 in the blinded evaluation of MPXV-positive and MPXV-negative clinical samples.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="BLINDED ANALYSIS OF 55 MPXV-POSITIVE AND 47 MPXV-NEGATIVE SAMPLE LYSATES">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">BLINDED ANALYSIS OF 55 MPXV-POSITIVE AND 47 MPXV-NEGATIVE SAMPLE LYSATES</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE LFA’s diagnostic performance for MPXV is evaluated in the same blinded analysis of 55 MPXV-positive and 47 MPXV-negative clinical sample lysates.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="QPCR ASSAY">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">QPCR ASSAY</data>
      <data key="d9">OUTPERFORMS</data>
      <data key="d10">In the described outpatient pilot study, TRACE LFA achieves a substantially faster sample-to-answer time (~30 minutes) compared with the central laboratory qPCR assay (~3 hours), while maintaining full concordance in classifying 11 MPXV and 17 non-MPXV cases, thus outperforming qPCR on turnaround time for point-of-care use.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="COMPREHENSIVE CLINICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE LFA">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">COMPREHENSIVE CLINICAL VALIDATION OF TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE LFA is reported as the only CRISPR-based MPXV assay supported by comprehensive clinical validation, confirming its diagnostic performance in clinical settings.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.96</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="RPA STAGE OF TRACE">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">RPA STAGE OF TRACE</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE LFA incorporates an RPA stage as its nucleic acid amplification step before or concurrent with CRISPR-based detection.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="RECOMBINASE POLYMERASE AMPLIFICATION">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">RPA</data>
      <data key="d9">USES_AMPLIFICATION</data>
      <data key="d10">The TRACE assay uses recombinase polymerase amplification (RPA) as its core isothermal amplification method at 37 °C.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="PREVIOUS CRISPR-BASED MPXV ASSAYS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">PREVIOUS CRISPR-BASED MPXV ASSAYS</data>
      <data key="d9">OUTPERFORMS</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE LFA is described as faster and more sensitive than most previously reported CRISPR-based MPXV assays.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.92</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="QPCR">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">QPCR</data>
      <data key="d9">OUTPERFORMS</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE LFA achieves a mean sample-to-answer time of 30 minutes compared to about 3 hours for qPCR in the study, indicating superior speed for MPXV case identification.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.88</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="LATERAL FLOW ASSAY STRIPS">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">LATERAL FLOW STRIPS</data>
      <data key="d9">PRODUCES_SIGNAL</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE LFA produces a visual signal on lateral flow strips, translating CRISPR-mediated cleavage into a colorimetric readout for point-of-care interpretation.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="TRACE LFA OUTPATIENT STUDY">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">TRACE LFA OUTPATIENT STUDY</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE LFA performance is established by a real-world outpatient study showing full agreement with qPCR and an 83% reduction in diagnostic turnaround time.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d14">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRACE LFA" target="MIXING WITH SAMPLE LYSIS BUFFER AT A 3:1 RATIO AND INCUBATION AT 80 °C FOR 5 MIN">
      <data key="d7">TRACE LFA</data>
      <data key="d8">MIXING WITH SAMPLE LYSIS BUFFER AT A 3:1 RATIO AND INCUBATION AT 80 °C FOR 5 MIN</data>
      <data key="d9">REQUIRES_PREP</data>
      <data key="d10">TRACE LFA uses original clinical samples that are first mixed with lysis buffer and incubated at 80 °C for 5 minutes, making this lysis step required for the assay.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6f94756d-fd42-4a77-b6b1-d9dc6901591d_chunk_48</data>
